</P>
<P>
	Banks Have Mixed Results  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- First Union Corp. today confirmed its earlier  
prediction of an earnings drop; and Fleet Financial Group Inc. said 
its profits rose 15 percent. First Union Corp.'s second-quarter net 
earnings fell 1 percent to $873 million, or 82 cents a share, from 
operating earnings of $883 million, or 92 cents a share, in the 
same period a year ago. The quarterly results were better than the 
Charlotte, N.C.-based bank forecast in May, and a penny over 
analysts' expectations. Fleet Financial Group Inc., based in 
Boston, reported a 15 percent jump in profits for the second 
quarter as fees rose and its brokerage unit posted strong results. 
The nation's eighth-largest banking company earned $450 million, or 
74 cents a share, beating Wall Street's expectations by a penny. 
That compares with earnings of $393 million, or 65 cents a share, 
in the second quarter last year. First Union shares were at 46 
13/16, up 1/8. Fleet shares were at 42 1/8, up 3/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Bank of America To Go Wireless  
</P>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Bank of America customers next year will  
be able to do their banking with mobile phones, electronic 
organizers and other handheld, Internet-connected, wireless 
devices. Charlotte-based Bank of America announced today a deal 
with Toronto-based 724 Solutions Inc. The technology company will 
provide software to let Bank of America's 30 million U.S. customers 
to accomplish banking transactions with wireless communication 
devices, including cellular phones, hand-held organizers and 
``smart phones,'' which are a hybrid of the two. Bank of America 
says it will be the first major U.S. financial institution to offer 
wireless banking. 

</P>
<P>
	IBM Pension Plan Under Scrutiny  
</P>
<P>
	MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) -- A controversial change in IBM's pension  
plan, which many employees complain robs older workers of benefits 
on which they had relied, is getting congressional scrutiny. Eleven 
members of Congress suggest that the company's pension changes 
amount to age discrimination and they asked the Internal Revenue 
Service this week to look into it. Although they are seeking review 
of all ``cash balance plans,'' the congressmen were prompted by the 
changes at IBM, which took effect July 1. 

</P>
<P>
	Cable TV Boosts Time Warner Profit  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Time Warner today posted net earnings of $593  
million in the second quarter as a large gain from cable television 
deals boosted profits. The earnings, which were equivalent to 43 
cents per share, compared to net profits of $101 million, or 2 
cents a share, in the same period a year ago. Revenues slipped to 
$3.57 billion from $3.67 billion. Time Warner's net figures for the 
second quarter reflected several one-time gains, mainly a $771 
million profit from various sales and exchanges of cable television 
properties. 

</P>
<P>
	AlliedSignal Earnings Up 13 Pct  
</P>
<P>
	MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) -- Sweeping reorganization, cost  
cutting and shifts to some higher-profit products helped 
AlliedSignal Inc. post a 13 percent jump in second-quarter 
earnings. Income from continuing operations was up 12 percent, on 
sharply higher profits in the aerospace systems, turbine 
technologies and transportation products divisions within 
AlliedSignal, which is awaiting shareholder approval of its planned 
merger with Honeywell Inc. AlliedSignal, which also makes 
automotive products, chemicals and advanced materials, reported net 
income for the April-June quarter totaling $395 million, or 70 
cents per share, matching estimates from analysts surveyed by First 
Call. In the year-ago period, AlliedSignal earned $350 million, or 
61 cents per share. AlliedSignal shares were at 66 1/4, up 1/4. 

</P>
<P>
	Wholesale Prices Fall 0.1 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Prices at the wholesale level unexpectedly  
declined last month while consumers' spending slowed dramatically. 
With more news like this, the Federal Reserve may be content to 
remain on the sidelines and not push interest rates higher this 
year, economists said. The 0.1 percent decline in the Producer 
Price Index -- which measures inflation pressures before they reach 
the consumer -- was the first decline in four months and reflected a 
dip in energy prices, the Labor Department said today. And, the 
tiny 0.1 percent June increase in retail sales, which accounts for 
one-third of total economic activity, followed a hefty 1.2 percent 
gain in sales in May, the Commerce Department said in a separate 
report. A one percent drop in sales of cars and trucks, the biggest 
decline in this area since March, was the main factor slowing 
overall retail sales in June. 

</P>
<P>
	Microsoft-Bristol Case Goes to Jury  
</P>
<P>
	BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- A jury began deliberations today over  
whether Microsoft Corp. violated antitrust laws in its dealings 
with a small Danbury, Conn. software company. Bristol Technology 
Inc. makes a product called Wind/U, which allows programs, such as 
word processors and spreadsheets, written to work with Windows to 
be converted to run on computers with different operating systems 
such as Unix. The two companies had a three-year contract in which 
Microsoft gave Bristol access to source code -- software blueprints 
-- it needed to create Wind/U. Bristol sued in August after being 
unable to reach an agreement with Microsoft for a new contract for 
the latest versions of the Windows NT operating system. Bristol is 
making anti-trust claims against Microsoft, including a claim that 
Microsoft refused to negotiate a new contract. 

</P>
<P>
	Sikorsky To Cut 1,100 Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Helicopter maker Sikorsky Aircraft Corp.  
plans to cut 1,100 jobs in Connecticut, citing a need to reduce 
overhead and become more competitive in a global marketplace. The 
company also said today that it plans to close some of its 10 
plants in the state, but company spokesman William Tuttle would not 
identify the factories targeted for closure. All but about 1,000 of 
Sikorsky's 8,100 employees are in Connecticut. The company also has 
plants in West Palm Beach, Fla., Troy, Ala., and smaller facilities 
around the world. None of the plants outside Connecticut will be 
affected by the cuts, Tuttle said. 

</P>
