<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Takes Jab at Bush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- President Clinton mocked Texas Gov. George W.  
Bush on Wednesday for calling himself a ``compassionate 
conservative,'' saying the term applies to Republicans who intend 
to do nothing in office -- except be nice about it. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking at a ``national conversation'' convened by the  
Democratic Leadership Council, Clinton said Republicans have 
latched onto compassionate conversatism because it implies a sense 
of social responsibility. But at the same time, he said, they are 
rejecting socially responsible policies, such as using the federal 
budget surplus to bail out Social Security and Medicare, 
restricting criminals' access to guns and raising the minimum wage. 
</P>
<P>
	``This compassionate conservatism has a great ring to it, you  
know,'' Clinton said. ``It sounds so good. And near as I can tell, 
here's what it means: It means, 'I like you. I do.' ... 
</P>
<P>
	``And I'd like not to squander the surplus and, you know, save  
Social Security and Medicare for the next generation. I'd like to 
raise the minimum wage. I'd like to do these things. But I just 
can't, and I feel terrible about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd laughed uproariously at Clinton's remarks, and he  
quipped: ``You don't have to give me credit if you repeat that back 
home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By coincidence, Bush also was in Baltimore, visiting a poor  
inner city neighborhood and later attending a fund-raiser expected 
to net $400,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The president followed the lead of California Lt. Gov. Cruz  
Bustamante, who -- without directly referring to Bush-- criticized 
compassionate conservatism as a rehash of failed GOP policies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people think if you put a nice word in front of a mean  
word, you can fool people,'' Bustamante said. ``What a travesty it 
would be if the next president were the heir apparent to voodoo 
economics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In praising Bustamante, Clinton seized the chance to deliver an  
intended pun. 
</P>
<P>
	``One thing I like about the California lieutenant governor is  
he doesn't beat around the bush,'' Clinton said, laughing. ``You 
know what's on his mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And he hesitated before launching into his criticism of Bush,  
saying ``I shouldn't do this, because it's not really presidential, 
but I'm going to do it anyway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton spoke shortly after the White House announced that the  
president would take to the road to help Vice President Al Gore 
raise funds for his Democratic presidential bid. Gore trails both 
Bush and his main Democratic opponent, Bill Bradley, in raising 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton told the crowd of mostly moderate Democrats they should  
feel proud that Republicans are adopting some of their centrist 
``third way'' ideology, even if they are using it on the opposite 
end of the political spectrum. 
</P>
<P>
	``The third way has become the way of the future,'' Clinton  
said. ``We tried it their way. We tried it our way. I don't care if 
the election is next week, never mind next year, we have worked too 
long to get this country out of the hole, we are moving in the 
right direction and we must not compromise the future of America 
and the next generation just for the next election.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also announced a national drive to sign up low-income  
working families for food stamp benefits. He said he wanted to 
``make sure that working people know there is no indignity in 
taking public assistance to help feed their children if they're out 
there working 40 hours a week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president also relaxed rules to allow low-income families  
receiving government assistance for child care or other needs to 
also qualify for food stamps even if they own a car worth $4,650 or 
more. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
