<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *Donald Engen    	
</P>
<P>
	MINDEN, Nev. (AP) -- Donald Engen, the head of the Smithsonian  
Institution's National Air and Space Museum, died Tuesday when his 
glider broke apart and crashed. He was 75. 
</P>
<P>
	Engen was killed along with William Ivans, an internationally  
known pilot who was piloting the motorized glider. The cause of the 
crash was under investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Engen, of Arlington, Va., had been director of the Air and Space  
Museum in Washington since 1996. He also was administrator of the 
Federal Aviation Administration from 1984 to 1987, and earlier 
served for two years on the National Transportation Safety Board. 
</P>
<P>
	A much-decorated Navy pilot, Engen retired as a vice admiral in  
1978. He also was a test pilot for many years and had served as 
general manager of Piper Aircraft Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	He took over as head of the Air and Space Museum after his  
predecessor, Martin Harwit, resigned in 1995. Harwit left amid 
criticism that a planned atomic bomb exhibit would have depicted 
the United States as the aggressor and Japan as the victim of World 
War II. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Benjamin J. Gingiss    	
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Benjamin J. Gingiss, who founded a tuxedo shop in  
Chicago that grew into a large national chain, died Saturday of 
complications from cancer. He was 88. 
</P>
<P>
	Gingiss started a one-store operation in downtown Chicago with  
his brothers in 1936 after they struggled to find decent tuxedos to 
wear to their sister's wedding. The shop became a franchise, 
Gingiss Formalwear, with about 300 locations. 
</P>
<P>
	Gingiss was also president of the Illinois Humane Society, and a  
board member of Rosary College and the Lyric Opera. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Everett Greenbaum    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Everett Greenbaum, who collaborated with  
fellow writer Jim Fritzell on the 1950s television sitcom ``Mr. 
Peepers'' and other series including ``The Andy Griffith Show'' and 
``M-A-S-H,'' died Sunday of brain cancer. He was 79. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenbaum, a native of Buffalo, N.Y., studied at the  
Massachusetts Institute of Technology and the Sorbonne in Paris, 
and served in World War II as a Navy pilot. 
</P>
<P>
	After the war, he wrote, produced and starred in a Boston radio  
show called ``Greenbaum's Gallery.'' Greenbaum and Fritzell teamed 
up in 1952 for Wally Cox's ``Mr. Peepers,'' a collaboration that 
continued until Fritzell's death in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	The pair earned a Peabody Award, four Emmy nominations, three  
Writers Guild comedy awards and the Paddy Chayefsky Laurel Award. 
They wrote eight feature films, including ``Good Neighbor Sam'' and 
``The Shakiest Gun in the West.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On his own, Greenbaum wrote two books, including the memoir  
``The Goldenberg Who Couldn't Dance,'' and worked on ``The George 
Gobel Show.'' He also appeared in brief roles on Griffith's 
``Matlock'' series and other programs. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Clarence L. Harris    	
</P>
<P>
	GREENSBORO (AP) -- Clarence L. ``Curly'' Harris, manager of the  
Greensboro F.W. Woolworth Store lunch counter where the sit-in 
movement for civil rights caught fire, died Monday. He was 94. 
</P>
<P>
	It was at Harris' downtown diner where, on Feb. 1, 1960, four  
students from North Carolina A&AMP;T State University refused to leave 
the segregated lunch counter after being refused service. 
</P>
<P>
	The protest lasted nearly six months and shut down one of the  
busiest lunch counters in the Woolworth chain. Black students in 
other cities drew inspiration from the protests to begin similar 
sit-ins. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was on their side,'' he said. His objection, he said, was in  
never having been consulted before his business came under siege by 
the burgeoning movement. 
</P>
<P>
	Over time, the all-day sit-ins left his business hemorrhaging  
money, Harris said. Still, he continued paying his lunch counter 
and kitchen staffers, which included 13 black people, during the 
protest. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Henry Kimbro    	
</P>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Henry Kimbro, a Negro League outfielder  
known as the ``black Ty Cobb,'' died Sunday. He was 88. 
</P>
<P>
	Kimbro batted .320 over 18 seasons. He played from 1934 to 1951  
for the Nashville Elite Giants, the Washington Elite Giants, the 
New York Black Yankees, the Baltimore Elite Giants and the 
Birmingham Black Barons. He hit .393 for Baltimore in 1946. 

</P>
<P>
                           *James Newman    	
</P>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- James ``Jimmy'' Newman, the son and manager of  
singer Gladys Knight, died Saturday. He was 36. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of death was not released. The coroner said it appears  
that Newman died of natural causes. An autopsy was pending. 
</P>
<P>
	Newman managed his mother's career through his Newman Management  
Inc., one of four Knight-related companies sharing offices in 
Southern Nevada. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Newman helped his mother launch Many Roads, a  
specialty record label formed to support her recent gospel album, 
``Many Different Roads,'' and other gospel artists. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the album's media materials, Newman brought many of  
the songs to Knight's attention, including ``Jesus' Love Is Like a 
River,'' a song co-written by Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch. 

</P>
<P>
                             *Leon Romo    	
</P>
<P>
	ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) -- Leon ``Red'' Romo, a trainer who spent 41  
years at the Naval Academy and worked with such athletes as Roger 
Staubach and David Robinson, died Sunday of complications from a 
stroke. He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	Romo was the Navy's trainer from 1956 until his retirement in  
1997. He was popular with athletes and top brass at the academy, 
where he was known for his sharp wit. 
</P>
<P>
	He worked primarily with football, basketball and baseball  
teams, but also spent time with crew and lacrosse. He supervised 
all four of Navy's athletic training rooms and the training staff 
for the 30 intercollegiate sports at the academy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
