<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles Owner Apologizes for Belle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- A Baltimore Orioles fan who sent a written  
protest to team owner Peter Angelos about outfielder Albert Belle's 
on-the-field antics was invited to sit in Angelos' box at Camden 
Yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Angelos also apologized to Norm D. St. Landau, of University  
Park, who faxed his letter to the Orioles detailing lewd gestures 
he said Belle made to fans during a June 4 game at Camden Yards 
against the Philadelphia Phillies. 
</P>
<P>
	St. Landau said Belle gestured to fans in the bleachers with his  
middle finger and made other lewd displays after he was heckled for 
his slow chase of a fly ball. 
</P>
<P>
	The season-ticket holder faxed his complaint to Angelos on June  
9, and within days received an invitation to watch the Orioles' 
June 22 game against the Boston Red Sox from the owner's box. 
Ironically, Belle won the game with a three-run homer. 
</P>
<P>
	Belle also ran afoul of team management after he shattered a  
clubhouse TV following a loss at Tropicana Field on April 21 and a 
shouting match with manager Ray Miller on June 9. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Foss, the Orioles chief operating officer, said this was  
``really the first time I was aware of any of Albert's actions 
being directed at our fans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When an athlete is angry after a game or breaks a TV, ``Those  
are internal matters club officials deal with,'' Foss said. 
</P>
<P>
	Foss said the gesturing matter will be handled internally.  
</P>
<P>
	St. Landau's sister-in-law is Signe Wilkinson, Pulitzer  
Prize-winning editorial cartoonist for the Philadelphia Daily News. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilkinson sketched Belle's pose and eventually submitted it for  
publication in last Friday's editions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
