<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SLOC Buys Winter Sports Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The Salt Lake Organizing Committee took  
over Olympic venues for ski jumping, bobsledding and speed skating 
on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal requires SLOC to reimburse Utah taxpayers $59 million  
for building the Utah Winter Sports Park near Park City and a 
speed-skating oval at the Oquirrh Park Fitness Center in Kearns, a 
Salt Lake City suburb. 
</P>
<P>
	It means the park and skating oval will remain open to athletes  
and the public before and after the 2002 Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	SLOC already made a $1 million down payment on the purchase. The  
balance is due in January. Next March, SLOC must pay $40 million 
into a Legacy Fund to support the Olympic facilities, supposedly 
forever. 
</P>
<P>
	Utah taxpayers still could be left holding a bag after the 2002  
Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Interest from the Legacy Fund will fall short of running the  
sports park and skating oval, said Randy Dryer, chairman of the 
Utah Sports Authority, the state agency that built the venues. 
</P>
<P>
	The venues will need an operating subsidy of $500,000 to $1  
million a year, Dryer told the Legislature's Sports Advisory 
Committee Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Don't ask us for the money, legislators replied.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think that's up to the private sector,'' committee chairman  
Jordan Tanner of Provo said. 
</P>
<P>
	Utah officials are determined to run an Olympics without  
government subsidies, but taxpayers are vulnerable. 
</P>
<P>
	Salt Lake City, the official host, had to guarantee the Olympics  
against any financial losses, and the state agreed to indemnify the 
city. 
</P>
<P>
	SLOC, for its part, agreed years ago to reimburse $59 million  
that state and local taxpayers invested to build the sports park 
and skating oval. A sales tax diversion raised the money in 10 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though SLOC is buying the Olympic venues, it won't get to  
keep or sell them. The venues eventually will be turned over 
debt-free to the Utah Athletic Foundation, a nonprofit organization 
that will use the Legacy Fund to run the facilities after the 
games. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
