<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Manager of Protest Counter Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) -- Clarence L. ``Curly'' Harris, manager of  
the city's Woolworth's lunch counter where the civil rights sit-in 
movement was born, has died. He was 94. 
</P>
<P>
	It was at Harris' downtown diner where, on Feb. 1, 1960, four  
students from North Carolina A&AMP;T State University refused to leave 
the segregated lunch counter after being refused service. 
</P>
<P>
	For nearly six months, hundreds of other area college students  
followed suit, shutting down one of the busiest counters in the 
chain. In the end, the counter was integrated and black students in 
other cities drew inspiration to begin similar protests. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 1998 interview, Harris said he saw no heroism in the four  
students' initial defiance, saying they could have taken 
Woolworth's to court instead. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was on their side,'' he said. His objection, he said, was in  
never having been consulted before his business came under siege by 
the burgeoning movement. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we could have worked something out,'' Harris said.  
</P>
<P>
	McArthur Davis, the leader of a nonprofit effort to preserve the  
old store as a civil rights museum, said Harris' reluctance to have 
the students arrested for trespassing had an unintended effect. 
</P>
<P>
	``He thought by not having the students arrested, it would fail  
to gain publicity and the effort would die,'' Davis said. ``That in 
and of itself helped the movement spread.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Over time, the all-day sit-ins left his business hemorrhaging  
money, Harris said. 
</P>
<P>
	The protests ``cost me $150,000 in lost business,'' he said.  
``Wound up I lost one-third of my profits and I lost one-third of 
my salary. I resented it because I got no help from my company, I 
got no help from the city, I got no help from anybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet Harris continued paying his lunch counter and kitchen staff  
members, 13 of whom were black. 
</P>
<P>
	Geneva Tisdale, a black woman who worked at the South Elm Street  
store from 1951 until it closed in early 1994, recalled Harris 
fondly. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was always nice to me,'' she said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
