<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alaskan Port Tops in Fish Landings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Alaskan port of Dutch Harbor-Unalaska  
topped the nation in fish landings last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Commercial fishermen brought the port 597.1 million pounds of  
fish, worth $110.0 million in 1998 -- making it the port with both 
the highest volume and greatest dollar value of fish landings in 
the country, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration 
announced today. 
</P>
<P>
	NOAA's National Marine Fisheries Service said Dutch  
Harbor-Unalaska netted the top landings slot for the 11th straight 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The second-ranked port for landings was Reedville, Va., at 509.0  
million pounds; followed by Kodiak, Alaska, 357.6 million; 
Empire-Venice, La., 328.0 million; and Seattle, 312.8 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Ranking second in the value of its landings was New Bedford,  
Mass., at $93.5 million; followed by Kodiak, $78.7 million; 
Brownsville-Port Isabel, Texas, $64.2; and Honolulu, $49.0 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
