<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Hogan's Alley' Is the Unfair-way  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARNOUSTIE, Scotland (AP) -- ``Hogan's Alley'' is a bad  
neighborhood. And now the alley's even tougher. 
</P>
<P>
	The nasty, narrow strip down the par-5, sixth fairway is named  
for Ben Hogan, who in 1953 won the British Open at Carnoustie. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hogan's day, two pot bunkers about 265 yards off the tee  
ruined the ideal line to the green. There were two choices: thread 
the ball through a 25-yard gap between the bunkers and an 
out-of-bounds fence, or play safe to the right, which made getting 
near the green in 2 impossible. 
</P>
<P>
	Now there's a third bunker -- 310 yards off the tee -- dug there  
six months ago in Hogan's honor by head greenskeeper John Philp and 
deputy Paul O'Connor. 
</P>
<P>
	Carnoustie is a 7,361-yard links course and might be the  
toughest test in golf. So O'Connor thinks it merits ``a rough, 
tough alley.'' 
</P>
<P>
	O'Connor, a 32-year-old Irishman, has spent nine years helping  
restore a course that fell into disrepair after Tom Watson won the 
last British Open there 24 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The others on the exclusive list of Open winners at Carnoustie  
include Tommy Armour (1931), Sir Henry Cotton ('37) and Gary Player 
('68). 
</P>
<P>
	``The bunker is there to protect some of the Hogan mystique and  
to guarantee the integrity of the hole,'' said O'Connor, who 
suggested the change to the Royal and Ancient Golf Club, which 
oversees golf everywhere but the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the power the players have now and the equipment, flying  
the first two bunkers was too easy,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Flying all three is impossible, even on a rare calm day. Even  
for Tiger Woods. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods played the Scottish Open on this course in 1995 and '96  
and was able to clear the two at will. But not now. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even if the wind was into me, I still was able to carry those  
bunkers, that's always a nice advantage to have,'' O'Connor said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have made the pros think, and we've hurt their egos a  
little,'' he added. ``It makes them choose their weapons and armor 
carefully.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sixth plays due west into a prevailing southwest wind with a  
knee-high meadow of grass narrowing the 578-yard hole to 14 yards 
at one point -- the narrowest on the course. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's not the width of a room,'' U.S. Open champion Payne  
Stewart said during practice for Thursday's first round. 
</P>
<P>
	When Hogan played this course his one time he arrived two weeks  
early to practice meticulously. He often angered Scots with his 
cutting comments about the course and the modest accommodations in 
this small speck of a town on the rugged North Sea coast. 
</P>
<P>
	``Send back to Texas for my lawnmower,'' he is reported to have  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some stories have him walking the course backward to see every  
hill and gully. 
</P>
<P>
	His final two rounds to win in 1953 were played on the same day.  
He shot 70 and a then course-record 68, played in a cold, driving 
rain that forced him to take penicillin for a high fever. 
</P>
<P>
	That was his ninth major, and his last to go with the U.S. Open  
and Masters titles the same year. His performance won him the 
respect of Scots, who dubbed him the ``Wee Ice Mon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hogan is everywhere in Carnoustie, where he promised to return  
and never did. 
</P>
<P>
	The new 80-room hotel just off the 18th green has a Hogan Suite  
with a balcony overlooking the sea and the course. Down the road is 
the Hogan House Hotel, a modest bed and breakfast. 
</P>
<P>
	It's disputed whether Hogan played all four of his tee shots on  
No. 6 down the alley or just the final two. According to one tale 
O'Connor likes, Hogan never ``took a divot on his second shot on 
No. 6, so he could land the ball in that same spot every day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's also unclear if the new bunker, having done it's work, will  
stay. 
</P>
<P>
	The Royal and Ancient paid for it and, faced with complaints  
from Carnoustie members, might remove it after the Open. Philp, the 
head greenskeeper, hopes not. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just want it to influence the championship in some way,'' he  
said. ``I want the challenge of `Hogan's Alley' to be as strong now 
as it always has been and ever was.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
