<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Most Asian Markets Tumble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian markets tumbled Wednesday amid  
growing political tension between Taiwan and China, concerns that 
China might devalue its currency, and fears of higher interest 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo, Asia's biggest market, bucked the trend and posted a  
gain. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, share prices plunged to their lowest level in four  
weeks. The blue-chip Hang Seng Index tumbled 2.9 percent, or 405.36 
points, to 13,575.57. The Hang Seng fell 80.91 points, or 0.6 
percent, on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Taiwan, the Weighted Price Index plunged 315.84 points, or  
3.84 percent, to 7,888.66, in the second largest drop this year. 
The index had already fallen 3.06 percent on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In South Korea, the Kospi index plummeted 3.4 percent, or 33.83  
points, to close at 953.67. Concerns over a domestic interest rate 
hike accelerated the fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were dumping shares amid the latest standoff between  
Taiwan and China, sparked by Taiwan President Lee Tung-hui's recent 
remarks that bilateral relations should be conducted on a 
``state-to-state'' basis. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee infuriated Beijing, which maintains that Taiwan and China  
are two separate political entities within a single state and 
warned Taiwan of dire consequences for ``playing with fire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some investors also worried that China might devalue its  
currency, the yuan, after China's central bank governor, Dai 
Xianglong, commented that its value should be determined by market 
forces rather than administrative policy. 
</P>
<P>
	A yuan devaluation could deal regional currency and stock  
markets a heavy blow. 
</P>
<P>
	But in Tokyo, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 176.77  
points, or 0.97 percent, to 18,357.86. On Tuesday, the Nikkei had 
lost 0.42 points, or 0.03 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese investors were cheered by continued gains in high  
technology companies reliant on international sales. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the U.S. dollar fell against the Japanese  
yen. The dollar bought 121.12 yen in late trading, down from 122.14 
yen late Tuesday in Tokyo and below its late New York level of 
121.32 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, shares in Manila and Sydney also fell as investors  
remained worried ahead of the release of key U.S. inflation data, 
which analysts said would provide hints on whether the U.S. Federal 
Reserve might increase interest rates again. 
</P>
<P>
	The Philippine Stock Exchange Index fell 33.53 points, or 1.3  
percent, to 2,570.96. Sydney's All Ordinaries Index closed down 9.5 
points, or 0.3 percent, to 3,054.4. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai shares fell as investors sold banking and finance  
shares heavily ahead of the release of second-quarter results from 
financial institutions, due on July 21. The SET index hit a 
five-week low of 494.00 points, down 1.2 percent, or 6.25 points. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares rose as sentiment improved after  
President B.J. Habibie said he would step aside for his rival, 
Megawati Sukarnoputri, if she wins the presidency. The JSX 
Composite Index rallied 1.3 percent, or 8.695 points, to 664.882. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares rose, even though some brokerages  
are making investors put up more cash to invest in the market. The 
Composite Index closed at 851.21 points, up 9.20 points, or 1.1 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares closed flat, with a late sell-off on Taiwan  
concerns erasing strong gains by media company Singapore Press 
Holdings Ltd., which hit a record high on growing optimism on the 
country's economy. The Straits Times Index rose just 0.14 point, or 
0.06 percent, to 2,178.63. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand stocks fell slightly despite solid gains  
made by Fletcher Challenge's energy and paper division on group 
restructuring. The NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 4.52 points, or 0.2 
percent, to 2,169.55. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
