<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4:30 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	New Drug Protects Newborns from AIDS  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Scientists working in Uganda have discovered a  
dramatically more effective way to prevent pregnant women from 
spreading the AIDS virus to their babies: a drug treatment that 
costs just $4 per mother and could save up to 1,000 newborns a day. 
The drug nevirapine already is widely sold around the world to 
treat AIDS. But the new study found it is 47 percent more effective 
than the therapy now recommended in developing countries for 
preventing mother-to-baby transmission of the AIDS virus. 

</P>
<P>
	Carnival Crew Accused of Sex Assault  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Carnival Cruise Lines reportedly has disclosed  
that its crew members were accused of sexual assault 62 times in a 
five-year span ending last summer -- or just about once per month. 
The number, included in court papers filed yesterday in Miami, is 
the first such public disclosure by a cruise line, The New York 
Times reported today. Such ships are often registered abroad and 
safety figures aren't reported to U.S. authorities. Carnival, the 
world's largest cruise company, said the alleged attacks involved 
passengers and employees. 

</P>
<P>
	Taiwan Leader Denies Policy Change  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- After sparking an uproar by insisting  
Beijing deal with Taiwan ``state-to-state'' and not as part of 
China, President Lee Teng-hui told Washington today he's not 
seeking formal independence that could prompt China to go to war. 
As Beijing kept up its verbal attacks, the Taiwanese president said 
his new definition of the delicate Taiwan-China relationship merely 
clarifies the political reality that has emerged 50 years after the 
island separated from China when the communists gained control of 
the mainland. 

</P>
<P>
	Railway Suspect Admits Burglary  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- The man arrested in the railroad killer case  
appeared eager to cooperate with authorities in Texas, twice 
admitting he committed burglary in one of the slayings. But the 
burglary charge could open Angel Maturino Resendez to the death 
penalty for the killing. Police said today they have evidence 
linking Maturino Resendez, a suspect in eight killings in three 
states, to a ninth murder. Maturino Resendez surrendered yesterday, 
ending a six-week manhunt. 

</P>
<P>
	Kasich Pulls Out; Backs Bush  
</P>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Rep. John Kasich, a longshot for the  
Republican presidential nomination, threw in the towel today and 
tossed his support to former opponent George W. Bush. ``I feel as 
though I have a soul brother,'' he said. The nine-term Ohio 
congressman also said he would not seek re-election. Kasich became 
the second candidate in two days to announce his withdrawal from 
consideration for the Republican nomination for president. New 
Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith said yesterday he was quitting the party 
and running for president as an independent. 

</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com Buys Into Gear.com  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Amazon.com, the world's largest online book  
retailer, is taking another step toward its goal of being a huge 
online shopping hub. Amazon.com announced today it has bought a 49 
percent stake in Gear.com, an online discount sporting-goods 
retailer. The announcement came one day after Amazon.com began 
selling toys and electronics on its Web site. The online superstore 
has already invested millions of dollars in online pharmacy 
drugstore.com, Internet pet shop Pets.com, and cyber supermarket 
HomeGrocer.com. 

</P>
<P>
	New Element on Periodic Table  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Russian physicists have created a new,  
super-heavy element that lasted a surprisingly long 30 seconds 
before disintegrating -- long-sought proof, they say, of the 
existence of an ``island of stability.'' Using an atom smasher to 
bombard plutonium with calcium ions, the physicists created an 
element with an atomic weight of 114. The newest addition to the 
periodic table has yet to be named. 

</P>
<P>
	Nasdaq Hits Record; Dow Down 26.92  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index reached a new closing  
high today amid a rally in technology stocks that was spurred by a 
tame inflation report and a strong earnings outlook from computer 
chip maker Intel. The Dow Jones industrial average, meanwhile, 
ended down 26.92 at 11,148.10. Advancing issues on the New York 
Stock Exchange led declines 1,532-1,397. The Nasdaq rose 39.14 to 
2,817.37. 

</P>
<P>
	Lemieux May Miss Court Deadline  
</P>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Mario Lemieux reportedly may miss Friday's  
court-imposed deadline to put together a $50 million offer to buy 
the Pittsburgh Penguins as he wrangles over terms with one key 
investor in his proposal. Lemieux's lawyers were expected to ask 
the judge for an extension on the deadline, believing that the 
delay is only needed to work out some details, the Tribune-Review 
of Pittsburgh reported today. The move is not expected to threaten 
the Hall of Fame player's purchase of the team, the newspaper said. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  





  	   	
