<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady Gets Rock Star Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WANTAGH, N.Y. (AP) -- Retirees Ruth and Hal Sackstein raced for  
Jones Beach in pants and long-sleeved shirts when the radio relayed 
the news: Hillary Rodham Clinton was on Long Island, chatting up 
sun-seekers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never got out of the house so fast,'' said Mrs. Sackstein of  
New York City's Queens borough. ``We would not miss seeing her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the first lady was greeted like a rock star at the  
popular beach Tuesday as a crowd of several hundred people gathered 
to shake hands and snap pictures. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, who has established an exploratory committee for a  
likely Senate campaign, began making visits through the state last 
week in what she has described as a ``listening tour.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She was to return to Long Island today for a forum on gun  
control and a discussion on health issues in Great Neck. 
</P>
<P>
	New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a Republican, has also  
established an exploratory committee for a possible Senate run. He 
has criticized Mrs. Clinton's interest in the state as 
carpetbagging. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton told reporters she had not decided yet where in the  
state she might live, but has looked over a few houses and received 
brochures and videos on others. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I can afford it, I'd buy,'' she said, ``but I probably will  
end up renting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Melanie Antonelli, a hair salon owner from upstate Cornwall  
visiting the beach, said she is a Republican but would vote for 
Mrs. Clinton anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need more women in politics,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton began her day at Westchester Community College in  
Valhalla at a forum with with former welfare recipients who now 
have jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I support welfare reform,'' she said. ``I believe we needed to  
make those changes, but it can only work if we have child care, 
support and other necessities that people need to move on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rebecca Hodges, a once-homeless, single mother who now works at  
a center for AIDS patients after getting a child care grant, said 
she worries about losing the grant and appreciated Mrs. Clinton's 
interest. 
</P>
<P>
	``It showed me she was concerned,'' Miss Hodges said. ``She  
really was listening. She was very friendly, very open to 
suggestion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not everyone was impressed.  
</P>
<P>
	``She spoke in generalities. I wouldn't think Giuliani would  
have any problem agreeing with any of it,'' said Sarah Stern, a 
Republican. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton also expressed support for universal  
pre-kindergarten, which New York state has declined to fund; for 
making college tuition tax-deductible; and for a federal initiative 
to pay for school construction that the White House has backed but 
Congress has not. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have a lot of old schools and a lot of fast-growing  
suburbs,'' she said. ``It's not just an inner-city problem, it's 
also a suburban -- and as I learned last week -- a rural problem as 
well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, another potential Senate candidate, Rick Lazio, a  
Long Island congressman, said several Senate GOP leaders, Senate 
Majority Leader Trent Lott among them, would be holding a 
Washington fund-raiser for him. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
