<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Release Rollover Test Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a step toward vehicle rollover ratings,  
federal safety regulators on Wednesday released track test results 
on 12 vehicles -- including one that nearly tipped over. 
</P>
<P>
	A computer is being used to steer the vehicles through sharp  
turns so officials were able to reliably repeat the maneuvers, a 
report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration plans to  
propose a federal test later this year to provide consumers with 
information on the relative likelihood of rollover for cars and 
light trucks -- pickups, sport utility vehicles and vans, agency 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	A compact pickup, the 1997 Ranger, tipped so far to the side  
during two tests that it was caught by the metal outriggers on its 
sides that are designed to prevent it from rolling over and hurting 
the driver, the agency report said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If no outriggers were present, the vehicle might well have  
rolled over,'' the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Highway crash data shows that pickups and sport-utility  
vehicles, which have a higher center of gravity, roll over more 
than cars. But developing a test to assess rollover propensity has 
long been controversial among automakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer groups applauded the agency's testing, saying  
development of a rating system is even more important now since 
light truck sales have grown rapidly this decade to nearly half of 
auto sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a hopeful sign that NHTSA will move decisively to help  
reduce death and injuries from rollover,'' said R. David Pittle, 
the technical director for Consumers Union, publisher of Consumer 
Reports. ``A rating system for consumers will be a major step 
forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The group had petitioned the agency to develop such a rollover  
test. 
</P>
<P>
	The safety agency tested the 12 vehicles in severe driving  
maneuvers using the computer to execute turns at speeds up to 60 
mph. The two main tests involved a sharp turn in one direction 
followed by an even larger turn in the opposite direction, and a 
single large turn similar to getting on a cloverleaf ramp. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ranger and a mid-size sport utility vehicle, the 1998  
Chevrolet Tracker, also had moderate tipping in a single turn test 
that involved some braking by the driver. A moderate tilt meant the 
vehicle tipped up on two wheels by more than 2 inches. Each of the 
vehicles has two moderate tilts on that test. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal test researchers cautioned against comparing the vehicle  
test results to draw conclusions about any individual vehicle since 
so few vehicles have been tested and officials were still deciding 
on the best test. 
</P>
<P>
	``The results cannot be used to draw meaningful comparisons  
about the stability of specific models,'' an agency statement said. 
However, the report did say the Ranger ``exhibited the highest 
rollover propensity in this study.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ford spokeswoman Jennifer Flake said the company had just  
received the report and could not comment in detail until engineers 
had a chance to review it. However, she said the agency's rollover 
findings for the Ranger ``are not consistent with what we've found 
during nearly two decades of Ranger engineering, testing and 
development work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at General Motors, which sells the Tracker, said the  
outrigger adds weight to the vehicles and skews test results. The 
Tracker is made by Suzuki Motor Corp. and sold under the Chevrolet 
nameplate. 
</P>
<P>
	Automakers have long said a driver's behavior is the most  
important factor in determining vehicle rollover; for instance, a 
motorist who drives too fast and plows off the road is more likely 
to roll over. 
</P>
<P>
	``The phenomenon of rollover is primarily attributed to driver  
behavior,'' said GM spokesman Greg Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-seven percent of all fatalities in light trucks result  
from rollover, NHTSA says. By comparison, 22 percent of car deaths 
involve rollovers. More than 9,400 people died in rollover crashes 
in 1997, the latest year statistics were available. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
