<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Terrorist Threats Detailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An anthrax release in Boston, a North Korean  
sale of nuclear bombs and an Iraqi nerve-agent attack on U.S. 
troops were among the potential threats to Americans cited 
Wednesday by a commission urging government action to combat such 
risks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are woefully unprepared, and we would like to see something  
done before some incident occurs,'' said Sen. Arlen Specter, the 
commission's vice chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	Specter, R-Pa., said he would introduce legislation Thursday to  
tighten export controls on items that might be used to manufacture 
heavily destructive weaponry and wants to have all worldwide 
transactions recorded electronically. 
</P>
<P>
	The main proposals of the 12-member panel, headed by former CIA  
Director John Deutch and including a wide range of government and 
private nonproliferation experts, were disclosed in interviews last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton said the commission's report contained ``a  
number of interesting recommendations and observations that deserve 
serious consideration.'' He directed his national security adviser, 
Sandy Berger, to coordinate an interagency assessment of the 
recommendations and to report back within 60 days. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission on Wednesday released 265 pages of report and  
documentation that spells out fears of potential doomsday weaponry. 
</P>
<P>
	The material also details a plan to give the vice president the  
lead role in preventing and dealing with the threat of weapons of 
mass destruction, which the commission says has increased markedly 
in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe the country needs to be better protected,'' Deutch  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission concludes that the top levels of government are  
``not effectively organized to combat proliferation'' and 
recommends the president appoint a ``national director to combat 
proliferation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The director would coordinate diplomatic steps to stop the  
spread of nuclear, chemical and biological weapons. The director 
also would oversee a special government panel, made up of assistant 
secretaries from various agencies, that would seek to prevent the 
targeting of Americans and to respond to any catastrophic attack at 
home or abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	Deutch said placing the government's nonproliferation efforts  
under a single budget and director would help in preparing to deal 
with ``a calamitous eventuality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One commission member, former Democratic Sen. James Exon of  
Nebraska, dissenting from the report's main recommendation, urged 
greater Cabinet-level involvement and a nonproliferation director 
who would report directly to the president. 
</P>
<P>
	``What has been crafted, in may opinion, is another lower-level  
'working group,''' Exon said. He agreed with the extent of the 
threat and proposed an even more aggressive response. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal already has received a cool response at the  
Pentagon. Deputy Defense Secretary John Hamre said last week that 
the existing lines of authority are sufficiently clear and do not 
require the appointment of a special coordinator. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the scenarios outlined in the report by the Commission to  
Assess the Organization of the Federal Government to Combat the 
Proliferation of Weapons of Mass Destruction: 
</P>
<P>
	--Anthrax is released in a Boston subway station during rush  
hour, sending 6,000 people to hospital emergency rooms. 
</P>
<P>
	--Analysts estimate that North Korean scientists have assembled  
10 nuclear weapons, and intelligence reports say North Korea is 
planning to sell two. 
</P>
<P>
	--Iraqi President Saddam Hussein orders Scud missiles carrying  
nerve agents fired upon U.S. troops in Turkey and Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
<P>
	--A disgruntled Russian scientist at Ozersk acquires 44 pounds of  
highly enriched uranium and sells it to Iran. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 14:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
