<HEADLINE> Parziale Named Bureau Chief in Ohio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Eva Parziale, director of the photo archive of  
The Associated Press since 1997 and a former bureau chief in 
Oregon, has been named chief of bureau in Columbus, Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	She succeeds Jake Booher, who is retiring after 35 years with  
the AP, the last 18 in charge of Ohio operations. The appointment 
was announced today by President Louis D. Boccardi. 
</P>
<P>
	Parziale joined the AP in San Francisco in 1984. After earning a  
master's degree in journalism at Columbia University in 1985, she 
rejoined the AP in Miami. She also was correspondent in Portland, 
Maine; news editor in Columbia, S.C.; and assistant chief of bureau 
in Kansas City before being named bureau chief in Portland in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Parziale, 38, graduated from Bowling Green State University and  
worked for the Lake County Telegraph in Painesville, Ohio, before 
joining the AP. 
</P>
<P>
	Booher joined the AP in Albuquerque, N.M., in 1964. He worked on  
the news cooperative's main editing desk in New York and was news 
editor in Salt Lake City before becoming bureau chief in 
Louisville, Ky., in 1976. He has been bureau chief in Columbus 
since 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	Booher, 61, grew up in Knoxville, Tenn., and is a graduate of  
the University of Tennessee. He worked for the Knoxville 
News-Sentinel before joining the AP. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
