<DOCNO> APW19990714.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 18:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Eases Food Stamp Regulations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- President Clinton took several steps Wednesday  
to widen eligibility for food stamps as a way to encourage the 
continuing shift of Americans from welfare to low-paying jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are changing the rules so thousands of poor working  
families won't be denied food stamps, as they are today, just 
because they own a reliable car,'' Clinton told a meeting of the 
Democratic Leadership Council here. 
</P>
<P>
	The president ordered a simplification of food stamp rules that  
the White House said discourage recipients from getting jobs and 
burdens agencies with excessive paperwork. For instance, under the 
new rules, working families receiving food stamps will have to 
report expected earnings each quarter, rather than each month. 
</P>
<P>
	The new rules implemented through an executive order also will  
allow states to use more lenient asset tests in determining 
eligibility. Currently, working families on federal assistance, 
such as child care, lose food stamp eligibility if their car is 
worth more than $4,650. 
</P>
<P>
	Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, who administers the food  
stamp program, also will launch a public education campaign aimed 
at advising low-income families of their possible eligibility, the 
White House said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
