<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Old Pike Is Just Getting Started </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Don't let the name fool you.  
</P>
<P>
	Old Pike is a young rock band: five single guys in their 20s who  
are hoping their debut CD ``Ten Thousand Nights'' won't be their 
last. 
</P>
<P>
	Old Pike consists of singer Tim Jones, keyboardist Mike Flynn,  
guitarist Carl Broemel, bassist Jason Brammer and drummer Pat 
Spurgeon. 
</P>
<P>
	The group's roots are in Indiana -- Pike Township High School in  
Indianapolis to be exact, hence the band's name. Jones, Broemel and 
Brammer were students there. Old Pike was formed at Indiana 
University in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Band members say they are probably more influenced by Bruce  
Springsteen than by local star John Mellencamp, who lives near 
Bloomington, Ind., where the band makes its home. 
</P>
<P>
	Flynn joined Old Pike in 1996 and he began taking care of the  
business side of things. He got to know the names of people who 
hired bands and worked at record companies. He sent tapes to clubs, 
booked engagements and invited recording executives to hear the 
band play. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd pretend I was the manager,'' Flynn said. ``I'd say, `I've  
got a great band that wants to come through your town.' I got 
pretty lucky with a lot of shows.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, band members supported themselves by doing small  
construction jobs, borrowing $5,000 from a friend and taking loans 
from their families. 
</P>
<P>
	The band's first recordings were for Flat Earth Records in  
Indianapolis. Old Pike spent five days in October 1997 doing seven 
songs for an extended-play recording. The band also had a split 
record come out with Chamberlain, on Dog House Records. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones writes the band's lyrics, and Flynn and Broemel write the  
music. 
</P>
<P>
	Old Pike toured three weeks with Ben Folds Five in November  
1997. The band played 1,500-seat, sold-out audiences every night. 
</P>
<P>
	``The intensity and love for music was there and kids like to  
see that,'' Flynn said. ``It was our first experience of larger 
success.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``When we played the Fillmore in San Francisco, everybody was  
backstage calling friends, saying, `We're at the Fillmore.' It was 
one of the highlights of my life. Every sold-out show, they put the 
poster up at the Fillmore. No matter what happens, I can take my 
kids there someday and say, `See. I did it.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Old Pike signed with Sony's 550 Music label during last year's  
South by Southwest conference in Austin, Texas. They had performed 
at the American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers' 
showcase. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones said the band connected with producer Jim Scott.  
</P>
<P>
	``His objective was to make a rock 'n' roll record, which is  
kind of the point,'' Jones said. ``A lot of producers are into 
getting a hit right away -- which hopefully we can live with or live 
without. He wanted us to make a CD people would be able to listen 
to for a long time.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
