<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Mostly Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell Wednesday against most major  
currencies as the euro recovered slightly from the new low it set a 
day earlier and Japanese authorities failed to intervene on push 
the yen lower. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0209, up  
from late Tuesday's $1.0164 and above the record low of $1.0108 set 
earlier Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, the euro remains 14 percent below its level of  
nearly $1.19 when it started trading Jan. 4, replacing the 
currencies of 11 European nations. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 120.59 Japanese yen, down from  
121.32 yen late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Nickerson, a currency strategist in New York for Bank of  
America, said the Bank of Japan's continued absence from the 
currency markets was a key factor in the dollar's decline. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have already gone through some levels here where we would  
have expected to see them'' buying dollars, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese authorities have expressed concern that a strong yen  
could hurt exports and inhibit Japanese economic recovery. The Bank 
of Japan showed over the past month it was willing to buy dollars 
aggressively in an effort to curb the yen's rise. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar may have also been hurt by reports of an unexpected  
decline in U.S. wholesale prices and a weaker-than-expected rise in 
U.S. retail sales last month. The government statistics were seen 
as easing pressure on Federal Reserve policy-makers to raise 
interest rates further. Rising U.S. rates boost returns on 
dollar-denominated investments and often increase demand for the 
dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Wednesday, the dollar also was quoted at 1.5727  
Swiss francs, down from 1.5766 a day earlier, and 1.4810 Canadian 
dollars, down from 1.4815. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound rose to $1.5637 from late Tuesday's $1.5574.  
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on Wednesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.9152  
German marks, down from 1.9216; and 6.4250 French francs, down from 
6.4537. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
