<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Banks Report Mixed Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Two big banks reported divergent second-quarter results  
Wednesday, as First Union Corp. confirmed its earlier prediction of 
an earnings drop and Fleet Financial Group Inc. said its profits 
rose 15 percent. 

</P>
<P>
                         *First Union Corp.    	
</P>
<P>
	First Union's second-quarter net earnings fell 1 percent to $873  
million, or 82 cents a share, from operating earnings of $883 
million, or 92 cents a share, in the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's sixth-largest bank reported operating earnings for  
the year-ago quarter because its net profits were reduced sharply 
by $634 million in one-time acquisition and restructuring costs. 
Operating earnings made for a more accurate picture of the 
company's performance. 
</P>
<P>
	The quarterly results were better than the Charlotte, N.C.-based  
bank forecast in May, when it deflated Wall Street expectations for 
the second time this year by predicting second-quarter earnings in 
the range of $770 million to $800 million, or 80 to 83 cents a 
share. 
</P>
<P>
	The results were also a penny over the expectations of analysts  
polled by the research firm First Call Corp. Before the bank 
revised its earnings outlook in May, analysts expected First Union 
to earn about 97 cents per share in the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	First Union reported a 13 percent increase in fee and other  
income to $1.7 billion, excluding portfolio securities 
transactions. 
</P>
<P>
	Chairman and chief executive officer Edward Crutchfield said one  
reason for the company's struggles has been its tripling in size 
over the last three years. First Union's largest acquisition, 
Philadelphia's CoreStates Financial Corp., has not produced the 
revenues First Union had anticipated. 
</P>
<P>
	In February, First Union said it would trim its work force 7  
percent to cut annual costs by $400 million. 
</P>
<P>
	After merger-related and restructuring charges, net income for  
the year's first six months was $1.6 billion, or $1.63 per share, 
compared with $1 billion, or $1.07 per share, for the first six 
months of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	First Union's shares rose 12 1/2 cents to $46.81 1/4 in trading on the  
New York Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
                     *Fleet Financial Group Inc.    	
</P>
<P>
	Boston-based Fleet reported a 15 percent jump in profits for the  
second quarter as fees rose and its brokerage unit posted strong 
results. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's eighth-largest banking company earned $450 million,  
or 74 cents a share, beating Wall Street's expectations by a penny. 
That compares with earnings of $393 million, or 65 cents a share, 
in the second quarter last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Total revenue increased to $2.07 billion from $1.79 billion last  
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both our core franchise and recent acquisitions continue to  
perform well, giving us strong momentum as we approach our merger 
with BankBoston,'' Terrence Murray, chairman and chief executive 
officer, said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareholders of Fleet and BankBoston are scheduled to vote on  
the merger next month. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue from fees charged to Fleet customers rose 28 percent in  
the second quarter to $1.04 billion -- and now accounts for half the 
bank's total revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	Investment services revenue increased 20 percent to $264 million  
driven by a strong stock market, which boosted the corporation's 
brokerage and clearing units of Quick &AMP; Reilly. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first half of the year, the bank earned $888 million, or  
$1.45 a share, up 24 percent from the $716 million, or $1.18 a 
share, for the same period of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues for the first half were $4.07 billion vs. $3.42  
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleet shares rose 18 3/4 cents to $42.12 1/2 in trading on the New  
York Stock Exchange. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
