<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Weyerhaeuser Profit Up 138 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FEDERAL WAY, Wash. (AP) -- Weyerhaeuser Co.'s second-quarter  
profits more than doubled on strong demand for lumber and other 
wood products. 
</P>
<P>
	Weyerhaeuser had net earnings of $164 million, or 82 cents per  
share, up 138 percent from $69 million, or 34 cents a share, in the 
same period a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Net sales for the quarter rose 14 percent from $2.7 billion to  
$3 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The results surpassed analysts' consensus prediction of 70 cents  
a share, according to First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said new home construction and homeowners'  
renovation of existing houses contributed to growth in its wood 
products business and in its real estate segment. It predicted the 
growth would continue into the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Weyerhaeuser's wood products business had operating earnings of  
$173.8 million, a 226 percent increase over the $53.3 million in 
earnings for second-quarter 1998. Earnings for real estate rose 
from $16.5 million to $44.9 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnings for the timberlands segment also were up, while the  
pulp, paper and packaging segment was down slightly because of 
plant maintenance, drought conditions affecting the Plymouth, N.C., 
mill, and a labor dispute at the Dryden, Ontario, paper mill. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first six months of the year, profits were $166 million,  
or 58 cents a share, compared with $154 million, or 77 cents a 
share, a year earlier. The net earnings include a one-time charge 
of $150 million for an accounting change and the sale of 
Weyerhaeuser's composite products business. 
</P>
<P>
	Net sales for the first half were $5.7 billion, up from $5.3  
billion in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares for Weyerhauser Co. remained unchanged at $63.50 in  
trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 19:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
