<HEADLINE> 3 Killed in Stadium Crane Collapse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- A giant crane used for building Miller Park  
collapsed Wednesday onto the partially finished stadium, killing at 
least three people, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	The crane, nicknamed ``Big Blue,'' collapsed while trying to  
lift a section of the retractable roof, aerial photos shown on 
local television stations showed. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong winds in the area were gusting to about 30 mph at the  
time. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Geoff Leber, a senior plastic surgery resident at the nearby  
Veterans Administration hospital, said he was taking photos of the 
crane's lift just before 5 p.m. but had gone back inside the 
hospital when a patient told him the crane collapsed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was just wondering how that crane could support all that  
weight. It was windy at the time,'' he said. When he looked back 
outside, ``you could see the whole structure inside the stadium.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new ballpark for the Milwaukee Brewers is scheduled to open  
next season. Its most unique feature is the retractable roof. 
</P>
<P>
	The roof is being built by Mitsubishi. The huge crane, soaring  
480 feet into the air, was used to lift seven sections of a roof 
structure with a total weight of 12,000 tons. 
</P>
<P>
	With about half the sections in place, the roof had been  
expected to be done in about November. 
</P>
<P>
	Construction of the 43,000-seat, grass-field ballpark had  
resulted in few accidents until Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, several workers were injured when a steel girder  
being lowered into position collided with an aerial basket. 
</P>
<P>
	A worker fell 60 feet from the retractable roof May 10 and was  
hospitalized about a week with multiple injuries. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
