<HEADLINE> Hugh Downs To Report Via Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Veteran broadcast journalist Hugh Downs, who  
recently announced his retirement as host of ABC-TV's ``20/20'' 
news show, will begin working with the Internet video network 
iNEXTV Corp. this fall, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Downs, 78, who will leave ``20/20'' in September, will work on  
stories and projects for the New York-based iNEXTV, a provider of 
audio and visual content for the Internet. Downs, the company said, 
will have a lot of freedom in what he chooses to cover. 
</P>
<P>
	One project Downs will be involved in will be iNEXTV's Executive  
Branch TV, which will cover the White House and the activities of 
executive agencies such as the Federal Communications Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Downs' work will be shown on iNEXTV's network of three Internet  
video sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Downs joins CNN's Lou Dobbs as another high-profile journalist  
making a foray into the Internet. Dobbs quit CNN's ``Moneyline'' 
last month to launch Space.com, a Web site devoted to educating 
users about outer space. 
</P>
<P>
	Downs began his career as a journalist with NBC after serving in  
World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	When he announced he was leaving ABC in May, Downs hinted at his  
latest move. ``This fast-moving cybernetic age holds such challenge 
and opportunity that I now find it irresistible,'' he said in 
reference to new media. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
