<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bookseller Urged To Alter Ad Slogan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Barnesandnoble.com, the online superstore, likes  
to boast that ``If we don't have your book nobody does.'' An 
industry regulator says the claim is false and should be changed. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you were to interpret the slogan literally, it would  
discourage searches from other sources,'' said Nicholas Vianna, 
advertising review specialist with the National Advertising 
Division. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the book industry there are private books, local  
publishers, all kinds of books,'' Vianna said Tuesday. ``Some of 
the independent sellers make their livelihood on that special niche 
market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NAD was responding to a complaint filed last December by the  
American Booksellers Association, which compiled a list of 100 
out-of-print titles and found 24 that were available only through 
competitors of Barnesandnoble.com. They included such obscure works 
as ``Cartels, Combines &AMP; Trusts in Post-War Germany'' and ``Studies 
in Machiavellianism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of independent booksellers complained because that  
slogan just wasn't accurate,'' said association president Richard 
Howorth, whose organization consists overwhelmingly of independent 
stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Barnesandnoble.com agreed to comply with last week's  
decision, as of Tuesday the slogan still appeared on its Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	``We disagreed with the NAD's recommendation but chose to comply  
because we were moving away from that advertising slogan,'' said 
spokeswoman Mary Ellen Keating. ``We agreed to remove or modify the 
slogan over the next several months.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The National Advertising Division, part of the Council of Better  
Business Bureaus, is a self-regulating body established by the 
advertising industry. Compliance with NAD decisions is voluntary, 
but some cases are referred to the Federal Trade Commission. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
