<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SKorea Moves Vs. Monfort Beef </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korea has accused Monfort Inc.  
of illegally upgrading beef quality certificates and banned the 
American meat packer from bidding on government purchases of 
imported beef. 
</P>
<P>
	The Agriculture and Forestry Ministry said Wednesday it took the  
action after 313 tons of Monfort meat sold to the government in 
November was found to have been improperly upgraded to ``choice'' 
from ``no grade.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The action dealt a further blow to Monfort, whose 30 percent  
share of South Korea's growing imported beef market has already 
been hurt by a trademark dispute with its former South Korean 
distributor. 
</P>
<P>
	Ministry officials said they were investigating an allegation  
that Monfort had systematically upgraded U.S. Department of 
Agriculture certificates on its meat. 
</P>
<P>
	``We consider this a serious violation. There will be harsher  
punishment if we find similar violations in beef sold to private 
distributors as well,'' said Kim Jong-bin, a ministry official. 
</P>
<P>
	The government buys about one-third of at least 200,000 tons of  
beef that South Korea promised to import annually under the World 
Trade Organization free trade pact. 
</P>
<P>
	The government also ordered Viteck and Unicorp --  
California-based meat exporters which shipped the Monfort beef -- to 
pay $76,077 in damages. They were also banned from South Korea for 
1 1/2 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Viteck and Unicorp were reportedly owned by the family of Kim  
Gap-su, a Korean-American who had worked as Monfort's South Korean 
distributor for 10 years until he was fired in November. 
</P>
<P>
	``The certificate was altered while the meat was going through  
Mr. Kim's hands,'' said Lee Soo-yeon of Seoul's MediCom, a public 
relations firm that speaks for Monfort. ``Monfort had no knowledge 
of what happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kim, now in the United States, was not immediately available for  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Monfort filed a lawsuit in April, accusing Kim of registering a  
Monfort trademark in Korea in 1993 in his own company's name 
without Monfort's approval. 
</P>
<P>
	About the same time, Kim persuaded South Korea's customs  
authorities to block entry to 776 tons of Monfort beef, saying his 
trademark registration gave him exclusive rights to the Monfort 
label in Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	The import ban ended in June when Monfort won a preliminary  
injunction barring Kim from enforcing his trademark rights pending 
a ruling on the dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Monfort, of Greeley, Colo., is owned by food giant ConAgra Inc.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
