<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Girl With Brain Partially Removed OK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- A teen-ager plagued by seizures caused by a  
deadly neurological condition was moving and starting to open her 
eyes today after surgeons removed half of her brain to block the 
spread of her rare disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Amber Ramirez was in fair condition at Johns Hopkins Medical  
Center, said her surgeon, Dr. Benjamin Carson. 
</P>
<P>
	Scar tissue from previous operations slowed the surgery that  
lasted nine hours Tuesday, but there were ``no real 
complications,'' Carson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The operation removed the left side of Amber's brain -- the side  
that controls speech and fine motor movements. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've lived all my life with seizures,'' Amber said before the  
operation. ``I'm tired of having to put up with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The surgery could leave 15-year-old Amber without the ability to  
speak. 
</P>
<P>
	Amber, who was diagnosed with Rasmussen's disease, was making  
some sounds and was starting to open her eyes, and she grabbed his 
hand when she was stimulated, Carson said. 
</P>
<P>
	She also moved her left arm and leg when stimulated, said Dr.  
John Freeman, director of the pediatric epilepsy program at 
Hopkins. 
</P>
<P>
	``I anticipate she will be able to use her arm, not for fine  
movement, but as a helper hand,'' Carson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Without the surgery, the Lincoln, Neb., girl faced the  
possibility of mental retardation, paralysis and even death as the 
disease gradually attacked her brain. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rasmussen's syndrome eats away at one side of the brain like a  
PAC Man,'' Freeman said earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Amber and her mother, Sheri Ramirez, knew that the girl was  
considered old for the procedure. But Carson said he was confident 
the procedure will work, though she will need years of 
rehabilitation. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's a bit older than most patients who had a hemispherectomy  
but she's certainly not the oldest patient we've operated on,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Amber's disease began with a limp in 1993, when she was 9. She  
couldn't remember getting hurt, but her right foot ached. She was 
in a wheelchair two months later. 
</P>
<P>
	Then the seizures began, one each hour, pulling on her right leg  
and arm until she wanted to scream from the pain. 
</P>
<P>
	She was eventually diagnosed with Rasmussen's syndrome, which  
affects about 1,000 people worldwide. Medication and surgery to 
remove diseased snippets of brain tissue slowed the disease but 
could not stop it. 
</P>
<P>
	Amber's doctors say the remaining portion of her brain will try  
to compensate for the tissue removed. 
</P>
<P>
	``After a hemispherectomy, the other side of the brain picks up  
a lot of function,'' Freeman said. ``Intelligence and memory 
remain, but the patient will walk with a limp and will not be able 
to use their opposite hand.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Ramirez said she and her daughter understood that the  
rehabilitation would be long and difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	``We thought a lot about the future when making our decision. We  
thought about Amber maybe being able to leave home and being 
independent,'' Ms. Ramirez said. ``Amber wanted to get rid of her 
seizures, to not have to have somebody walk two steps behind her 
all the time.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 14:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Berkeley Station Rocked by Protests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) -- Public radio station KPFA, a longtime  
outlet for radical politics in famously liberal Berkeley, has been 
rocked by arrests, firings and demonstrations in what staff members 
see as a battle against corporate conformity. 
</P>
<P>
	Staffers say the station's parent company, the nonprofit  
Pacifica Foundation, is trying to make KPFA more mainstream. 
</P>
<P>
	``These people have come in and have stolen the station,'' said  
Lavarn Williams, one of some 30 people holding a day-long protest 
outside the station Wednesday morning. ``Instead of free speech, 
they want government-controlled speech.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Williams is a consultant brought in to help the station --  
one of the nation's oldest listener-supported stations -- celebrate 
its 50th anniversary. Instead, she found herself caught up in an 
escalating series of clashes over KPFA's soul. 
</P>
<P>
	The unrest has gotten so bad that on Wednesday, the doors were  
locked and managers were playing tapes of old shows. ``Everyone at 
KPFA has been placed on administrative leave until we're able to 
cool things off,'' said Pacifica spokeswoman Elan Fabbri. 
</P>
<P>
	Longtime staffers say Pacifica's board wants to give KPFA a more  
conventional image so that it can attract corporate donations. They 
also suspect that Pacifica, which owns five radio stations, is 
interested in selling KPFA. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither of those contentions is true, Ms. Fabbri said. ``There  
is no attempt to `corporatize.' That's a nice little buzzword 
that's been thrown into this,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	KPFA, founded by World War II conscientious objectors, plays a  
mix of music, public affairs and educational programming. The 
station claims to have been the first to play the Grateful Dead. 
Over the years, it also broadcast Allen Ginsberg reading ``Howl!'' 
and Patty Hearst, the kidnapped newspaper heiress, denouncing her 
parents as ``capitalist pigs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dissent over the future of KPFA has been building since April,  
when popular general manager Nicole Sawaya was dismissed. 
</P>
<P>
	Two longtime programmers, broadcaster Larry Bensky and volunteer  
folk music host Robbie Osman, were later fired for denouncing 
management policies on the air. Last month, 13 people were arrested 
for trespassing as they demonstrated against those firings. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday night, Dennis Bernstein, host of a public affairs  
program called ``Flashpoints,'' was yanked off the air for talking 
about conflicts with the station's management. That violated orders 
not to report on growing tensions between KPFA and its parent 
company, Ms. Fabbri said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bernstein was told he was being put on administrative leave  
after his program ended, but his ensuing tussle with Pacifica 
guards was heard on the air. ``Those are my personal papers!'' 
Bernstein was heard yelling. ``Don't go into my desk!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Management cut off the newscast and, in a quintessentially  
Berkeley moment, replaced the evening news with a taped 
Marxist-Maoist analysis of the 1960s. 
</P>
<P>
	Bernstein, seven other KPFA employees and more than 40  
protesters were arrested Tuesday night for trespassing after they 
refused to leave the station. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm flabbergasted that I would be pulled from the air by  
people who founded the station to stand as a bastion of free 
speech,'' Bernstein said later. ``This is an absolute case of 
censorship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters of the station say it is not so much a radical forum  
as one of the last remaining outlets for alternative points of 
view. 
</P>
<P>
	``This country wants to manufacture consent,'' said retired  
anatomy professor Jack Chamberlain, who held up a sign reading 
``Speak Free or Die'' outside KPFA. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 22:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Holland Mulls Coaching Minnesota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Terry Holland, former basketball coach at  
Virginia and the school's athletic director for four years, says he 
expects to decide by the weekend whether to become basketball coach 
at Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	In a copyright story for Thursday's editions, the Star Tribune  
said Holland was offered a seven-year contract that would pay him 
close to $1 million per year, $500,000 of that from outside sources 
such as basketball camps and shoe deals. 
</P>
<P>
	Holland told the newspaper after he met with the search  
committee and toured the facilities Wednesday that he hadn't yet 
accepted the job. He planned to fly back to Virginia on Thursday 
morning to think about it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The main thing is making sure for both parties that it is the  
right thing,'' Holland said. ``As I mentioned earlier, a lot of 
people have said to me, and they have probably said to folks here 
at the University of Minnesota, this is a natural. But we need to 
make sure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holland said he, athletic director Mark Dienhart and assistant  
AD Jeff Schemmel talked about how his contract should be 
structured. There has been criticism about the contract of Clem 
Haskins, who resigned in wake of an academic fraud scandal but got 
a $1.5 million buyout. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're still working on the contract,'' Holland said. ``We  
haven't come to any final conclusion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holland told the Star Tribune he does not want to return to  
administration if he takes the Minnesota job. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would want a contract that very clearly says that, that I'm  
here to coach basketball for the rest of my career,'' he said. ``If 
I do this, I certainly have no interest in going back into 
administration again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holland had a 418-216 record in 21 seasons as coach at Davidson  
and Virginia, holding the latter job from 1975 through 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Holland comes highly recommended.  
</P>
<P>
	Among those pushing Holland for the job are Big Ten commissioner  
Jim Delany, Wake Forest coach Dave Odom and Kentucky athletic 
director C.M. Newton. 
</P>
<P>
	If Holland, one of the highest-paid athletic directors in the  
country at about $250,000 a year, turns down the Gophers, Jim 
Crews, a former Indiana assistant and head coach at Evansville the 
past 13 years, is said to be next on the list. 
</P>
<P>
	Schemmel made it clear Holland is their first choice.  
</P>
<P>
	``We've offered him the job,'' Schemmel told the Star Tribune.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 08:39:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pakistan Shells Indian Highway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MUSHKOH VALLEY, India (AP) -- Pakistani artillery shells hit an  
Indian town in Kashmir today even as some Islamic fighters withdrew 
from India's portion of the territory. 
</P>
<P>
	India sent reconnaissance jets over the 1972 cease-fire line  
that divides Kashmir to ensure that Pakistan-based fighters are 
moving back from bunkered positions they had seized on strategic 
heights. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Pakistan's agreement with President Clinton to take  
``concrete steps'' to end the fighting in Kashmir, its artillery 
have shelled India's only highway through northern Kashmir for two 
consecutive nights and intermittently hit towns and villages. 
</P>
<P>
	In Islamabad, Foreign Ministry spokesman Tariq Altaf denied  
Pakistani troops were continuing to fire on Indian positions. ``To 
my knowledge, we are not involved in any shelling,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Artillery fire, however, has come from positions inside  
Pakistan, where Pakistani troops are positioned. The Islamic 
fighters are not known to have artillery. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian officers speculate it is meant to cover the retreat,  
although India had agreed Sunday, during a meeting between the two 
nations' military chiefs, that withdrawing fighters would not be 
fired upon. 
</P>
<P>
	The shelling continued into the daylight hours today, hitting  
the Indian town of Dras, where India has a major military presence. 
Four houses were damaged. 
</P>
<P>
	Officers said Indian soldiers were wounded in exchanges of small  
arms fire with resistant infiltrators in Mushkoh Valley to the west 
of Dras, and Batalik to the east. In Batalik, officers said their 
soldiers can see Islamic fighters who have taken positions right on 
the cease-fire line. 
</P>
<P>
	Near the Siachen Glacier, outside the area covered by the  
agreement to disengage forces, Indian jets spotted cement bunkers 
and airstrikes appear imminent, an intelligence officer told The 
Associated Press today. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the three bunkers were spotted near Turtuk, in a valley  
near the mountains of Batalik, where some of the heaviest fighting 
has taken place since May. More than 1,200 combatants have been 
reported killed in the fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indian army seized Turtuk in the last war with Pakistan in  
1971. About 25 people from the town were caught last month with 
stores of weapons and explosives, and were suspected to be working 
with Pakistan-based fighters. 
</P>
<P>
	At Bandipora, 10 miles from the cease-fire line, police said  
separatist militants attacked a heavily guarded paramilitary police 
camp Tuesday and shot to death a senior officer, three of his men 
and a soldier's wife. 
</P>
<P>
	This morning, a commando force from New Delhi stormed the  
barracks where militants had held 12 soldiers' relatives hostage 
overnight. All the civilians were rescued and the building was 
reduced to rubble after a two-hour firefight, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	India has said it will consider resuming peace talks with  
Pakistan that began in February only after the last intruder has 
left its territory. India's Foreign Ministry spokesman, Raminder 
Singh Jassal, has said that India holds Pakistan responsible for 
supporting terrorist acts by the militants in Kashmir. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan says it has no control over what it calls freedom  
fighters in Muslim-majority Kashmir who are seeking independence 
from the mostly Hindu India or a merger with Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	India and Pakistan have fought three wars since gaining  
independence from Britain in 1947, two of them over Kashmir. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 08:39:28 </DATE_TIME>
