<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 14:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate GOP Tallies HMO Victories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Holding firm for a second day, Senate  
Republicans refused to extend new HMO rules to all 161 million 
people with private health insurance on Wednesday. GOP leaders 
crafted alternatives to other Democratic proposals in an effort to 
blunt political damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Only a handful of Republicans have defected in a series of votes  
this week over the details of new patient protections. That's 
partly because Republicans answered -- or promised to answer -- 
Democratic proposals on emergency room care, women's health and 
clinical trials. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's why people are sticking together, because they know we  
are going to deliver on the substance,'' said Sen. Bill Frist, 
R-Tenn., who is helping to lead the GOP effort. ``That's the 
strategy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate considered more than a half-dozen issues Wednesday,  
including clinical trials, breast cancer treatments, emergency room 
treatments, access to specialists and a new tax deduction for 
long-term care. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate voted, 52-48, to restrict many of the provisions to  
the 48 million Americans whose health plans fall outside state 
regulation. Democrats wanted to cover all 161 million people with 
private health insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate also agreed to require health insurance companies to  
pay for overnight hospital stays when women are treated for breast 
cancer, if a doctor recommends it. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote on breast cancer came a day after Republicans rejected  
a similar, broader Democratic measure and promised to produce their 
own version. 
</P>
<P>
	But on Wednesday, all 45 Democrats balked at the GOP breast  
cancer provision because it also eliminated a Democratic amendment 
that would have allowed easier access to experimental treatments. 
Democrats tried to get the Senate to include both provisions, but 
Republicans refused. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Republicans promised to produce their own amendment on  
experimental treatments by Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll deliver,'' Frist said, promising to fold some ``very  
good'' Democratic ideas into the final GOP bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The only major issue yet to be considered is the right to sue.  
Democrats want to give patients who are denied care the power to 
take their health plans to court. That issue was set for debate 
Thursday, when the Senate will take a final vote on the HMO 
package. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, the Senate is virtually certain to approve the  
Republican plan, which President Clinton has signaled he will veto. 
With no compromise in sight, it is unlikely any of these rules will 
become law this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Democrats and Republicans have legislation offering new  
federal rights for Americans in health maintenance organizations 
and other managed care plans. But the GOP plan is more modest than 
the Democratic bill on virtually every issue. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the Senate took a second vote concerning who is  
covered under the GOP bill. 
</P>
<P>
	It had considered the same issue Tuesday, but that vote was  
muddied because it was actually voting to replace the measure on 
coverage with one concerning taxes. The vote Wednesday vote was a 
direct referendum on who is covered by the legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Who is covered is among the most fundamental questions being  
debated this week, clearly demonstrating each party's approach to 
the role of government. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP bill would apply many of the new patient protections  
only to the 48 million Americans who are in health plans that are 
exempt from similar state regulations. Other people are covered by 
state law, and Republicans say states can adopt these rules if they 
want to. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't think that the source of all wisdom when it comes to  
health care is in Washington, D.C.,'' said Sen. Don Nickles, 
R-Okla. ``We don't have the philosophy that one size fits all ... 
that whatever the states have done is not good enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats want to include all 161 million Americans who have  
private health insurance. This would assure that everyone gets the 
new rights, even if the states do not adopt them on their own. 
</P>
<P>
	``The role of the federal government is to step in when  
protections need to be everywhere in this country,'' said Health 
and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala, who went to Capitol 
Hill to boost the Democrats' bill. 
</P>
<P>
	But Republicans did extend some of their provisions beyond the  
core 48 million people. 
</P>
<P>
	The breast cancer amendment, introduced by Sen. Olympia Snowe,  
R-Maine, covers everyone with private health insurance except state 
and local workers, or about 140 million people. 
</P>
<P>
	And the GOP would require all health plans to adopt appeals  
procedures, allowing patients to take denials of care to outside 
panels. The same goes for a ban on discrimination against people 
based on their genetic information. 
</P>
<P>
	No Democrat has voted with Republicans during this week's  
debate, and only a handful of Republicans have voted with 
Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Those siding with Democrats at least once were GOP Sens. Spencer  
Abraham of Michigan, John Chafee of Rhode Island, Peter Fitzgerald 
of Illinois, John McCain of Arizona, Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania 
and John Warner of Virginia. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 16:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> News Channels Following Ventura </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- MSNBC's Laura Ingraham was immersed in serious  
political talk with presidential contender John McCain when, 
suddenly, the screen filled with a picture of Jesse Ventura in a 
feather boa and jewel-studded sunglasses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Minnesota governor's return to the wrestling ring blends  
politics and entertainment in a novel fashion and, as a result, 
gave cable news networks an interesting test of how it defined 
news. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox News Channel aired live coverage of Ventura's announcement  
that he'll referee a World Wrestling Federation match next month. 
So did MSNBC. CNN ignored it. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can do news events and still have fun,'' John Moody, Fox  
News Channel's vice president for news, said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox commentator Dick Morris, called the event ``a ritual  
political suicide ... In the last 15 minutes, this man has 
destroyed his political career,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coverage of Ventura's news conference delayed Ingraham's MSNBC  
interview with McCain on issues facing presidential candidates, 
leaving the Arizona senator looking slightly perturbed. Ingraham 
asked McCain to talk about Ventura's conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	CNN thought Ventura's announcement wasn't particularly  
newsworthy, spokesman Earl Casey said. CNN was covering the arrest 
of a suspect in the railroad killer case and Israeli Prime Minister 
Ehud Barak's visit to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was our decision at the time to give more topical  
information to our viewers,'' Casey said. 
</P>
<P>
	CNN was also queasy about airing live video provided by the WWF  
to promote a pay-per-view event. CNN founder Ted Turner's TNT 
network also telecast World Championship Wrestling events, and the 
WCW is the WWF's mortal competitor. 
</P>
<P>
	Moody admitted Fox considered whether it was being used to  
promote an event but thought he couldn't pass up the event. Fox 
used the WWF's video. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jesse Ventura is a political phenomenon,'' he said. ``There is  
no other way to describe him. To come from his background and be 
elected governor is a political rarity. Therefore, he's 
newsworthy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NBC had its own news crew at Ventura's announcement, said Bob  
Epstein, MSNBC executive producer. He said covering the event was a 
perfect fit with Ingraham's show, which tries to mix politics and 
culture. 
</P>
<P>
	``It really did show how these lines have been crossed and  
merged into one,'' Epstein said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 17:46:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  First Half Forgetful for Dodgers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Despite a strong start and fast finish, the  
first half of the season has been a total disaster for the Los 
Angeles Dodgers, who have proven to be one of the worst teams money 
can buy so far this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to completely forget about the first half, to tell you  
the truth,'' said catcher Todd Hundley, one of the many 
disappointments on one of baseball's highest-paid teams through 86 
games. ``We're not worried about the total picture, we're worried 
about the next game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That comes Thursday night when the Dodgers return from the  
All-Star break to open a three-game interleague series at Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
	Dodger hopes were high before the season, and understandably so.  
General manager Kevin Malone shelled out plenty of the Fox Group's 
money, much of it to Kevin Brown, to produce a winner, and there 
was even talk of a World Series appearance from a team that hasn't 
won a postseason game since 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	Raul Mondesi hit two dramatic homers on opening day to trigger a  
5-1 start, and it appeared the Dodgers were on their way. However, 
they struggled soon thereafter and the four-game winning streak 
they took into the break wasn't enough to get them out of last 
place in the NL West. 
</P>
<P>
	``The other teams are outperforming us,'' first-year manager  
Davey Johnson admitted. ``We need to change that. I think we're 
pressing, but all of us press when things don't go our way. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been painful, no doubt.''  
</P>
<P>
	Johnson's previous teams finished first or second in all 10  
years he managed a full season. That streak is in serious jeopardy, 
since the Dodgers (39-47) trail the NL West-leading San Francisco 
Giants by 10 games with 76 remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	Statistics tell much of the story.  
</P>
<P>
	The Dodgers are next-to-last in the NL in team batting average  
(.263), 12th in runs scored (397), and 14th in on-base percentage 
(.336). 
</P>
<P>
	That might be acceptable if the pitching was up to usual Dodger  
standards, but it's not even close. The team ERA of 4.58 ranks 10th 
in the NL, and would be the highest since the franchise moved to 
Los Angeles from Brooklyn 41 years ago if the season ended today. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the staff ERA has been over 4.00 just three times since  
the team moved -- 4.47 in 1958, 4.04 in 1961, and 4.17 in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown (9-6, 3.53 ERA), who became baseball's first $100 million  
man when he signed a signed a seven-year, $105 million contract 
last December, and Ismael Valdes (7-7, 3.36 ERA) have pitched 
reasonably well. However, the other starters -- Darren Dreifort 
(7-8, 5.77 ERA), Chan Ho Park (5-7, 6.52 ERA) and Carlos Perez 
(2-9, 6.95 ERA) -- have struggled. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know the fans are frustrated and the front office is  
frustrated, but there's no one more frustrated than we as 
players,'' said Hundley, who is hitting only .229 and has thrown 
out just 10 of 74 base-stealers. 
</P>
<P>
	Trying to bounce back from reconstructive surgery on his  
throwing elbow, Hundley missed most of spring training and is still 
paying for that. 
</P>
<P>
	Mondesi got off to a great start, prompting comparisons to  
fellow Dominican Sammy Sosa. However, Mondesi has hit just one 
homer since finishing May with 18, and hasn't homered in his last 
102 at-bats. 
</P>
<P>
	Todd Hollandsworth, a reserve, is one of the few accomplished  
left-handed hitters the Dodgers have, prompting recent trade talk 
involving first baseman Eric Karros, a right-handed batter. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, if the Dodgers don't get back into the division race in  
the next few weeks, there's a good chance they'll try to make some 
deals to dump salaries and replenish the farm system before the 
July 31 trade deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're looking at all our options,'' Malone said. ``Our first  
choice is we get on a roll and play winning baseball, and all the 
questions we have will have been answered.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 17:46:00 </DATE_TIME>
