<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 15:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arrested Mother Suing NBA Entity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Laurie Del Negro spotted a newspaper ad  
offering a good price on San Antonio Spurs caps during the NBA 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Thrilled by the bargain, she bought more than four dozen and  
sold some outside the Alamodome before attending a Spurs game with 
her husband on May 29. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of earning extra bucks, Del Negro was hauled away in  
handcuffs and spent the night in jail. Now, she's suing NBA 
Properties Inc., the marketing and licensing arm of the league. 
</P>
<P>
	NBA Properties, which worked with plain-clothed police officers,  
accused Del Negro of counterfeiting the merchandise but has since 
dropped its complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	The NBA would not comment on Del Negro's arrest, citing the  
pending litigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are confident that no rights were violated,'' said Hilary  
Cassidy, an NBA spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 43-year-old Del Negro, a mother of two teen-age  
daughters, contends that in its zeal to squeeze ``every last buck'' 
out of its merchandise licensing fees, NBA Properties caused her to 
be falsely arrested and publicly humiliated. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was so unbelievable that I kept telling myself that this is  
going to be over in just a few minutes. They're going to say, 
'Oops, I made a mistake,' '' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Del Negro spent nearly 15 hours behind bars before being  
released on $800 bond at 5:30 a.m. the next day. 
</P>
<P>
	She is seeking ``substantial damages,'' her lawyer, Bernard  
Fischman, said without giving details. 
</P>
<P>
	She also is suing Jim Dunworth Inc., owner of Designer Outlet,  
where she bought the caps at a going-out-of-business sale. A Jim 
Dunworth Inc. representative did not return a telephone call for 
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not clear whether the caps were indeed fakes. Each one  
had a tag bearing what looked like a serial number and official 
seal. NBA Properties had said it appeared the caps were made by a 
former business partner. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 00:50:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls, Japanese Stocks Rise / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar dropped vs. the yen Wednesday, while  
Japanese stocks jumped amid hopes for Japan's economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.08 yen in mid-afternoon trading, down 1.06  
yen, late Tuesday in Tokyo and below its late New York level of 
121.32 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 176.77  
points, or 0.97 percent, to close at 18,357.86 points. On Tuesday, 
the average closed down 0.42 points, or 0.03 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, investors sold dollars on reduced concern  
that the Bank of Japan will intervene to weaken the yen, as it has 
done on several recent occasions. The moves were meant to help the 
nation's economy recover from its worst recession since World War 
II. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong yen makes Japanese exports more expensive abroad and  
thus less competitive, reducing dollar-denominated earnings of 
Japanese exporters. 
</P>
<P>
	But the central bank seems comfortable with the current  
dollar-yen level, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	It is also unlikely that the Bank of Japan will step into the  
currency market right now because the United States wants Japan to 
improve economic fundamentals rather than tinker with currency 
exchange rates, said Kosuke Hanao, a currency trader at the 
Industrial Bank of Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	``The general mood is against intervention,'' Hanao said. There  
is resistance in the U.S. Congress to Japanese moves to strengthen 
the dollar, a move that could exacerbate the United States' soaring 
trade deficit, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Concern that demand for U.S. products and services could decline  
in Latin American economies also hurt the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	New uncertainty about Latin America surfaced Monday when  
candidates for Argentina's October elections raised the possibility 
of debt restructuring, which could hurt some U.S. lenders. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 123.22 yen, down  
from 123.64 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices rose amid active buying of  
international blue chips. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section jumped 13.38 points, or 0.90 percent, to 1,497.07. 
The TOPIX closed down 0.42 points, or 0.03 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York on Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average fell  
25.96 points to 11,175.02. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.6550 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.6000 
percent, driving its price down to 101.26 yen from 101.74 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
