<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Suit Goes to Conn. Jury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- A jury began deliberations Wednesday in  
the case of a small Danbury software company that claims Microsoft 
Corp. violated antitrust laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury in U.S. District Court deliberated for about four hours  
before adjourning for the day. Deliberations were scheduled to 
resume at 9 a.m. Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bristol Technology Inc. claimed during a six-week civil trial  
that Microsoft cut off its access to Windows source code -- software 
blueprints -- hampering its ability to do business. 
</P>
<P>
	Bristol makes a product called Wind/U, which allows programs,  
such as word processors and spreadsheets, written to work with 
Windows to be converted to run on computers with different 
operating systems such as Unix. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies had a three-year contract in which Microsoft  
gave Bristol access to source code it needed to create Wind/U. 
</P>
<P>
	Bristol sued in August, claiming it was unable to reach an  
agreement with Microsoft for a new contract for the latest versions 
of Windows NT, a top program for running computer networks. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft lawyers told the jury the company tried repeatedly to  
negotiate a new contract with Bristol, and that Bristol rejected 
the same licensing deal that was approved by Mainsoft, one of its 
main competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe the evidence shows Microsoft treated Bristol very  
fairly and favorably,'' Microsoft spokesman Tom Pilla said after 
the case went to the jury Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The evidence is before the jury, and we have full confidence  
that the jury will make the right decision,'' said Bristol Chief 
Executive Officer Keith Blackwell. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft is also facing a much larger antitrust case in  
Washington, brought by the Justice Department and 19 states. The 
government contends that Microsoft illegally wielded monopoly power 
from its dominant Windows product to expand into new markets, such 
as Internet software, and thus crush competitors. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 14:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ludzik Takes Over As Lightning Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- When the Tampa Bay Lightning decided on a  
coaching change, there was no question the struggling franchise 
would turn to Steve Ludzik. 
</P>
<P>
	The former NHL player not only had close ties to new owner  
William Davidson and vice president of hockey operations Rick 
Dudley, but his style fits the philosophy of the new regime to a 
tee. 
</P>
<P>
	``In today's game, there's a new wave of coach,'' Dudley said  
Wednesday after firing Jacques Demers and replacing him with the 
38-year-old Ludzik. 
</P>
<P>
	``The old coach said this is my system and you will do it. The  
new wave says I have to be able to adjust because not everything I 
do every day is going to work against everything someone else 
does.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ludzik spent the last three seasons in the International Hockey  
League coaching Davidson's Detroit Vipers. He was an assistant 
under Dudley for a year before succeeding his boss and leading the 
club to a pair of appearances in the IHL's Turner Cup Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale of the Lightning to a group led by Davidson was  
finalized last month. Dudley, meanwhile, was lured from the Ottawa 
Senators to run the team's hockey operation. 
</P>
<P>
	Demers led the Lightning for a little less than two seasons,  
finishing with the NHL's worst record each year, including a 
19-54-9 mark last winter. He had three years remaining on his 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Once Dudley decided not to retain Demers, whose 409 victories  
rank 11th on the league's all-time list, he moved swiftly to bring 
in Ludzik. Director of player development Don Murdoch was also 
fired. 
</P>
<P>
	Ludzik, 38, becomes the team's fourth coach in eight seasons.  
</P>
<P>
	He compiled a 154-58-34 record in the IHL and led Detroit to the  
league title in 1997. The Vipers were Turner Cup finalists the 
following year and advanced to the Eastern Conference finals last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	His transition to coaching in the NHL figures to be helped by  
his relationship with Dudley. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will try to build this franchise the way we did it in  
Detroit ... Every coach that takes over says: `We're going to be 
the hardest-working team.' We're going to be hard-working, but 
we're going to work smart. We're going to learn and we're going to 
do things the right way,'' Ludzik said. 
</P>
<P>
	Demers, who led Montreal to the Stanley Cup title in 1993,  
joined the Lightning in November 1997. In just under two seasons, 
he guided the team to a 34-96-17 record. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to serving as coach, he was the team's general  
manager, a role that will be handled now by Dudley, who also was 
responsible for making two draft-day trades that figure to help the 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know these people,'' Ludzik said. ``We will not stop until  
we get this franchise where it should be. And I can't say I'd be 
happy playing average. I want to get to the top of the 
conference.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 22:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Accused Ex-Deputy Found Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) -- A former California sheriff's deputy was  
found dead Wednesday a few days after he became the subject of a 
nationwide search for allegedly killing a colleague 14 years ago in 
a possible love triangle. 
</P>
<P>
	DNA tests unavailable at the time of the 1985 killing were  
performed on blood and hair evidence, implicating retired Los 
Angeles sheriff's deputy Ted Eugene Kirby in the death of Sgt. 
George Arthur. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirby, 54, disappeared June 30 after having provided saliva and  
other DNA samples to police. On Monday, police issued a warrant for 
his arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	A television reporter and photographer in Kirby's neighborhood  
Wednesday found his decomposed body near his Spokane home. 
</P>
<P>
	The body ``appeared to have some sort of head trauma,'' possibly  
a gunshot wound, Spokane County sheriff's spokesman Deputy Dave 
Reagan said. A handgun was found nearby. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators say a DNA sample taken from Kirby matched blood  
collected from the crime scene in 1985. A love triangle may have 
been the motive, police sources told the Los Angeles Times. 
</P>
<P>
	Arthur, 37, was found dead in his van parked on a Los Angeles  
freeway ramp. He was shot after leaving work at the Men's Central 
Jail, where Kirby also worked. 
</P>
<P>
	Detectives believe Kirby, who retired from the jail, hid inside  
Arthur's van and shot him while he was driving, causing the vehicle 
to crash. Witnesses said they saw a man crawl from the wreckage and 
limp away. 
</P>
<P>
	A coroner's autopsy showed Arthur had struggled with his  
attacker before he was shot. At the time, however, the technology 
did not exist to link the hair and blood samples found in the van 
to a suspect. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, investigators reopened the case and took DNA samples  
from several people, including Kirby. On July 7, they went to 
Kirby's home in Spokane, but his wife said he left June 30 without 
explanation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 05:50:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Sales Rise 0.1 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Retail sales growth slowed in June, rising  
just 0.1 percent, reflecting a sharp drop in automotive sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Total retail sales, which represent about a third of the  
nation's economic output, rose last month to a seasonally adjusted 
$243.3 billion, the Commerce Department said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The June increase followed a big 1.2 percent gain in retail  
sales in May -- better than the government previously estimated. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had expected June's retail sales growth to slow, mainly  
predicting that consumers' red-hot buying spree for autos and 
trucks so far this year would cool. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, retail sales have climbed or held steady for 11 months  
running and were 8 percent percent higher than June of last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers' robust appetite for shopping is being fueled by the  
country's economic good times. The nation's low unemployment rate 
is hovering at levels that haven't been seen in three decades. 
Consumer confidence is high, inflation remains low and the stock 
market continues to post record gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the overall increase in retail sales, automotive sales  
fell a sharp 1 percent in June after reporting strong gains of 3.5 
percent in May. And, sales at gasoline stations also went down 0.4 
percent last month. 
</P>
<P>
	But even without the often volatile autos category, retail sales  
would have increased 0.4 percent in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of durable goods -- items expected to last at least three  
years -- fell 0.4 percent in June following a strong 2.3 percent 
increase in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Furniture stores' sales rose 0.2 percent in June after being up  
0.7 percent in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of nondurable goods, such as food and fuel, also were up  
in June, rising 0.4 percent, following a 0.5 percent increase in 
May. 
</P>
<P>
	At apparel and accessory shops, sales rose 0.2 percent in June  
and sales at department and general merchandise stores rose 0.5 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Food store sales also edged up in June, rising 0.1 percent,  
while grocery store sales inched down 0.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Bar and restaurant sales crept up 0.2 percent and drug and  
proprietary stores rose a sharp 1.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week the nation's biggest retailers reported surprisingly  
strong sales in June as the strong U.S. economy and warm weather 
had Americans buying everything from bathing suits to air 
conditioners. Discount chains, such as Wal-Mart, Target and Kmart, 
were the biggest winners. Specialty clothing and department stores 
also fared well. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 15:16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Ventura Will Referee WWF Match </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, who wrestled  
professionally as ``The Body,'' is returning to the ring. This 
time, however, he'll be The Guest Referee. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura promised today to bring ``law and order'' back to  
wrestling when he appears at the World Wrestling Federation's 
``SummerSlam'' event Aug. 22, ``because I rule here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura was introduced to a crowd of several hundred cheering  
wrestling fans by WWF Chairman Vince McMahon. He bellowed: ``I'm 
bigger than you, McMahon, I'm more powerful than you, I'm more 
powerful than the World Wrestling Federation. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as you're in this state, you hold no power here. It's  
very simple. It's The Body rules, it's my rules, or the highway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The governor, know for wearing feather boas in the ring before  
he retired from wrestling in 1986, was dressed in a business suit 
but accepted yellow and black feather boas from female wrestler 
Chyna and wrapped them around his neck, then donned jewel-studded 
sunglasses. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura said he will be paid $100,000 for the event. Half will  
go to a foundation for abused children and half will go to a 
scholarship endowment at his alma mater, Roosevelt High School in 
Minneapolis. Ventura said he also will get videotape royalties and 
payment for use of his name, but he said the amount is 
confidential. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, Ventura slapped down any suggestion that his return to  
wrestling threatens the dignity of his office. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no rule that says a governor can't have fun. There's  
no rule that says a governor on his own time can't be a human,'' he 
said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	State GOP Chairman Ron Eibensteiner today challenged Ventura to  
account for every dime he receives for his appearance. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our governor, donning tights and performing in a ballet of  
violence, as he likes to call it, will not bring honor and dignity 
to the office of governor in our state,'' Eibensteiner said. ``It 
seems as though, if the paycheck is big enough, The Body can be 
resurrected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura countered such criticism by saying GOP St. Paul Mayor  
Norm Coleman just struck a deal as a paid radio host. 
</P>
<P>
	``Where's the outcry? See, for Republicans, he's an  
entrepreneur,'' Ventura said. The governor also has a radio show, 
but receives no money. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the hoopla, the Reform Party governor has recorded some  
significant achievements in his first half year, including a 
permanent income tax cut and sales tax rebates. Ventura and 
Democratic and Republican leaders declared the legislative session 
a success. 
</P>
<P>
	In a poll published today, 56 percent of Minnesotans rate  
Ventura's performance as governor as good or excellent, although 
about half the respondents were concerned about his unorthodox 
behavior. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 15:16:00 </DATE_TIME>
