<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Products Boost Polaroid Profit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Polaroid Corp. reported Wednesday that  
second-quarter earnings rose 22 percent on increased sales of new 
products including its disposable instant camera. 
</P>
<P>
	Net earnings were $15 million for the quarter ended June 27, or  
33 cents per share, compared to $12 million, or 27 cents per share, 
for the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's figure took into account $10 million set aside for  
money owed by Russian retailers and a $26.3 million gain on real 
estate sales, both of which were pretax items. When those items are 
excluded, Polaroid had per-share earnings of 3 cents in the 
year-earlier period. 
</P>
<P>
	The results met the expectations of analysts surveyed by First  
Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Second-quarter revenue rose 4.7 percent to $487 million from  
$465 million last year. Worldwide sales of instant cameras were up 
60 percent compared to last year, due in part to increased sales in 
Japan and to a lesser extent in the Americas, the company reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The sales increase in both regions was attributed to the  
introduction of new products, especially PopShots, a disposable 
instant camera. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales in Europe fell to $107 million from $117 million last year  
due to lower conventional and instant film sales and unfavorable 
foreign exchange rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Polaroid has lost money in five of the last six years amid  
declining sales. It has changed its product mix in hope of 
regaining market share lost to traditional cameras. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first six months, Polaroid said its loss narrowed to  
$5.3 million, or 12 cents a share, from $16 million, or 36 cents a 
share, in the first half of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue fell to $855.3 million from $865.8 million.  
</P>
<P>
	Shares for Polaroid Corp. fell $5, or 17 percent, to $23.75 in  
trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 08:24:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Martinez Mows Down Baseball's Best </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- At the end of the next century, baseball fans  
still will be talking about what Pedro Martinez did on this night. 
</P>
<P>
	Of how Mark McGwire flailed at strike three.  
</P>
<P>
	Of how Sammy Sosa looked like a statue when a called third  
zoomed by. 
</P>
<P>
	Of how Barry Larkin, Larry Walker and Jeff Bagwell walked away  
from the plate, strikeout victims all. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball's biggest boppers came to the plate and Pedro Martinez  
made the power go out. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really didn't appreciate leading off today. I had to do  
it,'' Larkin said, in awe of Martinez's MVP performance in the 
American League's 4-1 victory Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez became the first pitcher to strike out the first three  
batters in an All-Star game, fanning Larkin, Walker and Sosa in the 
first. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't see the ball when it went by me,'' Walker said.  
</P>
<P>
	He boosted his record to the first tour when he got McGwire on  
four pitches leading off the second. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout old Fenway Park, fans were buzzing. Would Martinez  
equal, maybe surpass, the great Carl Hubbell, who struck out five 
of baseball's best, all in a row. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a matter of how bad he wants to make hitters look,''  
Texas closer John Wetteland said. 
</P>
<P>
	Now it came down to Matt Williams, no slouch himself with 23  
homers this season. Williams, who threatened Roger Maris' home run 
record before the 1994 strike, turned out to be the only blemish. 
And it wasn't that much of a smudge, a grounder to second that was 
misplayed for an error. 
</P>
<P>
	No problem.  
</P>
<P>
	All Martinez did was strike out Jeff Bagwell, and Ivan Rodriguez  
threw out Williams at second for an inning-ending double play. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those guys, those are some of the best in the world,''  
Martinez said after his 28-pitch performance in two electric 
innings. ``But anything could happen, and that's what makes our 
game so special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez silenced the National League dugout.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty obvious there's not a lot to say,'' Jeromy Burnitz  
recalled. ``Guys aren't coming back happy and gay when they strike 
out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martinez is 15-3 at the All-Star break, and has an outside  
chance to become the first 30-game winner in three decades. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got the best lively arm in the game of baseball,''  
McGwire said. ``There's a very, very good chance he'll win 30 or 
more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The performance drew comparisons of the 1934 All-Star game at  
New York's Polo Grounds, when Hubbell struck out Babe Ruth, Lou 
Gehrig, Jimmie Foxx, Al Simmons and Joe Cronin, each and every one 
elected to the Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	Larkin (165), Walker (250), Sosa (305), McGwire (485) and  
Bagwell (249) have combined for 1,454 homers. Hubbell's victims in 
1934 finished their careers with 2,218, and before long, Martinez's 
prey may top that. 
</P>
<P>
	Era of offense? Not with Martinez on the mound.  
</P>
<P>
	Ignoring all the sluggers on the field, fans who stuck around  
after the game kept chanting his name. In the shadow of the Green 
Monster, the very symbol of offense, Martinez was the star. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Pedro pretty much dominated and lifted everybody up,''  
Cleveland's Jim Thome said. ``He's a big-game pitcher, and he rises 
to the occasion.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
