<DOCNO> APW19990714.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 08:00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore No. 1 in Competitiveness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Asian financial crisis could not hold  
Singapore back from once again ranking as the world's most 
competitive nation. The United States moved up to second place from 
last year's third-place rating, while Hong Kong dropped to third, 
according to a survey released Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The report, prepared by the World Economic Forum, measures eight  
variables -- from government regulations to technology and labor 
conditions -- to try to determine which economies have the best 
ability to achieve rapid growth in coming years. 
</P>
<P>
	Completing this year's Global Competitiveness Report ``top 10''  
were Taiwan, in fourth place, followed by Canada, Switzerland, 
Luxembourg, the United Kingdom, the Netherlands and Ireland. The 
bottom five were Russia, in last place, preceded by Ukraine, 
Zimbabwe, Bulgaria and Bolivia. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeffrey Sachs, a Harvard University Professor who served as an  
adviser to the project, noted that many Asian economies ranked high 
in 1997, before the crisis caused by the collapse of several 
currencies and the flight of foreign capital. Some are just now 
showing signs of recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the Asian economies recover in the next few years and  
resume fairly rapid growth, then we would claim some vindication 
for the index,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The report cited three countries that moved up significantly in  
this year's rating, compared with 1998: Italy, up eight positions 
to No. 35; Poland, up eight to No. 43, and Finland, up four to No. 
11. 
</P>
<P>
	Italy, the report said, ``strongly improved its infrastructure  
ratings due to enhanced rail and telephone data.'' For Poland, the 
advance reflected ``rapidly improving labor market indicators,'' 
while Finland scored strongly in telecommunications and information 
technology. 
</P>
<P>
	The bottom-most tier all suffered from a variety of ailments,  
the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	``All are characterized by a low extent of the rule of law,  
reliability of property rights and poor infrastructure,'' it said. 
</P>
<P>
	The report measures finance, government policies,  
infrastructure, technology, management, labor, institutions and 
barriers to trade. 
</P>
<P>
	The forum, a Geneva-based international center dedicated to  
improving business and government, collects published data on the 
countries and conducts a survey of more than 4,000 executives 
worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Singapore has led the list of most-competitive countries in the  
four years that the report has been published. The United States, 
which ranked fourth in 1996, moved to third in 1997 and 1998 before 
reaching No. 2 this year. Hong Kong had held second place for three 
years before dropping this year to No. 3. 
</P>
<P>
	Asia's biggest economy, Japan, still struggling to recover from  
the financial crisis, slipped to 14th place from 12th. 
</P>
<P>
	The largest European Union countries also slipped slightly in  
1999 from 1998, France to 23rd from 22nd, and Germany to 25th from 
24th. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
