<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Says Bush Overlooking Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore, shadowboxing  
with his chief Republican opponent, suggested today that Texas Gov. 
George W. Bush was ``ready to move into the mansion before the 
election.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president, who trails Bush in many polls and has raised  
only half as much money, drew parallels between the 2000 
presidential race and Iowa Gov. Tom Vilsack's 1998 victory, 
although he never mentioned Bush by name. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a time when he was 20 points behind in the polls and  
there were people who said he couldn't win, right? Hmmmm,'' he 
theatrically reminded Democratic activists at the Java Joe's 
coffeehouse. 
</P>
<P>
	``He developed -- what was it? -- momentum and ideas while his  
Republican opponent was ready to move into the mansion before the 
election. I don't know, maybe it's deja vu.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The vice president used a farmhouse surrounded by cornfields  
near Waukee as a venue for pledging a renewed battle against drug 
abuse. The house has been used recently as a lab for manufacturing 
methamphetamine, also known as crank or speed. 
</P>
<P>
	The highly addictive drug has become ``a particularly insidious  
kind of threat'' in rural communities in recent years, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know that when methamphetamines can strike a place like  
this, we've got to strike back hard in a determined way,'' Gore 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	At a dinner Tuesday, Gore sharpened jabs at Bush and asked women  
to bear with his slower, steadier race focused on issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore derided Bush for his recent rejection of any ``litmus  
test'' on the abortion issue and his signature on Texas legislation 
allowing citizens to carry concealed firearms and barring 
localities from suing gun manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about the GOP stand on abortion rights, Gore parroted  
language Bush used recently to say that, as president, he would not 
select Supreme Court nominees on the basis of their views on 
abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Make no mistake about it. There IS a litmus test in the  
Republican party,'' Gore insisted to some five dozen Des 
Moines-area women he was trying to recruit for his campaign 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	``I yield to no one in my support of women's rights,'' said  
Gore, who loses narrowly to Bush among women in current polls. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, the vice president closed a two-day Iowa swing with a  
deliberative expansion on his theme of the week: crime. His drug 
speech in Waukee followed a Monday speech in Boston on gun control 
and urban crime. 
</P>
<P>
	Use of the illegal drug in rural communities has soared in  
recent years. Police seizures from clandestine meth labs in 
Missouri, Iowa, Kansas, South Dakota and Nebraska tripled between 
1992 and 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Low on specifics and bare of cost estimates, Gore is proposing  
to add 100 Drug Enforcement Administration agents specially 
assigned to rural areas and trained to shut down meth labs. The 
Clinton administration budget for fiscal 2000 asks Congress for $20 
million for this purpose. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore also would create anti-meth education programs in rural  
schools and launch a new multimedia campaign -- like the egg in the 
frying pan with the slogan ``This is your brain on drugs,'' but 
specially targeted to rural residents. 
</P>
<P>
	He also proposes doubling the number of areas designated as high  
intensity drug trafficking, a designation that brings additional 
federal attention and funds for police. There are currently 20 such 
areas. 
</P>
<P>
	And, he would up the ante by 50,000 on an old Bill Clinton  
campaign pledge to put 100,000 new cops on the beats in 
neighborhoods across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his outward focus on laying out his own policy agenda,  
Gore, for the first time since Federal Election Commission reports 
two weeks ago showed Bush raised a record $36 million in campaign 
cash this year, vented some frustration as he plugged for support. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to keep our powder dry, conserve our resources,  
develop as much unity of purpose as we can,'' the Democratic 
presidential hopeful told local women activists here Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``The other side, the Republican side, has raised more money  
than anyone ever has,'' Gore said in dire-warning tones. ``They 
have raised all this money and they're not even slowing down.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
