<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Suspected Rail Killer Faces Hearing  
</P>
<P>
	EL PASO, Texas (AP) -- The Mexican drifter suspected in eight  
murders will make another court appearance today after his attempt 
to plead guilty to a lesser charge was rebuffed. Rafael 
Resendez-Ramirez surrendered to police yesterday, ending a six-week 
manhunt. He tried to enter a guilty plea to a burglary charge 
earlier this morning, but a judge said it was an inappropriate time 
for the plea. Resendez-Ramirez is charged with three murders and 
linked to five other slayings, all of them in Texas, Kentucky and 
Illinois, and was on the FBI's 10 Most Wanted List. 

</P>
<P>
	Wider Food Stamp Eligibility Sought  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will announce today a series  
of steps intended to increase food stamp enrollment. The White 
House says only two of five working families eligible for food 
stamps actually apply for assistance and receive it. Fueled by a 
strong economy, welfare rolls have dropped from more than 5 million 
families in 1994 to just 2.7 million by the end of last year. 
However, studies show that many of the families still have trouble 
paying for food and other household bills. The president will 
simplify food stamp reporting rules which, the administration said, 
discourage recipients from going to work. 

</P>
<P>
	FCC Voting on Disabled Rule  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators are prepared to approve new  
rules requiring the telecommunications industry to make pagers, 
cellular phones and other equipment and services easier for 
disabled individuals to use. The FCC will vote today on the rule. 
Changes would include voice-activated phones, talking Caller ID and 
phones with keypads that have large buttons or specific identifying 
marks would be more commonplace. Failure to comply with the rules 
could result in penalties or damage awards ranging from the 
thousands to the millions of dollars. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Jets Bomb Iraqi Defense Sites  
</P>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- U.S. warplanes bombed Iraqi defense sites  
in the northern no-fly zone today after being fired on by Iraqi 
anti-aircraft artillery, the U.S. military said. Air Force F-16s 
and F-15s dropped laser-guided bombs on command and control sites 
west of Mosul, a city some 250 north of Baghdad. Baghdad does not 
recognize the no-fly zones and has been challenging the allied 
planes regularly since Dec. 28. 

</P>
<P>
	Suspect Mistakenly Freed Surrenders  
</P>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- An Arizona murder suspect who was  
mistakenly released from jail in a paperwork mix-up has surrendered 
to authorities. Allen Brown, charged with stabbing his girlfriend 
more than 100 times, turned himself in to FBI and Kansas City, Mo., 
investigators yesterday, a week after he was let out of Pima County 
Jail. Brown's mother said she convinced him to turn himself in. 
Police said ``a communications breakdown'' resulted in the wrongful 
release. 

</P>
<P>
	Girl Has Half Her Brain Removed  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- A Nebraska teen-ager plagued by seizures from a  
deadly neurological condition had surgeons remove half of her brain 
to stem the spread of the rare disease. The left side of Amber 
Ramirez' brain -- the side that controls speech and fine motor 
movements -- was removed at Johns Hopkins Medical Center. Her 
condition was not immediately released. The surgery may leave the 
15-year-old without the ability to speak, but she didn't want to 
put up with the constant seizures, a symptom of Rasmussen's 
disease, any longer. Without surgery, the girl faced the 
possibility of mental retardation, paralysis and even death. 

</P>
<P>
	Wholesale Prices Fall 0.1 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Prices at the wholesale level dipped 0.1  
percent in June, the first decrease since February, as declining 
prices for gasoline and new cars helped offset the biggest jump in 
beef prices in 12 years. The Labor Department said today that the 
decline in the Producer Price Index -- which measures inflation 
pressures before they reach the consumer -- followed a 0.2 percent 
increase in May and was the first decline since a 0.5 percent 
plunge in February. The tame inflation report should help to calm 
fears that the Federal Reserve might want to continue hiking 
interest rates to cool the economy. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 14  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 10 a.m. EDT, the Dow industrials  
were up 14.56 to 11,189.58. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 893-621. The Nasdaq was up 14.60 to 
2,792.83. 

</P>
<P>
	Fraser To Be Thrashers' Coach  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The expansion Atlanta Thrashers are expected to  
name former NHL player Curt Fraser their first head coach today. 
Fraser, who led Orlando to the IHL finals twice in the last four 
years, was chosen from a short list that also included former 
Buffalo coach Ted Nolan and ex-Edmonton coach Ron Low. Fraser 
worked with Thrashers general manager Don Waddell in Orlando. 
Fraser played with Vancouver, Chicago and Minnesota in a 12-year 
NHL career. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
  	   	
</P>
