<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Showers and storms darkened the Southwest and Southeast on  
Wednesday. It was pleasant over New England and the Great Lakes 
area, while the Pacific Northwest saw clouds. 
</P>
<P>
	The most persistent shower activity continued across the eastern  
parts of North Carolina and Virginia into Maryland and Delaware. 
</P>
<P>
	High pressure remained in control over New England and the Great  
Lakes. Very pleasant conditions and clear to partly cloudy skies 
persisted throughout the region. 
</P>
<P>
	Farther south, the central and southern Plains were fair and  
pleasant with only a few scattered showers occurring along the Gulf 
in southeastern Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	The Southwest continued to be very wet with more flooding  
occurring across parts of the Desert Southwest as a result of the 
monsoonal flow in the region. Rain continued from Southern 
California and Arizona into Colorado and New Mexico, with flood 
advisories in effect for most of northern Arizona, western 
Colorado, and the southern two-thirds of the state of Utah. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials closed a major trail in Grand Canyon National Park  
because of rock and mud slides as monsoon storms swept much of 
Arizona. Four people were injured by falling rocks, two of them 
suffering broken legs. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Park Service said the Grand Canyon was hit by up to  
3 inches of rain, producing flash flooding that damaged Bright 
Angel Trail. It will be closed for weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, storms dumped more than an inch of rain on Tucson and  
Phoenix, flooding streets and stranding vehicles. The storm also 
temporarily shut down Sky Harbor International Airport in Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	Showers also extended farther north along the eastern edge of  
the Sierra Nevadas from Nevada into Oregon and southern Idaho. 
</P>
<P>
	Farther north, skies were clear to partly cloudy across most of  
the Pacific Northwest, although a frontal boundary moving through 
the region caused shower activity in western sections of Washington 
state. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures across the Lower 48 ranged from a low of 37 in  
Stampede Pass, Wash., to an early-afternon high of 92 in Phoenix. 
With the heat index, it felt like 99 in Palm Springs, Calif. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
