<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 15:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Half Forgetful for Dodgers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Despite a strong start and fast finish, the  
first half of the season has been a total disaster for the Los 
Angeles Dodgers, who have proven to be one of the worst teams money 
can buy so far this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to completely forget about the first half, to tell you  
the truth,'' said catcher Todd Hundley, one of the many 
disappointments on one of baseball's highest-paid teams through 86 
games. ``We're not worried about the total picture, we're worried 
about the next game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That comes Thursday night when the Dodgers return from the  
All-Star break to open a three-game interleague series at Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
	Dodger hopes were high before the season, and understandably so.  
General manager Kevin Malone shelled out plenty of the Fox Group's 
money, much of it to Kevin Brown, to produce a winner, and there 
was even talk of a World Series appearance from a team that hasn't 
won a postseason game since 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	Raul Mondesi hit two dramatic homers on opening day to trigger a  
5-1 start, and it appeared the Dodgers were on their way. However, 
they struggled soon thereafter and the four-game winning streak 
they took into the break wasn't enough to get them out of last 
place in the NL West. 
</P>
<P>
	``The other teams are outperforming us,'' first-year manager  
Davey Johnson admitted. ``We need to change that. I think we're 
pressing, but all of us press when things don't go our way. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been painful, no doubt.''  
</P>
<P>
	Johnson's previous teams finished first or second in all 10  
years he managed a full season. That streak is in serious jeopardy, 
since the Dodgers (39-47) trail the NL West-leading San Francisco 
Giants by 10 games with 76 remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	Statistics tell much of the story.  
</P>
<P>
	The Dodgers are next-to-last in the NL in team batting average  
(.263), 12th in runs scored (397), and 14th in on-base percentage 
(.336). 
</P>
<P>
	That might be acceptable if the pitching was up to usual Dodger  
standards, but it's not even close. The team ERA of 4.58 ranks 10th 
in the NL, and would be the highest since the franchise moved to 
Los Angeles from Brooklyn 41 years ago if the season ended today. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the staff ERA has been over 4.00 just three times since  
the team moved -- 4.47 in 1958, 4.04 in 1961, and 4.17 in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown (9-6, 3.53 ERA), who became baseball's first $100 million  
man when he signed a signed a seven-year, $105 million contract 
last December, and Ismael Valdes (7-7, 3.36 ERA) have pitched 
reasonably well. However, the other starters -- Darren Dreifort 
(7-8, 5.77 ERA), Chan Ho Park (5-7, 6.52 ERA) and Carlos Perez 
(2-9, 6.95 ERA) -- have struggled. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know the fans are frustrated and the front office is  
frustrated, but there's no one more frustrated than we as 
players,'' said Hundley, who is hitting only .229 and has thrown 
out just 10 of 74 base-stealers. 
</P>
<P>
	Trying to bounce back from reconstructive surgery on his  
throwing elbow, Hundley missed most of spring training and is still 
paying for that. 
</P>
<P>
	Mondesi got off to a great start, prompting comparisons to  
fellow Dominican Sammy Sosa. However, Mondesi has hit just one 
homer since finishing May with 18, and hasn't homered in his last 
102 at-bats. 
</P>
<P>
	Todd Hollandsworth, a reserve, is one of the few accomplished  
left-handed hitters the Dodgers have, prompting recent trade talk 
involving first baseman Eric Karros, a right-handed batter. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, if the Dodgers don't get back into the division race in  
the next few weeks, there's a good chance they'll try to make some 
deals to dump salaries and replenish the farm system before the 
July 31 trade deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're looking at all our options,'' Malone said. ``Our first  
choice is we get on a roll and play winning baseball, and all the 
questions we have will have been answered.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
