<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Five Questions With Chris LeDoux </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Chris LeDoux is the kind of fellow who  
takes his cowboy hat seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	In ``This Cowboy's Hat,'' a song on the country singer's new  
``20 Greatest Hits'' album, a motorcyclist threatens to ``rip that 
hat right off your head.'' 
</P>
<P>
	LeDoux responds: ``You'll ride a black tornado across a Western  
sky. ... Bulldog the Mississippi, pin its ears down flat. Long 
before you take this cowboy's hat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even in a distinctly nonrugged white golf shirt during an  
interview at the offices of Capitol Nashville record company, the 
former rodeo champion exudes cowboy. He is ruggedly handsome, 
offers a firm handshake, looks you in the eye and is unfailingly 
polite. 
</P>
<P>
	One doesn't even consider messing with his hat, even if this day  
it's a baseball cap. 
</P>
<P>
	LeDoux, 50, is the genuine article, the world champion bareback  
bronco rider of 1976. He began writing and singing songs about the 
rodeo for his own amusement. He is still a working rancher, with 
about 200 cows on his Wyoming spread. 
</P>
<P>
	LeDoux put out dozens of albums on his own small record label  
starting in 1972, selling to a strong cowboy subculture left behind 
by much of mainstream country music. In 1989, a new singer named 
Garth Brooks praised LeDoux in the lyrics of his first hit single 
``Much Too Young to Feel This Damn Old.'' Brooks sang: ``The 
worn-out tape of Chris LeDoux, lonely women and bad booze seem to 
be the only friends I've left at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks has acknowledged an artistic debt to LeDoux, for his  
energetic stage show and the melding of country with 1970s rock 
influences. ``20 Greatest Hits'' includes LeDoux duets with Brooks 
(``Whatcha Gonna Do With a Cowboy''), Jon Bon Jovi, Toby Keith and 
Charlie Daniels. 
</P>
<P>
	LeDoux signed in 1991 with Capitol Nashville, which is also  
Brooks' record company, but he has not been supported by country 
music radio stations. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he continues to sell, especially in the West. ``20  
Greatest Hits'' has been selling around 10,000 copies a week, an 
amazing amount without any radio exposure. 
</P>
<P>
	1. You've had a slow-building career that has lasted an  
extraordinary long time. How have you managed that? 
</P>
<P>
	LeDoux: It was this gradual uphill climb. We started out selling  
maybe 4,000 or 5,000 albums the first year. I didn't know if I was 
reaching anybody, and I was going down a long dark tunnel and there 
didn't seem to be a light at the end of it. I was really beginning 
to wonder. And then some guy came on the radio talking about a 
`worn-out Chris LeDoux tape.' That was really the turning point. 
</P>
<P>
	2. Let's get you in trouble. Is it true Garth Brooks basically  
stole your act? 
</P>
<P>
	LeDoux (laughing): You are a troublemaker. Garth has often given  
me some credit for what he does, and I feel flattered that he says 
that. I think he was doing his thing before he saw us perform. I 
think maybe when he did see us, it kind of made him feel like it 
was OK to do that. You know, here's a guy that's a real cowboy and 
he's doing it so it's OK to go ahead and be whatever you want to 
be. I borrowed some stuff from Garth. I've borrowed from Charlie 
Daniels, so we all kind of borrow a little here and there from 
people we admire. 
</P>
<P>
	3. Your new album is called ``20 Greatest Hits,'' but really  
you've never had a ``hit.'' Why do you think radio stations 
continue to ignore you despite evidence that you have a substantial 
audience? 
</P>
<P>
	LeDoux: No, we don't really have any hits according to radio or  
Billboard or whatever. But these are the hits of my fans, hard-core 
fans. ... It is frustrating that radio hasn't really picked up on 
the stuff. We have little pockets out West that play everything we 
send out as a single. If it weren't for those areas, I don't know 
if this thing would have worked at all. 
</P>
<P>
	I hate to really go into it too much, but radio is a business,  
and they've got to play what has worked in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	4. You were among the first country acts to perform with the  
energy of an arena rock show. How did that evolve? 
</P>
<P>
	LeDoux: Somewhere in the '80s, I really started listening to a  
lot more music than just country. There was some old ZZ Top things, 
Charlie Daniels, the Eagles and just a wide variety of things. And 
my kids were listening to people like Bon Jovi, Motley Crue, AC/DC, 
all of it. 
</P>
<P>
	I hated to admit that I liked rock 'n' roll back in the '70s,  
but I did. Maybe because I was a cowboy and I thought cowboys 
aren't supposed to like rock 'n' roll. But I do. The groove, the 
energy, and then if they have a lyric to go along with it that sort 
of fits my lifestyle, then it's really good. Charlie Daniels is a 
great example of that. He can put a country lyric to a rock 'n' 
roll tune and it works. 
</P>
<P>
	5. How do you balance a music career with keeping a ranch going?  
</P>
<P>
	LeDoux: My father-in-law runs the ranch, my kids help, my wife  
helps, and when I'm home they save me some of the good chores. 
Musically, we do probably 100 dates a year, so that gives me a lot 
of time off and keeps me fresh, so when I do get back out on the 
road, we're ready and rocking. We're pretty small compared to most 
ranches. We have about 200 cows. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 13:40:27 </DATE_TIME>
