<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Concert Ticket Prices Skyrocketing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Cathy Berkman paid $125 apiece for two tickets  
to Bob Dylan and Paul Simon's upcoming show at Madison Square 
Garden, a far cry from the cheap old days of concerts. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York City epidemiologist and her husband have ticket  
stubs from a Dylan concert with the Band in 1974 for $9.50. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do wish it were more affordable,'' she said Tuesday. ``If I  
were a college student now, I wouldn't be seeing Dylan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The average concert ticket costs $38.56, up $5 in one year and  
$13 since 1996, according to a survey by the industry trade 
publication Pollstar. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rolling Stones charged an average of $109.62 per seat at the  
34 shows the band performed in the United States this year. Opera 
star Luciano Pavarotti charged a $130.77 average at four shows. 
</P>
<P>
	``The artists have really dropped the pretext that they are not  
doing it for the money,'' said Gary Bongiovanni, Pollstar editor. 
</P>
<P>
	For the hottest shows, fans don't seem to mind. Two concerts at  
Madison Square Garden by Latin sensation Ricky Martin -- with 
tickets priced between $38 and $78 -- sold out in 20 minutes on 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The actual cost to fans is usually several dollars higher than  
the ticket price, since many venues and ticket agencies add 
surcharges that weren't figured in Pollstar's average. 
</P>
<P>
	Concert tickets were undervalued for many years, judging by the  
stiff premiums that shady brokers were able to get for premium 
seats. Promoters saw how much people were willing to pay brokers, 
so they decided to charge more themselves, Bongiovanni said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ego and greed quickly became involved. When some musicians  
tested the waters with high prices, their competitors figured they 
deserved as much or more and raised their prices accordingly, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sixties-era rock fans now have more money and are willing to  
spend it on their heroes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Twenty years ago, if you were a rock 'n' roll star you had  
certain countercultural connections. You couldn't maintain that and 
charge a high level ticket price,'' Bongiovanni said. ``That's gone 
by the boards.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three old favorites -- Neil Young, Elton John and Rod Stewart --  
were in Pollstar's top 10 list of most expensive tickets this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The cheapest average tickets among the 50 most lucrative tours  
this year were sold by the heavy metal double bill of Poison and 
Ratt, at $18.09. The Offspring charged an average of $18.45. 
</P>
<P>
	Veteran concertgoer Berkman said that along with the high  
prices, concert venues do little to ensure that fans are 
comfortable, secure and enjoy the show. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems like fans have an infinite tolerance to put up with  
this kind of abuse,'' she said. ``I wish there would be a 
boycott.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 11:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
