<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 00:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Medicare Contractors Implicated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Contractors hired as the ``first line of  
defense'' against Medicare fraud'' have their own integrity 
problems, including misuse of government funds, federal 
investigators report. 
</P>
<P>
	The General Accounting Office, Congress' investigative agency,  
found that six of the contractors have paid at least $235 million 
in civil and criminal penalties since 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	And the inspector general's office of the Health and Human  
Services Department found that contractors were ``misusing 
government funds and actively trying to conceal their actions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two reports, submitted to a House Commerce subcommittee and  
obtained by The Associated Press on Tuesday, accused Medicare 
officials of doing a poor job of monitoring the contractors. The 
GAO said the officials ``may have placed too much trust'' in the 
contractors' promises that their anti-fraud systems were working. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Thomas Bliley, R-Va., chairman of the House Commerce  
Committee, had a more harsh view of findings he called ``deeply 
disturbing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the contractors were able ``to dupe'' officials of the  
Health Care Financing Administration because the agency ``routinely 
gave them advance warning about the dates of any reviews and about 
the records the agency wanted to review.'' HCFA administers the 
insurance program for the elderly. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Peacock, HCFA spokesman, responded that over the past two  
years, HCFA has cut the Medicare error rate in half, and, working 
with other agencies and officials, has returned $1.2 billion to the 
Medicare trust fund. 
</P>
<P>
	HCFA has taken steps to cut down on Medicare fraud and toughen  
oversight on Medicare contractors, Peacock said. He said HCFA has 
asked Congress to pass legislation that would enable Medicare to 
impose stiffer penalties and make it easier to take work away from 
contractors who fail to protect Medicare funds, but Congress has 
not done so. 
</P>
<P>
	General Accounting Office official Leslie G. Aronovitz told the  
committee that the six contractors who were assessed the $235 
million in penalties were charged with numerous fraudulent 
practices, including improperly paying claims, destroying or 
deleting backlogged claims, failing to recoup money owed Medicare 
and manufacturing documentation to support claims payments that 
should have been rejected. 
</P>
<P>
	The current and former contractors cited in the reports were  
hired ``to serve as Medicare's first line of defense against 
inappropriate and fraudulent claims made on Medicare funds,'' 
Aronovitz said. They work in the fee-for-service portion of the 
insurance program, and are responsible for paying providers for 
their Medicare services. 
</P>
<P>
	The GAO said the health care agency was able to identify only  
three of 17 contractors with ``integrity problems.'' The others 
were discovered through whistleblowers and federal investigators 
familiar with the contractor practices. 
</P>
<P>
	George F. Grob, deputy inspector general at HHS, reported that  
the contractors were ``misusing government funds and actively 
trying to conceal their actions, altering documents and falsifying 
statements that specific work was performed. 
</P>
<P>
	``In some cases, contractors prepared bogus documents to falsely  
demonstrate superior performance for which Medicare rewarded them 
with bonuses and additional contracts,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Grob said some contractors ``turned off'' processing systems  
designed to prevent inappropriate payments, ``resulting in misspent 
Medicare Trust Fund dollars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said a review of 12 contractors found deficiencies at all of  
them in documenting the amount of money that providers owed 
Medicare, due to overpayments and claims that should have been paid 
by other insurers. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, electronic security was so weak at 11 of the 12  
contractors that ``we were able to penetrate the security systems 
and obtain access to sensitive Medicare data,'' Grob reported. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his office's investigations resulted in nine civil  
settlements and two criminal convictions, while 21 former or 
current contractors remain under investigation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
