<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate GOP Tallies HMO Victories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Holding firm for a second day, Senate  
Republicans refused to extend new HMO rules to all 161 million 
people with private health insurance on Wednesday. GOP leaders 
crafted alternatives to other Democratic proposals in an effort to 
blunt political damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Only a handful of Republicans have defected in a series of votes  
this week over the details of new patient protections. That's 
partly because Republicans answered -- or promised to answer -- 
Democratic proposals on emergency room care, women's health and 
clinical trials. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's why people are sticking together, because they know we  
are going to deliver on the substance,'' said Sen. Bill Frist, 
R-Tenn., who is helping to lead the GOP effort. ``That's the 
strategy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate considered more than a half-dozen issues Wednesday,  
including clinical trials, breast cancer treatments, emergency room 
treatments, access to specialists and a new tax deduction for 
long-term care. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate voted, 52-48, to restrict many of the provisions to  
the 48 million Americans whose health plans fall outside state 
regulation. Democrats wanted to cover all 161 million people with 
private health insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate also agreed to require health insurance companies to  
pay for overnight hospital stays when women are treated for breast 
cancer, if a doctor recommends it. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote on breast cancer came a day after Republicans rejected  
a similar, broader Democratic measure and promised to produce their 
own version. 
</P>
<P>
	But on Wednesday, all 45 Democrats balked at the GOP breast  
cancer provision because it also eliminated a Democratic amendment 
that would have allowed easier access to experimental treatments. 
Democrats tried to get the Senate to include both provisions, but 
Republicans refused. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Republicans promised to produce their own amendment on  
experimental treatments by Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll deliver,'' Frist said, promising to fold some ``very  
good'' Democratic ideas into the final GOP bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The only major issue yet to be considered is the right to sue.  
Democrats want to give patients who are denied care the power to 
take their health plans to court. That issue was set for debate 
Thursday, when the Senate will take a final vote on the HMO 
package. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, the Senate is virtually certain to approve the  
Republican plan, which President Clinton has signaled he will veto. 
With no compromise in sight, it is unlikely any of these rules will 
become law this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Democrats and Republicans have legislation offering new  
federal rights for Americans in health maintenance organizations 
and other managed care plans. But the GOP plan is more modest than 
the Democratic bill on virtually every issue. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the Senate took a second vote concerning who is  
covered under the GOP bill. 
</P>
<P>
	It had considered the same issue Tuesday, but that vote was  
muddied because it was actually voting to replace the measure on 
coverage with one concerning taxes. The vote Wednesday vote was a 
direct referendum on who is covered by the legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Who is covered is among the most fundamental questions being  
debated this week, clearly demonstrating each party's approach to 
the role of government. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP bill would apply many of the new patient protections  
only to the 48 million Americans who are in health plans that are 
exempt from similar state regulations. Other people are covered by 
state law, and Republicans say states can adopt these rules if they 
want to. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't think that the source of all wisdom when it comes to  
health care is in Washington, D.C.,'' said Sen. Don Nickles, 
R-Okla. ``We don't have the philosophy that one size fits all ... 
that whatever the states have done is not good enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats want to include all 161 million Americans who have  
private health insurance. This would assure that everyone gets the 
new rights, even if the states do not adopt them on their own. 
</P>
<P>
	``The role of the federal government is to step in when  
protections need to be everywhere in this country,'' said Health 
and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala, who went to Capitol 
Hill to boost the Democrats' bill. 
</P>
<P>
	But Republicans did extend some of their provisions beyond the  
core 48 million people. 
</P>
<P>
	The breast cancer amendment, introduced by Sen. Olympia Snowe,  
R-Maine, covers everyone with private health insurance except state 
and local workers, or about 140 million people. 
</P>
<P>
	And the GOP would require all health plans to adopt appeals  
procedures, allowing patients to take denials of care to outside 
panels. The same goes for a ban on discrimination against people 
based on their genetic information. 
</P>
<P>
	No Democrat has voted with Republicans during this week's  
debate, and only a handful of Republicans have voted with 
Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Those siding with Democrats at least once were GOP Sens. Spencer  
Abraham of Michigan, John Chafee of Rhode Island, Peter Fitzgerald 
of Illinois, John McCain of Arizona, Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania 
and John Warner of Virginia. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
