<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Turn Upward; Dow Gains 19.31 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved higher today, led by a late rally  
in technology stocks that was spurred by a strong earnings outlook 
from computer chip maker Intel. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 19.31 at 11,194.33, offsetting much of its 26-point drop on 
Tuesday and pushing the blue-chip index within points of a new 
high. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Nasdaq composite  
index was up 33.53 at 2,811.76 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index 
was up 5.84 at 1,399.40. 
</P>
<P>
	High-tech stocks rose on positive earnings news from Intel,  
which reported late Tuesday its second-quarter earnings jumped 49 
percent and that it expects a strong second half of 1999. Intel was 
up 2 1/2 at 67 7/8, the most active stock in Nasdaq trading today. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks also got a lift from reports that fund  
managers at Fidelity Investments were putting money back into the 
tech sector. The mutual fund company had backed off such stocks 
since February. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock market was also supported by tame inflation news. The  
Labor Department reported the Producer Price Index -- which measures 
inflation pressures before they reach the consumer -- fell a 
smaller-than-expected 0.1 percent in June, the first decline in 
four months. 
</P>
<P>
	Also today, the Commerce Department said retail sales rose just  
0.1 percent in June, a big slowdown from the May increase of 1.2 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Both reports helped ease worries about a potential breakout of  
inflation, which could cause the Fed to raise rates again this year 
to slow U.S. economic growth and keep inflation contained. 
</P>
<P>
	While stocks were mostly higher in the last hour of trading,  
there was some weakness earlier in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	Blue-chip stocks fell as some investors took profits on the  
market's recent record-setting rise, which lifted the Dow to a new 
high -- its third in four sessions -- on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market came a long way in a short period of time and  
that's why we are seeing a little weakness today,'' said Alfred E. 
Goldman, director of market analysis at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in 
St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks also were hurt by increasing fears about political  
tensions in Asia after the Chinese government accused Taiwanese 
President Lee Teng-hui of embarking on a doomed attempt to split 
his island from China. 
</P>
<P>
	There were also lingering concerns about Latin America's  
economic situation. The nervousness was set off Monday by comments 
from Argentina's presidential candidates, who hinted at a possible 
moratorium on repayment of the country's debt. That raised concerns 
on Wall Street that U.S. financial services companies would suffer 
losses because of unpaid loans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Plain and simple, the market turned a blind eye to the Latin  
American situation over the last seven or eight months,'' said 
Bryan Piskorowski, market analyst at Prudential Securities. 
``Argentina has served as a reminder that they need to watch the 
situation in Latin America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Stock Exchange composite index was up 1.99 at  
655.63, and the American Stock Exchange composite index was down 
0.42 at 811.91. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by narrow margin on the  
NYSE, where volume came to 594.09 million shares, up from 594.91 
million shares on Tuesday. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
