<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. To Work Against Trade Barriers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration pledged Wednesday  
to make elimination of foreign barriers to American farm exports 
the centerpiece of upcoming world trade talks, despite strong 
European opposition. 
</P>
<P>
	Administration witnesses before a Senate Finance subcommittee on  
trade said Europe's efforts to sidetrack the upcoming round of 
global trade talks with extraneous issues will not work. 
</P>
<P>
	David Aaron, under secretary of commerce for international  
trade, called Europe's tactics the ``ABA strategy -- anything but 
agriculture,'' hoping to include so many issues for negotiators to 
tackle that nothing gets accomplished in the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Failure to reach a deal would preserve current European  
agriculture trade policies, which include high barriers blocking 
sales of many American farm products and trade-distorting 
production subsidies for their domestic crops. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to make agriculture the centerpiece for progress in  
the round,'' Aaron told the senators. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy U.S. Trade Representative Richard Fisher said European  
farmers are the most protected in the world with EU programs 
accounting for 85 percent of total world spending on farm 
subsidies. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher said U.S. negotiators will push for significant cuts in  
agricultural tariffs and the total elimination of export subsidies, 
which distort trade by driving down global prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States is the host for a meeting of trade ministers  
from the 134 nations that belong to the World Trade Organization. 
The WTO conference in Seattle in late November and early December 
is the expected formal launch of a new round of talks with a goal 
of further lowering barriers to trade in manufactured goods, 
services and agriculture. 
</P>
<P>
	The subcommittee chairman, Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, said  
it was crucial to make agriculture a priority. 
</P>
<P>
	But he and other committee members criticized the administration  
for its failure to push aggressively for the legislative authority 
it will need to complete the global trade talks, known as fast 
track authority. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are hosting the meeting in November, yet the president of  
the United States is effectively without a seat at the table,'' 
Grassley said. ``Other countries won't have the confidence to 
negotiate an agreement with us if our president doesn't have fast 
track authority.'' 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton has been unable during the past two years to  
gain approval of fast track authority because of strong opposition 
from Democrats. Fisher told the committee the administration was 
engaged in consultations with Democrats and Republicans in the 
House and the Senate, trying to gain a consensus on fast track 
legislation that could be approved. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, criticized the administration for  
a lack of leadership in the trade area. 
</P>
<P>
	``This administration hasn't had the courage to push a fast  
track bill and push its own people to support it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm also criticized the administration for walking away in  
April from a good offer from the Chinese to open its markets to 
American exports in return for U.S. support of its membership in 
the WTO. Gramm said he feared ``we missed a golden opportunity'' 
that would have reaped significant benefits in increased sales for 
American farmers and manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher later told reporters that the trade talks with China  
probably would remain on hold until after an upcoming Chinese 
leadership meeting. While Japan and Australia recently completed 
their own WTO agreements with China, Fisher said those deals fell 
far short of the market-opening moves the administration will 
demand before it drops its objections to China's entry into the 
WTO. 
</P>
<P>
	``It appears that the Japanese have left it to us to do the  
heavy lifting'' in terms of getting meaningful trade concessions 
from the Chinese, Fisher said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
