<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady Makes Awkward Slip-Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCKVILLE CENTRE, N.Y. (AP) -- It was a poignant moment. In a  
discussion on gun violence, Hillary Rodham Clinton began addressing 
a woman whose son was injured in a 1994 shooting at the State 
University of New York at Albany. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've really spent a lot of time in the years since your  
son's murder ....'' Mrs. Clinton told Alice McEnaney. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. McEnaney interrupted her. ``He wasn't murdered,'' she said.  
``My son's alive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Thank God,'' said Mrs. Clinton.  
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton looked at the young man, who was among the 60  
people who had gathered at a middle school to discuss gun violence 
with the first lady. ``I support everything she does,'' he said of 
his mother's anti-gun work. ``It brings tears to my eyes that she's 
taken this on as her mission.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jason McEnaney was shot in the groin when he disarmed a gunman  
holding 36 people hostage in a classroom. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton had met Mrs. McEnaney, but not Jason, prior to the  
forum. Before Mrs. Clinton spoke, Mrs. McEnaney had talked about 
the incident involving her son but did not specifically say he had 
survived. 
</P>
<P>
	The discussion on gun violence was part of Mrs. Clinton's  
``listening tour'' of New York. She is traveling around the state 
as she considers a run for the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	A statewide poll released Wednesday said Rudolph Giuliani, the  
Republican mayor of New York City, had a slight lead in a 
head-to-head matchup against Mrs. Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll from Marist College's Institute for Public Opinion,  
said Giuliani was the choice of 47 percent of voters questioned 
with Mrs. Clinton favored by 41 percent. Twelve percent were 
undecided. 
</P>
<P>
	In January and February, separate Marist polls had the first  
lady sporting an 11-point lead over the mayor. By April that had 
dwindled to a statistical dead heat. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Hillary Clinton is on a listening tour, New Yorkers are not  
saying what she wants to hear,'' Marist pollster Lee Miringoff 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Miringoff said the first lady is obviously concentrating her  
efforts initially where she needs the most help. 
</P>
<P>
	Among upstate voters, the poll found Giuliani was favored by 56  
percent while 30 percent backed Mrs. Clinton. In the suburbs, 
Giuliani led the first lady, 54 percent to 35 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In Democrat-dominated New York City, Mrs. Clinton led, 61  
percent to 29 percent. Traditionally, if a Republican can draw 30 
percent of the New York City vote in a statewide race, the 
Democratic candidate is in trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	One-third of voters said they had a great deal of concern that  
she is not from New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton and Giuliani have both formed Senate exploratory  
committees. Also considering a run at the Republican nomination is 
Rep. Rick Lazio of Long Island. Mrs. Clinton led Lazio, 46 percent 
to 34 percent, the poll said. 
</P>
<P>
	The telephone poll of 515 registered voters was conducted Sunday  
and Monday and has a margin of error plus or minus 4.5 percentage 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hillary Clinton is listening to people, not polls,'' said  
Howard Wolfson, her committee spokesman. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
