<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bayer To Expand Calif. Biotech Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- German chemicals and pharmaceuticals  
group Bayer AG plans to spend $340 million in expanding its 
California biotechnology center because of biotechnology's 
increasing importance in medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	Bayer has already invested $300 million in facilities at the  
site in Berkeley, Calif., which is Bayer's global headquarters for 
research, development and production of biotechnology products. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the products produced there is the hemophilia treatment  
Factor VIII, or Kogenate. 
</P>
<P>
	Additional investment will be made over the next five years,  
starting with construction of a new $9 million central services 
building, due for completion next spring. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to act now to increase our capacities in order to  
continue to meet the challenges and requirements of the market in 
the future,'' said Michael Kamarck, senior vice president of Bayer 
Corp., the group's U.S. arm. 
</P>
<P>
	Bayer said production capacity at the site could double by 2022  
and sees payrolls increasing by 600 from a current 1,200. 
</P>
<P>
	The investment is part of a 10-year, $15 billion U.S. expansion  
program that began in 1995, the company said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
