<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Britain To Resume Beef Shipments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- British beef producers are preparing to resume  
exports on Aug. 1, now that European regulators have ended a 
three-year ban imposed after an outbreak of ``mad cow'' disease. 
</P>
<P>
	The embargo had crippled Britain's beef industry, with lost  
sales estimated at more than $2.4 billion, and cattle farmers and 
industry executives welcomed the European Commission's decision 
Wednesday to let British beef back into overseas shops and 
restaurants. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a tremendous day -- British beef will once again be  
able to leave these shores and be enjoyed on the dinner plates of 
the world,'' National Farmers' Union president Ben Gill said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the industry still faces a long struggle to regain its  
reputation and rebuild overseas sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's tremendous news, ... but unfortunately it's not the end  
of this sad story,'' said Welsh cattle farmer Peredur Hughes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've now got to work very, very hard to get that market back  
because other people have stepped in to sell their beef. They will 
not be happy to give up their business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Brussels, Belgium-based European Commission, which enforces  
rules for the 15-member European Union, voted to clear British beef 
for export after it received final approval from EU veterinary 
experts. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision ends a ban that the commission imposed after a 1996  
outbreak in Britain of bovine spongiform encephalopathy, or mad cow 
disease, which medical researchers linked to a fatal human brain 
ailment, Creutzfeldt-Jacob disease. 
</P>
<P>
	British beef still will be subject to strict precautions.  
</P>
<P>
	All meat for export must be de-boned and come from cattle born  
after Aug. 1, 1996, when a ban came into force on the feeding to 
animals of meat and bone-meal. Meat from cattle more than 30 months 
old will not be sold overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	The embargo devastated Britain's beef industry. Domestic prices  
plunged by more than 50 percent as desperate farmers sold their 
meat in a glutted local market, and foreign competitors grabbed 
lucrative overseas orders. 
</P>
<P>
	EU Agriculture Commissioner Franz Fischler, speaking to the  
British Broadcasting Corp., said that results of scientific studies 
and inspections justified ending the embargo. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I wouldn't be convinced about that, then I would not vote  
in favor to lift the ban,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But it will take more than Fischler's imprimatur to win back  
Britain's lost market share. The Meat and Livestock Commission, a 
privately funded trade organization, expects beef exports this year 
to number no more than 5,000 metric tons. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, British beef exports totaled 246,000 metric tons in  
1995, the last year before the ban. A metric ton is about 2,205 
pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a long, hard struggle,'' said commission  
spokesman Jon Bullock. 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort to restore confidence, industry officials have  
adopted a subdued marketing strategy. They've given beef industry 
tours to 15 groups of journalists from continental Europe, but 
otherwise they have no plans to call attention to their product. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you called a product 'British beef,' you'd never launch it.  
Because of the problems over the past years, British beef has a 
poor reputation,'' said Terry Lee, who heads export marketing for 
The Meat and Livestock Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the mad cow furor, British beef was synonomous with high  
quality. Most of it came from cattle raised in grassy pastures 
rather than commercial feedlots, and chefs served the meat from 
France to South Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee expects cattlemen in France and Italy to pressure  
supermarkets not to buy British beef, and he anticipates that 
initial exports will be mostly to high-end restaurants and butcher 
shops. 
</P>
<P>
	The first, symbolic shipment of beef is destined for a  
restaurant in Lille, France. 
</P>
<P>
	Cattle farmer Charles Smart said that exporters would probably  
have to offer big discounts to win back overseas customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't envy the men who are going to export this beef. I  
think they're going to lose a packet,'' said Smart, who owns 500 
head of cattle on a farm near Norfolk, 100 miles north of London. 
</P>
<P>
	For some producers, the embargo has ended too late. Gill, of the  
National Farmers' Union, suggested that many of Britain's 100,000 
cattle farms were irreparably damaged by the export ban. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know a number of people who just packed it in,'' said  
Hughes, who raises 70 cattle on a farm near Llangefni in Wales, 250 
miles west of London. 
</P>
<P>
	Hughes was lucky, and resourceful. He staved off financial ruin  
by renting out some of his wind-swept pasture land to a company 
that erected 16 wind turbines to generate electricity. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal earns him nearly $50,000 a year, while he barely breaks  
even selling cattle. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
