<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China.com Makes Big Debut on Nasdaq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Even with investors clamoring to enter China's  
potentially vast Internet market, the CEO of China.com was 
conspicuously shy Wednesday about the service provider's Wall 
Street debut. 
</P>
<P>
	China.com had an impressive initial public offering on the  
technology-heavy Nasdaq index -- rocketing from its launch at $20 a 
share to close Tuesday at $67.109 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	In early trading Wednesday, China.com gave up some of those  
gains, dropping 6.5 percent to $62.75 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the sort of debut -- raising $84 million dollars, 40  
percent more than expected -- that would have had many executives 
crowing. 
</P>
<P>
	But after weeks of news stories on China.com's  
less-than-sterling track record, chief executive Peter Yip at the 
last minute barred reporters from a speech Wednesday at an Internet 
conference in Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	Journalists who had received invitations to the event were  
denied entry at the door. 
</P>
<P>
	Yip specifically said he didn't want to talk to the media,  
explained Andrew Robinson, a representative from the conference 
organizer, Gavin Anderson &AMP; Co. 
</P>
<P>
	China.com targets users in mainland China, Hong Kong and Taiwan.  
But so far it is only a minor player in the mainland market, not 
even making the top 20 in some surveys. 
</P>
<P>
	It posted a loss last year of $8.5 million on revenue of $3.5  
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Further concerns have been raised about censorship from the  
Chinese government, a major stakeholder though its Xinhua News 
Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Rajeev Gupta, Asian Internet analyst at investment bank Goldman  
Sachs, said China.com attracted so many buyers in its stock debut 
because of big demand for ``a stock that provides both the Internet 
and Asia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The growing Internet market in China has had investors  
scrambling for a way on board. 
</P>
<P>
	A Xinhua report on Wednesday said the number of Internet users  
in China hit 4 million in June and could reach as high as 8 million 
by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	A large proportion of the users are young, well educated and  
urban, with 85 percent of them men, the report said. The number of 
on-line computers is also growing, hitting 1.46 million in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Gupta said China.com needs to customize its content for China's  
provinces to attract more mainland users and keep them coming back. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's about stickiness, getting your users there and keeping  
them there,'' Gupta said. 
</P>
<P>
	Key shareholders in China.com include Xinhua, with a 13.6  
percent stake; Hong Kong-based New World Infrastructure, with 22.7 
percent; and U.S. Internet access provider America Online Inc, with 
10 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
