<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coal Power Faulted Over Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Reliance on cheaper, coal-burning power plants  
by electric utilities because of price competition has 
substantially increased air pollution, two environmental groups 
charged Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	A 16 percent increase in electricity production from  
coal-burning power plants from 1992 and 1997 produced an additional 
755,000 tons of smog-causing pollution annually, the 
environmentalists said in a report. 
</P>
<P>
	The environmentalist attributed the increase to competition in  
the electric utility industry, which has made increased use of 
cheaper, more polluting coal plants more attractive to power 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Deregulation breathed new life into old creaky power plants,''  
maintained the report by U.S. Public Interest Research Group and 
the Environmental Working Group. 
</P>
<P>
	But utility spokesmen said that on a per-kilowatt-hour basis,  
smog-causing nitrogen oxide emissions have declined and that 
competition probably had little impact on the numbers cited by the 
environmental groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``You certainly can't say all that growth (in generation) is  
related to competition,'' said John Kinsman of the Edison Electric 
Institute, which represents investor-owned electric utilities. He 
said electricity generation from all plants has been going up 1.5 
percent to 2.5 percent a year because of economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Environmentalists long have been concerned that the new emphasis  
on price competition will give a cost advantage to utilities that 
rely heavily on cheaper, more polluting, coal-burning power plants, 
especially those in the Ohio Valley and Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	The environmentalists' report said annual nitrogen oxide  
emission from 446 coal-burning power plants increased by 755,000 
tons between 1992 and 1998 because of increases in electricity 
generation from those plants. 
</P>
<P>
	That increase was equivalent to the nitrogen oxide pollution  
from 37 million cars, said Rebecca Stanfield of U.S.PIRG, one of 
the authors of the study. 
</P>
<P>
	John Coequyt of EWG said, ``Switching from coal to cleaner fuels  
such as natural gas is the way to solve our smog and global warming 
problems. Instead the utilities are taking us in the opposite 
direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kinsman, the utility industry spokesman, said the report  
``totally ignores all the emission reductions we're required to 
undertake starting in 2000'' as part of federal acid rain 
regulations and beginning in 2003 as part of additional federal 
controls on nitrogen oxide emissions. 
</P>
<P>
	Buddy Eller, a spokesman for Southern Co., a utility that relies  
heavily on coal-burning power plants, said that while coal use has 
increased, emissions from coal-burning plants on a 
kilowatt-hour-basis have declined. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can do a lot with numbers,'' said Eller.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 08:10:27 </DATE_TIME>
