<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gold Hits 20-Year Low  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Gold futures fell to fresh 20-year lows Wednesday on the New  
York Mercantile Exchange after British officials appeared to reject 
suggestions they change their gold sale plans. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, copper futures rose sharply, while corn and  
soybeans moved high on the threat of hot, dry weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold futures continued their slide after British Prime Minister  
Tony Blair defended his country's recent sale of 25 tons of its 
gold reserves. His comments suggested his government will continue 
to dispose of what will eventually be more than half its reserves 
despite widespread criticism. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold futures have been in general decline for more than a year  
as the metal loses its traditional role as an investment hedge 
against economic or political turmoil, leaving it in demand mostly 
for making jewelry. 
</P>
<P>
	The slide steepened earlier this year after Britain announced it  
would join Australia, Canada, Belgium and other countries in 
selling reserves in favor of better-returning investments such as 
U.S. Treasury bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics have called Britain's gold sale plan especially flawed  
since the government essentially has told speculators when each 
auction would occur, allowing for price manipulation. Britain 
denied that occurred last week with its first sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Proposals by Switzerland and the International Monetary Fund to  
sell gold also have kept prices on the defensive. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold for August delivery fell $1.70 to $255 an ounce.  
</P>
<P>
	Copper futures jumped on the New York Mercantile Exchange,  
moving higher for the first time in days, on market talk that 
producers are considering additional cutbacks to boost prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Copper futures in recent weeks had experienced a price rebound  
as key producers moved to curtail the operations in the face of a 
global supply glut. But prices fell sharply on Tuesday after 
warehouses monitored by the London Metal Exchange reported a large 
increase, which led to ideas the glut would not ease quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	But prices rebounded Wednesday on talk that Asarco Inc. or  
Cyprus Amax Minerals Co. would be the latest to voluntarily cut 
back mine production. 
</P>
<P>
	Asarco declined comment, while Cyprus Amax denied the  
speculation. 
</P>
<P>
	September high-grade copper rose 1.5 cents to 77.70 cents a  
pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Grain and soybean futures advanced on the Chicago Board of Trade  
as hot, dry weather moved into Midwest growing regions. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were concerned about pockets of dryness across major  
growing areas, particularly in central Illinois, one of the 
nation's largest corn and soybean growing states. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures across the region were expected to rise into the  
90s over the next few days, which could further drain moisture from 
the soil and lead to heat stress. That, in turn, could lead to 
reduced yields. 
</P>
<P>
	December wheat rose 1 1/4 cents to $2.60 1/2 a bushel; December corn  
rose 4 1/2 cents to $2.01 a bushel; December oats rose 3/4 cent to 
$1.09 1/2 a bushel; November soybeans rose 1 1/4 cents to $4.21 a bushel. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
