<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wal-Mart To Pay $6.4M to Hilfiger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Wal-Mart Stores Inc. says it has hired  
an independent inspector to watch for counterfeit clothing after 
agreeing to a $6.4 million settlement with apparel-maker Tommy 
Hilfiger. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement Wednesday ends a five-year legal battle in which  
Tommy Hilfiger U.S.A Inc. had repeatedly accused the world's 
largest retailer of selling fake Hilfiger clothes under the guise 
of the real thing. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the settlement, Wal-Mart also agreed to donate its  
remaining counterfeit Tommy Hilfiger clothes to a charity selected 
by the clothing manufacturer. 
</P>
<P>
	Tommy Hilfiger said the merchandise would be distributed in  
Third World countries and elsewhere, such as the Yugoslavian 
province of Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart's new independent inspector will examine clothing for  
authenticity, the company said in a brief statement. The retailer 
said it also will require merchandise invoices to be tracked from 
the manufacturers to the sales floor. 
</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart had said it purchased the Tommy Hilfiger merchandise  
from third-party distributors and believed it was authentic. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wal-Mart has no interest in carrying non-authentic products,''  
the Bentonville-based retailer said in a statement. ``Recently, we 
have made improvements in how local purchases are made, including 
additional training for our buyers and field operations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, Wal-Mart agreed to a permanent injunction against  
knowingly or intentionally infringing on Tommy Hilfiger's 
trademarks. But last fall, a federal judge held Wal-Mart in 
contempt of court for continuing to sell counterfeit Tommy Hilfiger 
clothes. 
</P>
<P>
	Tommy Hilfiger claimed Wal-Mart -- which had fiscal 1999 sales of  
$138 billion -- was selling fake Tommy Hilfiger T-shirts and socks 
over the Internet and selling counterfeit ladies T-shirts at Sam's 
Wholesale Clubs. 
</P>
<P>
	Joel Horowitz, Hilfiger's chief executive officer, said the  
settlement should make the public aware that fake products are sold 
even beyond city sidewalks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many people don't realize that counterfeiting exists not just  
at the level of the street vendor, but also in large retail 
chains,'' he said. ``We will continue to pursue, and are pursuing 
right now, other retailers who buy in the secondary market and look 
the other way while counterfeit goods are shipped into their 
stores.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He did not identify those retailers.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
