<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU Panel OKs British Beef Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Union's executive  
Commission cleared the way today for resumption of British beef 
imports on Aug. 1, ending a three-year ban imposed after an 
outbreak of mad cow disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Lifting the trade blockade means most British beef can be  
exported again, and will trigger a major marketing campaign 
designed to regain lost sales estimated to have cost the industry 
$2.37 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The EU Commission voted to clear British beef for export  
following final approval from EU veterinary experts. 
</P>
<P>
	``What has changed is very clear. First of all, we have got  
positive advice from our scientists,'' the EU's Agriculture 
Commissioner Franz Fischler said on the British Broadcasting Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	``Secondly, we did a lot of inspections in the United Kingdom  
and the results are now all positive, so it is justified now to 
lift the ban. If I wouldn't be convinced about that, then I would 
not vote in favor to lift the ban,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain welcomed the EU decision.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is a very important step to bringing British beef back to  
markets across the world,'' a spokeswoman for the British Ministry 
of Agriculture said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ben Gill, the president of the National Farmers' Union said  
``obviously we are enormously pleased at today's announcement as it 
means we can start work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``But things will not happen overnight. This decision is long  
overdue but it is much needed when the industry is in the depths of 
depression. We must now work to restore confidence in British 
beef,'' Gill said. 
</P>
<P>
	British beef will still be subject to strict precautions.  
</P>
<P>
	All meat for export must be de-boned and come from cattle born  
after Aug. 1, 1996, when a ban came into force on the feeding to 
animals of meat and bone-meal. Meat from cattle more than 30 months 
old will not be sold overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	Northern Irish beef exports were allowed to resume last year  
because the province has a sophisticated computerized cattle 
monitoring and checking system. 
</P>
<P>
	The ban was imposed in March 1996 following an outbreak in  
Britain of mad cow disease, or bovine spongiform encephalopathy, 
and after medical researchers cited evidence of a link between the 
disease and the fatal human brain ailment, Creutzfeldt-Jacob 
disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Portugal is the only other European country still forbidden to  
export beef, a ban that was extended by the EC last week until 
August 2000. Portugal has complained that the ban is 
discriminatory. 
</P>
<P>
	The European Commission runs the day-to-day affairs of the  
15-nation union, proposes EU law and enforces its implementation 
across Europe. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
