<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Slower Growth Seen for Health Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Health care spending is projected to grow more  
slowly in the next decade than previously expected. 
</P>
<P>
	The revised projection is due largely to decreased Medicare  
spending last year and slower growth projections for both private 
and Medicare spending in the latter part of the next decade, 
according to a study released Tuesday by the Health Care Financing 
Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the downward revision, national health spending still is  
expected to double by 2008 to $2.2 trillion, up from $1.1 trillion 
in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The new projections show the rate of annual growth slows to an  
average of 6.5 percent for the 1997-2007 decade. Last year's 
calculations had projected a 7 percent yearly average growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Medicare spending is projected to grow just 4.5 percent a year  
over the 1997-2000 period, compared to 5.1 percent foreseen in last 
year's figures, the study said. 
</P>
<P>
	The study indicates that national health spending growth will  
accelerate through 2000, due mostly to an acceleration in the 
private-sector. That reverses the current trend of higher public 
spending, and the reversal is expected to be more significant than 
anticipated last year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 11:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IBM Pension Plan Under Scrutiny </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) -- A controversial change in IBM's pension  
plan, which many employees complain robs older workers of benefits 
on which they had relied, is getting congressional scrutiny. 
</P>
<P>
	Eleven members of Congress suggest that the company's pension  
changes amount to age discrimination and they asked the Internal 
Revenue Service this week to look into it. 
</P>
<P>
	Although they are seeking review of all ``cash balance plans,''  
the congressmen were prompted by the changes at IBM, which took 
effect July 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given the serious and unresolved age discrimination questions  
that exist, the (Internal Revenue) Service should not bless these 
arrangements,'' Rep. Bernard Sanders, I-Vt., wrote in a letter 
signed by 10 others. ``To do so not only jeopardizes public law and 
policy, but also provides a taxpayer subsidy for possibly illegal 
conversions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A fixed benefit plan, which IBM scrapped, provides a fixed  
monthly income based on how long a person works for a company. That 
is of greatest benefit to workers who have spent most of their 
career with the same company. They accrue their greatest benefits 
as they near retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	In a cash balance plan, employers contribute a set percentage of  
employees' pay annually to individual accounts. The accounts grow 
as a worker stays with a company, but the employee can take the 
money when leaving the company. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM said it opted for the new plan because so many workers in  
its industry now switch jobs so frequently. The cash balance plan 
is more attractive to such employees because they don't lose any 
benefits if they change jobs and they don't have to wait until the 
end of their careers for most of them to accrue, IBM said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The new plan is designed to be more competitive in order to  
allow IBM to attract and keep a larger pool of talented people,'' 
spokesman Phillip Bergman said in a statement. ``This was necessary 
because of the changing demographics of the company and realities 
of the employment market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer groups and others complain, however, that a cash  
balance plan actually hurts older workers because it provides them 
with less in benefits than the old defined benefit plan did. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM tried to accommodate those workers by allowing those closest  
to retirement to stay in the old plan and giving other experienced 
employees enhancements in the new one. 
</P>
<P>
	The congressmen agree with the consumer groups and argue that it  
is the IRS's job to investigate. Until it does, the congressmen 
want the IRS to stop approving the tax benefits of cash balance 
plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``On its face, it seems to me that there is a real question  
about the legality of IBM's actions,'' Sanders sad. ``Older workers 
who have loyally served IBM for 20 or 25 years are clearly being 
discriminated against.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 19:50:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boston Votes To End School Busing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A generation after Boston erupted in violence over  
court-ordered busing to desegregate public schools, the school 
board voted Wednesday to end busing in a city where the vast 
majority of pupils are now minorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``Underlying all of this is a dose of good old common sense that  
says `Let's move on. It's not the '70s. It's not the '80s. It's the 
end of the '90s,''' said Superintendent Thomas Payzant, flanked at 
an earlier news conference by three dozen parents, politicians and 
community leaders -- black and white. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boston school board voted 5-2 to end busing in a city where  
much has changed since the 1974 federal court order that forced the 
city to bus white students into black neighborhoods and vice versa. 
</P>
<P>
	The order sparked huge protests, staining the city's reputation  
as white parents hurled rocks and epithets at buses that brought 
black children into their neighborhoods, then refused to let their 
own attend black schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, with whites having pulled out of the city in past years  
and a burgeoning immigrant population having moved in, the school 
system has become 85 percent minority. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, a group of white parents filed a lawsuit alleging  
that the busing policy discriminates against their children by 
denying them access to their chosen schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a proposal put forth by Payzant, Boston parents would  
still get to choose where they want to send their children to 
school. Race, however, will not be a consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	The school department would evaluate other criteria when  
deciding which students attend which schools: the proximity of the 
child's home to the school; whether he or she has any siblings 
there; and the results of a yearly school choice lottery. 
</P>
<P>
	Some parents and community leaders expressed anger at  
Wednesday's meeting because they believed the committee was giving 
up in the face of litigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we are giving up only because we have a threat of losing a  
lawsuit, then shame on us,'' Rep. Gloria Fox, D-Boston said at the 
meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, Boston Mayor Thomas M. Menino said racial issues have  
distracted the city from what should be its main goal: improving 
teaching and student learning. 
</P>
<P>
	The policy would take effect in the fall of 2000.  
</P>
<P>
	Busing in the transportation sense would still exist. There  
aren't enough neighborhood schools to allow every one of the city's 
63,000 students to walk, and some parents would opt to send their 
children to schools across town. 
</P>
<P>
	Menino has promised to build six new neighborhood schools in the  
most impoverished areas of the city that need them most. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said the proposed change would not significantly  
change the racial breakdown of the schools because the city's 
school population is now about 85 percent minority -- 49 percent 
black, 26 percent Hispanic and 9 percent Asian. 
</P>
<P>
	Only a few of the city's 129 schools would end up with a mostly  
white student body, Payzant said. 
</P>
<P>
	A quarter-century ago, about 48 percent of the city's school  
children were minority. Back then, schools were either entirely 
white or black. 
</P>
<P>
	State Sen. Dianne Wilkerson, who represents some of the city's  
predominantly black areas, said Boston still has much work to do in 
ensuring that all its schools are of equal caliber. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, she said, the mere fact that blacks and whites were  
together endorsing the new proposal shows how much the city has 
changed over 25 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 17:40:16 </DATE_TIME>
