<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonanno Attends TV Taping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Retired New York mob boss Joseph Bonanno  
attended a private showing of a TV series based on his life. 
</P>
<P>
	``I come here for the good people who come here to honor me,''  
the 94-year-old Bonanno said Monday night at a theater where 
several hundred friends and family members had gathered for an 
advance screening of ``Bonanno: A Godfather's Story,'' a Showtime 
miniseries that will air July 25 and 26. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first publicized appearance in four years for the man  
who ruled one of New York's five Mafia families until he 
relinquished power in the late 1960s. 
</P>
<P>
	In his 37 years in the top ranks of organized crime, Bonanno was  
never convicted of anything more serious than obstructing justice. 
That was in 1980 for obstructing a grand jury investigation of his 
sons, Bill and Joseph Jr. The elder Bonanno served less than 18 
months in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	A year later, after his autobiography helped propel a federal  
investigation, a judge imprisoned Bonanno for nearly 14 months on a 
civil contempt charge for refusing to testify about the secret, 
national commission he helped create to resolve disputes between 
crime families. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 08:40:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Carnival Admits Sex Accusations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Carnival Cruise Lines has disclosed that its  
crew members were accused of sexual assault 62 times in a five-year 
span ending last summer -- or just about once per month, The New 
York Times reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The number, included in court papers filed Tuesday in Miami, is  
the first such public disclosure by a cruise line, the newspaper 
said. Such ships are often registered abroad and safety figures 
aren't reported to U.S. authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	Carnival, the world's largest cruise company, said it had  
investigated the 62 incidents, ending last August, but did not 
release details. The alleged attacks involved passengers and 
employees. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawyer for the cruise line, a subsidiary of Carnival  
Corporation in Miami, said the accusations were taken seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any allegation would be taken seriously, but do these  
statistics suggest that Carnival ships are unsafe? Absolutely 
not,'' said Curtis Mase, the lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	In November, Carnival responded to accusations that it covered  
up assault claims by saying it is ``at least 10 times more likely 
for a sexual assault to occur in a small town in America than on a 
cruise ship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Accused crew members are sometimes put ashore at the next port  
with air fare to get home, the Times reported, and industry lawyers 
are flown to the ship to question accusers. The cruise lines 
aggressively contest lawsuits and insist on secrecy as a condition 
of settling. 
</P>
<P>
	There are also jurisdictional disputes and questions.  
</P>
<P>
	The papers are part of a lawsuit against the company by a former  
employee who said she was attacked by an officer aboard a Carnival 
ship last August. 
</P>
<P>
	The man has been indicted on aggravated sexual assault charges,  
the Times said, but he remains in Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	9  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 11:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wholesale Prices Fall 0.1 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Prices at the wholesale level unexpectedly  
declined last month while consumers' spending slowed dramatically. 
With more news like this, the Federal Reserve may be content to 
remain on the sidelines and not push interest rates higher this 
year,economists said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 0.1 percent decline in the Producer Price Index -- which  
measures inflation pressures before they reach the consumer -- was 
the first decline in four months and reflected a dip in energy 
prices, the Labor Department said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	And, the tiny 0.1 percent June increase in retail sales, which  
accounts for one-third of total economic activity, followed a hefty 
1.2 percent gain in sales in May, the Commerce Department said in a 
separate report. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1 percent drop in sales of cars and trucks, the biggest  
decline in this area since March, was the main factor slowing 
overall retail sales in June. 
</P>
<P>
	The absence of inflationary pressures at the wholesale level  
combined with the sharp slowing in consumer demand should ease 
concerns at the Federal Reserve that a runaway economy will push 
inflation higher, some economists said. 
</P>
<P>
	``By themselves the reports can be viewed as putting less  
pressure on the Fed to tighten further,'' said Mark Zandi, an 
economist with Regional Financial Associates. 
</P>
<P>
	But there will be additional economic data between now and the  
next Fed meeting on August 24 that could influence the central 
bank's decision making, including Thursday's closely watched report 
on the Consumer Price Index, which measures inflation at the 
consumer level. 
</P>
<P>
	``Perhaps (Federal Reserve Chairman Alan) Greenspan has already  
done his work and pending tomorrow's CPI report might decide to 
take the rest of the summer off,'' said Oscar Gonzalez, an 
economist with John Hancock. Inflation at the wholesale level 
``remains as quiet as a sleepy child in a hammock on a lazy summer 
day,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	If the other economic reports show a similar performance, ``the  
Fed can remain on hold'' at its August meeting, said Gerald Cohen, 
a Merrill Lynch economist, who called both government reports 
``market friendly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fed officials went on alert two months ago when prices at both  
the wholesale level and the retail level posted huge increases 
reflecting big hikes in energy costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve increased a key interest rate for the first  
time in two years on June 30, but at the time the Fed indicated 
that the quarter-point raise might be all that was needed to slow 
the economy enough to keep inflation contained. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, energy prices dipped 0.3 percent, reflecting a 1.9  
percent fall in gasoline prices. Energy prices retreated in May and 
June after a whopping 5.1 percent increase in April. 
</P>
<P>
	The drop in auto sales dampened total retail sales, which rose  
to a seasonally adjusted $243.3 billion in June -- an increase of 
just 0.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Taylor, chief economist of the National Automobile Dealers  
Association, said the sales drop reflects a shift in consumer 
buying to cars with lower sticker prices and away from 
higher-priced sports utility vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	It also reflects big decreases in car prices stemming from  
foreign competition and efforts by dealers to clear showrooms for 
new models, economists said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the so-called core rate of inflation at the wholesale  
level -- excluding the volatile food and energy sectors -- fell 0.2 
percent in June. 
</P>
<P>
	The drop in the core rate of inflation reflected a big, 1.3  
percent fall in the price of passenger cars, the biggest reversal 
since January's 1.4 percent dip, and a 0.7 percent decline in the 
category that includes sport utility vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Food costs were up 0.4 in June led by a 8.2 percent increase in  
beef prices -- the biggest one-month jump since an 8.8 percent 
increase in October 1985. The big beef increase, however, was 
partially offset by a 5.2 percent drop in pork prices, the biggest 
decline in 11 months. Vegetable prices were up, while fruit prices 
went down. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 13:40:27 </DATE_TIME>
