<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 08:52:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Hard-Liners Stage Rally in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- Hard-line Iranian clerics  
mobilized tens of thousands of supporters at a rally today to 
counter six days of pro-democracy demonstrations and unrest on a 
scale unseen in Iran in two decades. 
</P>
<P>
	A senior Iranian cleric said at the rally in Tehran that  
pro-reform protesters who damaged public property during the 
previous demonstrations would be tried as enemies of the state, a 
charge punishable by death. 
</P>
<P>
	Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, the country's supreme leader who is  
allied with the hard-liners, has sought to deflect blame for the 
days of protests by accusing the United States and the ``mean and 
wretched enemies of Islam'' of fomenting trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	Iran's state-run television, monitored in Dubai, broadcast live  
pictures of today's rally in the Iranian capital and said about one 
million people took part. 
</P>
<P>
	The figure could not be independently confirmed, but pictures  
showed the area overflowing with people, including women in black 
Islamic robes, chanting slogans and waving Iran's flags. Their 
number appeared to be in the tens of thousands. 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses said few in the crowd carried pictures of reformist  
President Mohammad Khatami. Authorities warned Tuesday that no 
other rallies would be allowed today other than the demonstration 
called by the hard-liners. 
</P>
<P>
	Iranian television said many people gathered inside the  
sprawling grounds of Tehran University to show solidarity with 
Khamenei and hear speeches by clerics. Thousands more, unable to 
squeeze in, stood in the streets outside. 
</P>
<P>
	``Death to America, death to hypocrites'' the demonstrators  
chanted. ``Our blood is our gift to our leader,'' others shouted. 
</P>
<P>
	Hassan Rowhani, the deputy chief of Iran's Supreme National  
Security Council, said ``those who destroyed public property and 
went on the rampage and committed aggression against the Islamic 
system will be tried in our courts as mohareb and mofsed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mohareb and mofsed are terms used to identify die-hard opponents  
of the republic. The punishment for anyone found to be mofsed, 
Farsi for corrupt on earth, is death. 
</P>
<P>
	The rally sent a signal that hard-liners are in no mood to give  
in to Khatami, a moderate clergyman and a hero of the student-led 
protesters demanding more freedom. 
</P>
<P>
	Many people held aloft pictures of Khamenei, but none of Khatami  
were seen. 
</P>
<P>
	The pro-reform demonstrations, which have left two people dead  
and scores injured or arrested, mark the first time Iranians have 
taken to the streets en masse since the 1979 Islamic Revolution 
that overthrew the U.S.-backed shah and installed the clergy's 
rule. 
</P>
<P>
	The unrest began when police without authorization stormed a  
Tehran University dormitory on Friday hours after students rallied 
against the banning of a liberal newspaper. One person was killed 
and 20 were injured; hard-line clerics apparently backed the move. 
</P>
<P>
	The government fired two security chiefs and reprimanded a third  
but the punishments failed to appease protesters who have gathered 
every day in Tehran and at least seven other cities to vent anger. 
</P>
<P>
	One demand often heard at the protests has been that Khamenei,  
who has come to represent 20 years of strict and frustrating 
Islamic rule, step down and Khatami be allowed to carry on with his 
social and democratic reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	One protest numbered an estimated 25,000; most have been about  
10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the protesters rampaged after police dispersed them  
with tear gas. They burned empty buses, smashed shop windows and 
tried to burn down the offices of the hard-line Kayhan newspaper 
before they were stopped by police, witnesses said by telephone. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, Khamenei said ``a group of vicious people,  
supported by certain bankrupt political groups and encouraged by 
foreign enemies, have been engaged in ... destruction of people's 
properties.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said ``the mean and wretched enemies of Islam and the  
revolution'' think that Iranians would let them allow the 
``criminal United States'' to dominate Iran. 
</P>
<P>
	But security forces have been ``emphatically instructed to put  
down the corrupt and warring elements,'' he said in the statement 
released today by the official Islamic Republic News Agency, 
monitored in Dubai. 
</P>
<P>
	Khatami also has urged an end to the unrest, fearing that the  
protests will spin out of control and further set back his reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Khatami's May 1997 election held the promise of more freedom for  
Iranians, but he has faced an uphill battle in trying to overcome 
the hard-liners who control the armed forces, police, judiciary, 
Intelligence Ministry and broadcast network. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 08:52:13 </DATE_TIME>
