<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 19:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Adds Drug Deduction to Tax Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A tax deduction for the insurance that some  
Medicare recipients buy to cover prescription costs was added 
Wednesday to an $864 billion tax relief bill by House Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	After fighting off Democratic attempts to add broader Medicare  
and Social Security measures, the House Ways and Means Committee 
then cleared the bill on a 23-13 vote Wednesday night for action by 
the full House, possibly as early as next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would cut income taxes 10 percent across the board,  
reduce capital gains taxes, eventually abolish estate and 
alternative minimum taxes and give people new breaks for education 
and long-term health care. 
</P>
<P>
	The House panel's 11 hours of debate was the latest skirmish  
over how to divide $2.9 trillion in projected budget surpluses 
between tax cuts, safeguarding the two big retirement programs and 
new government spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can give tax relief. We can save Social Security. We can  
save Medicare,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, the House 
committee's chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	But its top Democrat, Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, said the  
bill ``disproportionately benefits the most affluent Americans'' 
and is intended mainly as fodder for the 2000 election. 
</P>
<P>
	``Instead of fiscal responsibility, Republicans chose to make  
political points,'' he charged. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed tax deduction for insurance costs paid by some  
senior citizens to cover prescription drugs was the GOP's first 
official reaction to President Clinton's popular proposal to add a 
drug benefit to Medicare. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Republican plan is contingent upon a passage later this  
year of an overall reform of Medicare -- including a direct drug 
subsidy for the poor -- which faces future insolvency as baby 
boomers retire. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not want to miss this opportunity,'' said Rep. Bill  
Thomas, R-Calif. ``We've put this provision into the tax bill 
contingent upon other action.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats said the measure was simply political cover for  
Republicans who fear being outflanked on Medicare as they push 
their huge tax cut, a bill Democrats say is a waste of time because 
Clinton has already pledged to veto it. 
</P>
<P>
	They attempted to shave roughly $270 billion off the tax cut for  
a more direct Medicare prescription drug benefit, but that was 
defeated on a party-line 23-11 vote as important for its political 
symbolism as anything else. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before we give tax breaks to the richest 10 percent of  
Americans, we should be willing ... to give senior citizens help 
with some of these bills,'' said Rep. Fortney ``Pete'' Stark, 
D-Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	In Baltimore on Wednesday, Clinton said the House GOP tax bill  
``could wreck our economy'' and would consume almost all of the 
non-Social Security surplus over the next decade. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would require, as our economy grows, real cuts in  
education, defense, the environment, research, technology -- the 
kinds of things we have invested more in,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Republicans insisted that the surplus was big enough to  
accommodate a large tax cut while fixing Social Security and 
Medicare and was the best way to prevent a new era of rampant 
federal spending. 
</P>
<P>
	On another symbolic party-line vote, Ways and Means Republicans  
turned back a Democratic effort to delay the entire tax cut until a 
long-term solution to Social Security is in place. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe the American people can see through this and it all  
boils down to one thing: who do you trust?'' said Rep. J. D. 
Hayworth, R-Ariz. 
</P>
<P>
	Moderate Republicans on the committee were able to divert some  
money intended to cut capital gains taxes for corporations into two 
programs supported by Democrats. Both moves were opposed by Archer. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Rep. Nancy Johnson, R-Conn., won approval of an amendment that  
would gradually raise the per capita cap on low income housing tax 
credits from $1.25 to $1.75 at a cost of $3.8 billion over 10 
years. A similar provision is expected in a Senate GOP tax measure. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Rep. Amo Houghton, R-N.Y., amended the bill to extend  
welfare-to-work tax credits for six months longer than the measure 
originally intended, at a cost of $277 million over 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the panel approved an amendment by Reps. Wes  
Watkins, R-Okla., and William Jefferson, D-La., for $389 million in 
tax breaks to benefit independent domestic oil producers suffering 
from economic distress. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
