<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tension Increases Over Mexico Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Political tension appears to be intensifying  
in Mexico's Congress over a controversial bank bailout and results 
of an independent audit of bad loans transferred from banks to the 
government over the past four years. 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition legislators released a variety of documents this week  
linking campaign funding for the ruling Institutional Revolutionary 
Party, or PRI, to illegal bank operations. There also have been 
leaks of the audit's initial findings, claiming that up to $8 
billion of the loans transferred to the government are of illegal 
origin. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Finance Ministry has cited banking secrecy laws  
for its refusal to give auditors access to information on a series 
of loans made by Banco Union, a bankrupt bank taken over by the 
government in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputies from the opposition National Action Party, or PAN,  
argue that the audit of Banco Union could clarify a series of 
illegal operations made by its former owner, Carlos Cabal Peniche, 
to fund PRI political campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	Cabal Peniche, who purchased Banco Union from the government in  
the early 1990s, is facing an extradition trial in Australia over 
an alleged $700 million fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday, PAN legislators gave the auditors documents from a  
government probe into a PRI trust managed by Banco Union to fund 
the 1994 gubernatorial campaign of Roberto Madrazo in southern 
Tabasco state. Legislators said Banco Union also was involved in 
funding the campaign of President Ernesto Zedillo in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The independent auditors were hired by Mexico's Congress  
following 1998 legislation to consolidate about $65 billion in bad 
bank assets as public domestic debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Fauzi Hamdam, a PAN congressman who designed the bank rescue  
legislation, said Congress will present a formal complaint to 
Zedillo on the Finance Ministry's denial to open Banco Union's 
books. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Zedillo supports the ministry's attempts to block access to  
the Banco Union files, then we will request the Supreme Court issue 
a constitutional ruling on the subject,'' Hamdam said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the congressional agreement, only loans of legal origin  
are to be assumed by the government's new bank deposit insurance 
agency, known as IPAB. Official results of the audit will be 
submitted to Congress on July 19. Public release of the probe is 
expected to take place July 23. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
