<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Wants Khmer Rogue Tribunal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) -- Despite delays in sending U.N. legal  
experts to help set up a genocide tribunal for Khmer Rouge leaders, 
the top U.N. envoy to Cambodia insisted Wednesday that the world 
body still supports such a trial. 
</P>
<P>
	The assurances follow missed deadlines for U.N. experts to help  
establish a controversial tribunal where Khmer Rouge leaders would 
be tried in Cambodia's chaotic, often corrupt courts, aided by 
foreign prosecutors and judges to ensure that international 
standards of justice are met. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas Hammarberg, the U.N. secretary-general's special envoy to  
Cambodia, said in a letter Wednesday in The Cambodia Daily that the 
legal mission would arrive by early August. They were originally 
supposed to arrive in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Hammarberg said the U.N. Office of Legal Affairs is still  
analyzing the implications of the so-called mixed trial, which is a 
compromise after Prime Minister Hun Sen refused to allow the 
creation of an independent U.N. tribunal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Khmer Rouge caused the deaths of as many as 1.7 million  
people when they ruled Cambodia from 1975-79. The long guerrilla 
war they launched after being driven from power by a Vietnamese 
invasion ended last year with the surrender of their last fighters. 
</P>
<P>
	In exchange for making peace, Hun Sen has allowed most of the  
surviving Khmer Rouge leaders to live freely, though he has said he 
would bring them to trial -- but only in Cambodian courts, which he 
has bent to his will in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	Hammarberg said in his letter that the U.N. secretariat has  
given the go-ahead for negotiations with the Cambodian government 
to proceed. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a major step that the U.N. secretariat implicitly has  
declared its willingness to support such a trial -- if agreement can 
be reached on its more precise design,'' Hammarberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	Detractors fear a mixed tribunal will set a dangerous precedent  
and make it more difficult to create future international tribunals 
to judge war crimes, crimes against humanity and genocide. 
</P>
<P>
	Its supporters say that a trial in Cambodia is better than no  
trial at all. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
