<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- A truck driver was fatally shot at a  
street barricade Wednesday, the ninth day of a strike by taxi, bus 
and truck drivers against a gasoline price increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Unidentified men in a speeding car opened fire on strikers  
manning a barricade of taxis and trucks in the town of Guabo, 225 
miles southwest of Quito, killing 31-year-old Gruber Aguirre, 
police said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first death in the strike against a 13 percent  
government-decreed gasoline price increase. Gasoline is sold 
through the state-owned company Ecupetrol. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) -- The United States and Nicaragua signed  
a $103.6 million aid agreement Wednesday to help the Central 
American country recover from the devastating damage caused by 
Hurricane Mitch. 
</P>
<P>
	The money will be used for health care, economic programs,  
rebuilding schools, repairing roads and other projects. Most of the 
aid is targeted for northeastern Nicaragua, the area most severely 
affected by the storm. 
</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Mitch killed thousands and caused billions of dollars  
in damage when it struck Central America last fall. The United 
States has approved nearly $1 billion in aid to countries affected 
by that storm and by Hurricane Georges, which struck the Caribbean 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Seven men were killed Wednesday in a shootout  
at a marijuana field in northern Mexico, authorities said. 
Traffickers removed harvested drugs before police arrived on the 
scene. 
</P>
<P>
	The shootout occurred in Higueras de Abuya, 55 miles south of  
Culiacan, the capital of Sinaloa state. 
</P>
<P>
	The bodies were of men between the ages of 17 and 25, including  
two pairs of brothers, said Marcelo Arellano, the state attorney 
general's spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- In the latest high profile case in Mexico  
City's crime wave, a major opposition party leader said he was 
kidnapped, held for three hours and forced to pay $1,175 ransom. 
</P>
<P>
	Jesus Ortega, former secretary-general of the Democratic  
Revolution Party, said three men forced him into a taxi late Monday 
and ordered him to reveal the personal identification numbers for 
his credit cards. When he said he didn't know the numbers, they 
beat him and forced him to call his wife to arrange for the ransom 
payment. He was released early Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ortega said he does not believe the attack was related to his  
political activities. 
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- In the first half of the year, 847  
Colombian civilians were killed in massacres, a 44 percent increase 
over the same period last year, a top human rights official said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Right-wing paramilitary squads were responsible for most of the  
killings, said independent ombudsman Jose Fernando Castro. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the war continues to escalate, the number of massacres will  
probably increase,'' Castro told a press conference in Bogota. 
</P>
<P>
	The paramilitary groups -- originally funded by rich landowners  
and drug traffickers -- were formed in response to extortion and 
kidnappings by leftist rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the rightist militias and guerrillas both regularly target  
civilians they accuse of collaborating with their enemies. 
</P>
<P>
	Castro said the armed factions use mass killings as a tactic to  
drive people from their homes and gain control of their territory. 
Over 308,000 Colombians were displaced by violence in 1998. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
