<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 09:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Questions PBS Funding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Several Republicans on the House Commerce  
Committee have demanded a review of public broadcasting after 
learning that Boston's public television station gave its donor 
list to the Democratic Party earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee postponed a session today at which it had planned  
to debate a bill authorizing release of $525 million in new funds 
to public broadcasters nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	At a subcommittee meeting Tuesday, a May 8 Boston Globe article  
about the list swap was circulated, and several Republican members 
immediately began lining up procedural maneuvers that could 
jeopardize the authorization. 
</P>
<P>
	WGBH-TV had previously admitted giving a list of donors' names  
to the Democratic National Committee, a possible violation of tax 
laws that prohibit public stations from playing political 
favorites. The station received, in turn, a comparable list of 
political contributors to the committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The name swap was discovered after a 4-year-old Massachusetts  
boy received a fund-raising pitch and ``agenda survey'' from the 
Democratic committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Wellesley resident Sam Black, a fan of public TV's purple  
dinosaur Barney, began receiving mail from the Democratic National 
Committee after his mother, Jody Black, 38, donated $40 to WGBH 
last fall in gratitude for their children's programs. She made the 
donation in her name and Sam's. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at WGBH-TV said the station mistakenly gave a few  
thousand names to the committee in exchange for an equal number of 
names. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal was made by new employees who weren't aware of a  
station policy against sharing lists with political or religious 
groups, a WGBH spokewoman said at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans said the list swap fed into old accusations that  
public broadcasting panders to the left. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 10:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Sugar Faces Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- The Philippine sugar industry should  
prepare for greater competition from foreign producers in order to 
survive, a government official said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	As the Philippines and other countries lower trade barriers,  
foreign-produced sugar will flood the market and pressure local 
producers in the years to come, Agriculture Secretary Edgardo 
Angara said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to face the reality that globalization is now the name  
of the game,'' Angara said in a statement to a conference of local 
and foreign sugar producers. ``The best we can do is to prepare for 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sugar is the country's fourth most important crop, next to rice,  
coconut and corn. The Philippines used to be a major sugar 
producer, supplying about 10 percent of the world's needs. 
</P>
<P>
	Angara, however, said years of government neglect and lack of  
initiative by local producers to modernize led to a gradual decay 
of the industry. The conversion of sugar plantations to other uses 
also hurt production, forcing the Philippines to become a net sugar 
importer today. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his department is preparing a master plan to try to  
reverse the sugar industry's decline. 
</P>
<P>
	It has also launched emergency measures, including a farm  
tractor loan program and the establishment of centers to develop 
and distribute disease-resistant and high-yielding cane varieties, 
Angara said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said it is trying to slow the pace of sugar tariff cuts  
pledged by past government trade negotiators. 
</P>
<P>
	Angara said efforts to protect local sugar producers are  
temporary and comply with the World Trade Organization's rules. 
</P>
<P>
	The Philippine sugar industry employs some 556,000 farmers and  
25,000 sugar mill workers, with up to 5 million other people 
directly or indirectly dependent on it. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
