<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dole Downplays Poll Numbers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Elizabeth Dole said Wednesday she hopes to  
keep raising enough money to remain a credible candidate for the 
Republican presidential nomination as one of her rivals, Ohio Rep. 
John Kasich, folded his campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was not able to raise the money, and that's his decision,''  
Dole said of Kasich and his subsequent endorsement of Texas Gov. 
George W. Bush. ``I'm focused on what I'm doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm pleased we led the rest of the candidates enough to be a  
credible candidate,'' Dole said. 
</P>
<P>
	But as Dole walked through a street fair greeting voters and  
munching on fried dough and spinach pastry, there was the question 
whether she also may fall victim to the Bush steamroller. 
</P>
<P>
	In early May, Dole stood as the favorite candidate of 24 percent  
of polled Republicans, to Bush's 42 percent. She has since dropped 
to 8 percent -- good for second place -- while Bush has jumped to 59 
percent, according to the latest CNN/USA Today/Gallup figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Red Cross candidate and wife of the last Republican  
presidential nominee, Bob Dole, wouldn't discuss the falling 
numbers or give a possible explanation -- but not because she 
discredits polls. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let me tell you about the poll that counts. I have  
consistently beaten Al Gore by 12 to 13 percentage points,'' she 
said, referring to the front-runner for the Democratic nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole raised $3.4 million through the first six months of 1999,  
more than any GOP candidate except Arizona Sen. John McCain and 
Bush, who raised $36 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
