<HEADLINE> Amazon.com Has Stake in Sports Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Internet retailer Amazon.com is moving in yet  
another direction, revealing Wednesday that it holds a 49 percent 
stake in an online discount sporting-goods retailer. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com sells books, music, videos and other products and has  
invested in online pharmacy drugstore.com, Internet pet shop 
Pets.com and cyber supermarket HomeGrocer.com. 
</P>
<P>
	Its varied investments will help it develop a massive online  
shopping presence, said Jupiter Communications analyst Fiona 
Swerdlow. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're incredibly well-capitalized, and if their goal is to  
become the online retailer of choice, then they need to be making 
these acquisitions now because the window of opportunity is not 
always going to be open,'' said Ms. Swerdlow. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Curry, a spokesman for Amazon.com, would not disclose the  
value of the investment or if Amazon.com will establish a link to 
Gear.com on its Web site, as it has for Drugstore.com. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry Devenney, spokesman for Gear.com, said the partnership  
with Amazon.com is the start of a marketing effort by the sport 
products retailer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are creating a whole new distribution channel for close-out  
sporting goods,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com officials, seeking investment opportunities, review a  
potential partner's management, customer service record and a 
product or service that provides improved online shopping, Curry 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly with Gear.com, they fire on all three pistons,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gear.com, in business less than a year, offers merchandise at 20  
percent to 90 percent off retail costs. The reduced prices are due 
to overproduction, changes in style or function and orders canceled 
by retailers. All merchandise is new and sold in original 
packaging. 
</P>
<P>
	Both companies are based in Seattle.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
