<HEADLINE> Tour de France Glance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	L'ALPE D'HUEZ, France (AP) -- A look at Wednesday's 10th stage of  
the 86th Tour de France: 
</P>
<P>
	 *STAGE:* A 220.5 kilometers (137.8 miles) between Sestrieres,  
Italy and the French ski resort of L'Alpe d'Huez. 
</P>
<P>
	 *WINNER:* Italy's Giuseppe Guerini, riding for Deutsche Telekom,  
won in 6 hours, 42 minutes, 31 seconds at an average speed of 32.9 
kph (20.6 mph). 
</P>
<P>
	 *HOW OTHERS FARED:* Russian Pavel Tonkov came in second, 21  
seconds off the pace. Spain's Fernando Escartin was third for the 
second day. Switzerland's Alez Zulle was fourth and Lance Armstrong 
fifth, just ahead of Frenchman Richard Virenque. 
</P>
<P>
	 *OVERALL STANDINGS:* Armstrong, holding the yellow jersey,  
extended his lead to a commanding 7 minutes, 42 seconds. Spain's 
Abraham Olano is second, Zulle third. 
</P>
<P>
	 *TOUR TIDBITS:* With the finish line in sight, Guerini collided  
with a fan who tried to get a photograph of him, but failed to pull 
out of the way in time. Guerini picked himself up, and rode on to 
victory -- with an apologetic push from the fan. 
</P>
<P>
	 *QUOTE OF THE DAY:* ``Suddenly, I went from the most beautiful  
moment of my life to the worst,'' Guerini said of his collision 
with the spectator. 
</P>
<P>
	 *NEXT STAGE:* Le Bourg d'Oisans to Saint Etienne, 198.5  
kilometers (124 miles) on Thursday. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
