<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cemetery's Art Is Portal to History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- In this Indianapolis history classroom you  
won't find books or desks. The lessons emerge from Crown Hill 
Cemetery's 555 park-like acres, where nearly 190,000 people are 
buried. 
</P>
<P>
	From pioneers to a president, the rich and poor are side by  
side. Each has a story to tell. 
</P>
<P>
	The inscriptions and fine artwork adorning the monuments provide  
the cultural portal through which visitors can look back in time to 
learn not only about an individual, but how society viewed death 
and memorialization. 
</P>
<P>
	The cemetery, which opened in 1864 in what was then a rural area  
northwest of the city, got its name from the glacier-formed knoll 
considered at the time to be Marion County's ``crowning summit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The shady grounds and large, grassy areas became a favorite  
place for visitors to stroll and even to picnic. 
</P>
<P>
	``People had a different relationship with death. It was a part  
of life; it wasn't scary,'' said associate professor Eleanor 
Weinel, who studies cemetery art and teaches architecture classes 
at the University of Oklahoma. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the Victorian era, the sentimental attachments to people  
and places were intense. In the 20th century, we don't feel 
attached, so it starts to be a place that makes us nervous,'' she 
added. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's visitors pass through the same elaborate, three-arch  
stone gate that greeted those who entered near the 34th Street 
Waiting Station at the turn of the century. The tree-lined roads 
criss-cross burial sections that contain the graves of Civil War 
soldiers and such notables as President Benjamin Harrison, poet 
James Whitcomb Riley and bank robber John Dillinger. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the markers and monuments are as elaborate and unique as  
they are beautiful. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was not unusual for prominent families to have monuments  
designed by the area's leading artists and sculptors,'' said Crown 
Hill tour guide Tom Davis. ``People in the Victorian era generously 
decorated their memorials to their loved ones and used symbols to 
express the things that words alone could not,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	As Davis walks between the rows of monuments, gently setting  
toppled stones back on their bases, he tells what he knows as fact 
and imagines what might have been. A broken column pays tribute to 
a life cut short, doves symbolize love and purity and the 
life-sized angels with outstretched wings direct the way to a 
heavenly afterlife. 
</P>
<P>
	Other symbols are more personal. While Indiana's climate has  
destroyed the luster of a white marble monument, there's no doubt 
an open Bible rests atop the stone pulpit of a minister. A 
painter's palette nearby suggests its owner found pleasure putting 
a brush to canvas. 
</P>
<P>
	Obelisks resembling the Washington Monument tower over some of  
the smaller memorials, but Davis said it's not known which statue 
or monument is the tallest. 
</P>
<P>
	``I keep wanting to get some trigonometry class out here to  
figure it out, but so far that hasn't happened,'' Davis quipped. 
</P>
<P>
	Crown Hill officials consider the monument of  
turn-of-the-century Butler University professor Albertina Allen 
Forrest one of the cemetery's most beautiful works of art. The 
elaborate tribute contains a bronze statue of a woman in mourning 
that was created by noted Austrian sculptor Rudolf Schwarz. 
</P>
<P>
	Schwarz also produced the ``War'' and ``Peace'' sculptures at  
the base of the Soldiers and Sailors monument on the Circle in 
downtown Indianapolis. The bronze portrayal of Indiana Governor 
Oliver Morton displayed on the east side of the Statehouse also is 
the work of Schwarz. 
</P>
<P>
	Examples of classical, Romanesque, Gothic, Egyptian and modern  
architecture are found in the cemetery's 57 family-owned 
mausoleums. The stately columns and intricate carvings draw the 
interest of even casual observers. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunlight streams through the colorful stained-glass windows  
inside many of the structures, but that's not apparent until 
visitors peek through the ornate doors that remain locked for 
protection. 
</P>
<P>
	``The exterior (of the mausoleum) is the object for the  
appreciation of other people; the interior is very private and for 
the family and people involved,'' Weinel said. 
</P>
<P>
	The cemetery's Gothic Chapel, patterned after a European  
cathedral, was designed by noted architect Diedrich A. Bohlen and 
was built in 1875. The chapel is still used for funerals. 
</P>
<P>
	One president, three vice presidents, 10 Indiana governors, 14  
U.S. senators and dozens of other famous politicians, poets, 
artists, musicians, and business owners lie within Crown Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	``I take visitors to Crown Hill because it's a really beautiful  
spot and everyone who was anybody in Indianapolis history is buried 
there,'' said William Selm, an instructor at Herron School of Art. 
</P>
<P>
	Not all the memorials at Crown Hill are elaborate, but that  
doesn't lessen their significance or diminish the lives of those 
who lived in relative obscurity. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most people go through life and aren't great people. They're  
born, live a life, do some things and die. Those markers are 
monuments for the regular guy,'' Selm added. 
</P>
<P>
	The mixture is what makes the cemetery an interesting place to  
visit and over the years, thousands have done just that. In 
mid-century, cemetery officials estimated as many people visited 
Crown Hill on Memorial Day as attended the Indianapolis 500. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some cemeteries may have more historical significance, but not  
too many have the variety of Crown Hill,'' Davis said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
