<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Earns $2.48B in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- Ford Motor Co., profiting from robust car  
and truck sales in the United States, reported Wednesday its 
second-quarter operating earnings rose 4 percent to $2.48 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	But the world's second-largest automaker said it was still  
struggling in Europe and South America. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford's operating earnings translated to $2 a share and compared  
with $2.38 billion, or $1.91 a share, during the same period a year 
ago. Sales came to $42.3 billion, up 13 percent from $37.3 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Overall, the numbers were quite strong,'' said analyst Gary  
Lapidus of Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co. ``Obviously, it's all North 
America -- the North American results were better than people 
expected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The results beat the average estimate of $1.95 of analysts  
surveyed by First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford had net earnings of $2.34 billion, or $1.89 a share,  
including a one-time profit reduction of $146 million related to 
its January acquisition of the car making unit of Sweden's Volvo 
AB. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford said its automotive operations earned just under $2 billion  
in North America, up 19 percent from the year-ago period. U.S. car 
and light truck sales are on track to break the 1986 industry 
record of nearly 16.1 million vehicles; in the first half, sales 
were running at an annual rate of 16.7 million. 
</P>
<P>
	With a strong lineup of popular pickups and sport utility  
vehicles, Ford said it is well-positioned to continue profiting 
from the strong U.S. market. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are so many positive factors at work in the U.S. economy  
right now,'' said Jac Nasser, Ford's president and chief executive. 
``We're confident vehicle sales will remain strong into 2000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	News from overseas was not so bright.  
</P>
<P>
	Operating earnings in Europe totaled $214 million, down 31  
percent from the $310 million earned a year ago. In South America, 
Ford lost $120 million, compared with earnings of $14 million a 
year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford did poorer than expected in Europe, while South America was  
a disaster, Lapidus said. Ford said its biggest problems were in 
Brazil, where industry sales declined 20 percent in the first half. 
W. Wayne Booker, Ford's vice chairman and chief financial officer, 
forecast no improvement before 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Booker said the addition of Volvo earnings did not affect its  
European results because the unit was ``about break-even.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earnings improvements in the highly competitive European market  
will be gradual over the very long term, Booker said. He 
acknowledged that without Volvo, Ford's European market share would 
have declined in the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong initial sales of Ford's new Focus subcompact and a better  
performance by Jaguar were not enough to completely offset slower 
sales of the aging Fiesta subcompact and Mondeo compact sedans in 
Europe. Lapidus said the Ka minicar also has been selling more 
slowly than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``All the other manufacturers have been very aggressive with new  
product over the past two years, and Ford has not in Europe,'' 
Lapidus said. ``The Focus is doing fine, it's just not enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ford stock fell 56 cents to $52.94 on the New York Stock  
Exchange. So far this year, Ford's stock is down 7 percent, clearly 
a frustration to Ford management. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wish I had the answer to that,'' Booker said.  
</P>
<P>
	Some on Wall Street complain that while they like Nasser's  
long-term strategy, they fear Ford doesn't have a clear short-term 
plan to improve results overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	``The quarter is a reminder that despite what is clearly a  
compelling vision to transform the company longer-term, there are 
some near-term challenges that Ford needs to address,'' said 
analyst John Casesa of Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Others have questioned Nasser's long-term focus on expanding  
Ford into auto-related businesses, such as its recent acquisitions 
of the Kwik-Fit service chain in Europe and auto-parts recycling 
operations in the United States. Booker denied that Ford was paying 
less attention to its automotive business. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford said it was making continued progress in cutting costs,  
which declined $300 million in the second quarter and $400 million 
for the entire first half. Ford's annual goal is $1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	First-half operating earnings totaled $4.32 billion, up 11  
percent from the $3.9 billion in the first six months of 1998. 
Revenues totaled $80.2 billion, up 8.5 percent from $73.9 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	General Motors Corp. plans to report its second-quarter results  
Tuesday, followed by DaimlerChrysler AG July 29. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
