<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House To Vote on Mining Restrictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House voted Wednesday to uphold Clinton  
administration efforts to limit mining operations on federal lands, 
putting the chamber on a collision course with the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	In an issue pitting Western mining interests against  
environmentalists, the House voted 273-151 to require mining 
companies using public lands to heed a 1997 Interior Department 
ruling limiting the size of their waste dumps to five acres per 
claim. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats voted almost solidly for the limits, while more than  
one in three Republicans broke with their party to support acreage 
limits as well. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate version of the legislation would let companies ignore  
that ruling, which was an interpretation of the 1872 law that still 
governs mining for gold and other hard-rock minerals on federal 
lands. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry supporters say the five-acre limitation on waste sites  
is too small for modern techniques, which use chemicals like 
cyanide on vast piles of rock from open-pit mines. Opponents say 
the provision is the only pro-environmental one in the entire 
127-year-old law, which lets companies purchase federal lands for 
$2.50 an acre or lease them for $100 annually per 20-acre claim. 
</P>
<P>
	``The public domain is a public trust, and there is an effort  
today to undermine that public trust,'' said Rep. Nick Rahall, 
D-W.Va., who sponsored the amendment with Reps. Christopher Shays, 
R-Conn., and Jay Inslee, D-Wash. ``It is a land grab, a land grab 
at public expense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But opponents of the amendment said it was based on a  
misinterpretation of law by overzealous bureaucrats that would cost 
jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, said the Interior  
Department has ``a proven track record of hostility toward mining'' 
and its officials are ``working feverishly to impose their 
unorthodox views on mining before they leave office.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The mining language was an amendment to a $14 billion measure  
financing the Interior Department and federal cultural programs 
next year. The bill contains well below what President Clinton has 
requested for purchasing land for federal and state parks, 
protecting Florida's Everglades, and energy conservation. 
</P>
<P>
	By voice vote, the House voted to trim $140 million from the  
legislation, part of a continuing effort by Republican leaders to 
satisfy conservatives demanding spending cuts. The reductions would 
come from clean coal and land acquisition programs plus a 0.48 
percent cut in the entire measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The cuts are what ``we have to do to get where we have to be,''  
said House Appropriations Committee Chairman Bill Young, R-Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., chided Republicans for yielding to  
conservatives ``who detest government.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other votes Wednesday, the House:  
</P>
<P>
	--Voted 243-180 to add $13 million to a program that helps  
low-income people insulate and otherwise winterize their homes, 
bringing it to $133 million, the same as this year. It also voted 
225-198 against eliminating a new requirement that states provide 
$1 for every $3 they receive from the program. 
</P>
<P>
	--By 217-207, rejected an attempt by Democrats and moderate  
Republicans to add $10 million each for the National Endowment for 
the Arts and the National Endowment for the Humanities. The House 
also defeated a conservative effort to cut the arts endowment by $2 
million by 300-124. The bill would provide NEA with $98 million 
next year, the same as this year and $52 million less than Clinton 
wanted. The NEH would get $111 million, the same as this year and 
$39 million below Clinton's request. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
