<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AMD Reports 2nd-Quarter Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Advanced Micro Devices Inc. president  
and chief operating officer S. Atiq Raza resigned Wednesday as the 
chipmaker released second-quarter losses, stemming from tough 
competition from Intel Corp. and low sales of a benchmark chip. 
</P>
<P>
	Raza cited personal reasons for his resignation, saying that his  
departure was not related to the company's financial problems. ``My 
decision to leave AMD was a difficult one,'' he said. ``I have 
enjoyed the challenges of helping to restore competition in the 
microprocessor market. 
</P>
<P>
	Raza's unexpected announcement came as AMD reported a loss of  
$162 million, or $1.10 per share, for the three months ended June 
27. The loss was less than the $1.26 predicted by industry analysts 
surveyed by First Call. 
</P>
<P>
	In the year-ago period, AMD lost $64.6 million, or 45 cents per  
share. 
</P>
<P>
	Including a one-time, after-tax gain of $259 million from the  
sale of its subsidiary Vantis, as well some charges, AMD recorded 
net income of $79.9 million for the quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Quarterly revenues totaled $595 million, up from $526 million in  
the year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	Several weeks ago, AMD warned that it would suffer a significant  
second-quarter loss because production problems with its most 
popular microprocessor, the K6, would hurt sales. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, W.J. Sanders III, chairman and chief executive  
officer of AMD, said the company's short-term future rested with 
its new Athlon processor. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the face of Intel's intensifying aggression in the consumer  
sector of the PC market, where our AMD-K6-2 processor family ... 
has achieved substantial market share in both desktop and portable 
PCs, further gains in unit market share or revenue growth are 
unlikely,'' he said. ``The key to resuming growth and expanding 
margins is the recently introduced AMD Athlon processor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The world's first seventh-generation processor, Athlon is the  
highest-performance processor for PCs available. Initial shipments 
of Athlon processors, including 600-megahertz versions, began in 
June. 
</P>
<P>
	AMD ranks second in the microprocessor market in terms of market  
share, behind Silicon Valley rival Intel. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of AMD rose 93 3/4 cents per share to $18 in advance of the  
earnings report, which was released after the close of Wednesday's 
trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
