<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Railway Suspect Admits Burglary  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Police said today they have evidence linking a  
man suspected to have committed eight killings along railway 
stations in three states to a ninth murder. Angel Maturino 
Resendez, also known as Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, admitted today he 
committed a burglary at one of the killing scenes. Police said 
palmprints found at the scene of the October killing of an elderly 
woman match those of Maturino Resendez, and that he will be charged 
in the death. Maturino Resendez surrendered yesterday, ending a 
six-week manhunt. 

</P>
<P>
	Kasich Pulls Out; Backs Bush  
</P>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Rep. John Kasich today ended his campaign  
for the Republican presidential nomination, short of both cash and 
public support, and endorsed Texas Gov. George W. Bush. ``I wish I 
didn't have to be here today to tell you that I have made a 
decision not to seek the nomination,'' Kasich said. The nine-term 
Ohio congressman said he would not seek re-election to the House. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Visit Moves U.N. Prosecutor  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A top U.N. war crimes prosecutor  
took her first tour today of one of the worst killing fields of 
Kosovo and said she was ``profoundly moved'' by what she saw. 
Louise Arbour visited several dug-up mass graves. Her trip comes 
just a day after British forensic specialists discovered the bodies 
of 11 children shot to death at close range in Celine. War crimes 
investigators have exhumed 57 bodies so far from nine separate 
grave sites in Pristina. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Proposes Prescription Tax Break  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans proposed tax deductions today to  
help some Medicare recipients pay for prescription drugs as they 
resumed pushing their $864 billion, 10-year tax cut through the 
House Ways and Means Committee. Lawmakers provided no information 
on how much the plan would cost, but they said it would be paid for 
from projected federal surpluses. The tax plan, nearly half of 
which is a 10 percent across-the-board cut in income tax rates, 
would be phased in slowly from 1999 to 2009. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Questions PBS Funding  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Several Republicans on the House Commerce  
Committee have demanded a review of public broadcasting after 
learning that Boston's public television station gave its donor 
list to the Democratic Party earlier this year. The committee 
postponed a session today at which it had planned to debate a bill 
authorizing release of $525 million in new funds to public 
broadcasters nationwide. WGBH-TV had previously admitted giving a 
list of donors' names to the Democratic National Committee, a 
possible violation of tax laws that prohibit public stations from 
playing political favorites. 

</P>
<P>
	New Drug Protects Newborns from AIDS  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Scientists in Uganda have discovered a drug  
that is cheaper and more efficient than AZT in helping to lower a 
pregnant woman's chance of spreading AIDS to her newborn. Using the 
drug nevirapine instead of AZT proved 47 percent better in 
protecting babies from AIDS, the U.S. National Institutes of Health 
announced today. Just 13.1 percent of the nevirapine-treated babies 
became infected with HIV, compared with 25.1 percent of the 
AZT-treated babies. The U.S. government funded the Ugandan study as 
part of a hunt for ways to reduce the cost of preventing AIDS in 
the world's poorest countries. 

</P>
<P>
	Study: Carpal Tunnel Symptoms Common  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A new study indicates that more than 14 percent  
of those surveyed were found to have symptoms of carpal tunnel 
syndrome, although only 2.7 percent can be diagnosed with the 
ailment. ``Symptoms of pain, numbness and tingling in the hands are 
common in the general population,'' reported the authors of the 
Swedish study, published in today's Journal of the American Medical 
Association. Carpal tunnel syndrome has been on the rise in 
developed countries with increasing computer-keyboard use, but the 
study shows that two problems are misdiagnosis and the lack of 
consensus on how to treat the condition. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 15  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 15.83 to 11,159.19. Declining issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,465-1,313. The Nasdaq was up 18.13 to 
2,796.36. 

</P>
<P>
	Guerini Wins Tour de France Stage  
</P>
<P>
	L'ALPE D'HUEZ, France (AP) -- Italy's Giuseppe Guerini survived a  
last-minute collision with a spectator to win today's 10th stage of 
the Tour de France, while American Lance Armstrong kept the yellow 
jersey and widened his lead. Armstrong finished fifth but widened 
his overall lead to seven minutes and 42 seconds over Spain's 
Abraham Olano. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
