<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Lighter Side of Business /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DECLINING NET WORTH: There have been plenty of warnings in  
recent years that Baby Boomers aren't saving enough for retirement. 
Metropolitan Life Insurance Co., which tracks Americans' financial 
health, says they also have too much debt and that's lowering their 
net worth. MetLife estimates that boomers outstanding debt is equal 
to 95 percent of their annual personal incomes, and that has 
contributed to a decline in net worth for people age 35 to 54 over 
the past 10 years. Sandra Timmerman, who studies the problems of 
older people for MetLife, attributes boomers' willingness to take 
on more debt to their high confidence in the U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WILLY LOMAN, THE NEXT GENERATION: Fifty years after Arthur  
Miller wrote ``Death of a Salesman,'' not only has a Broadway 
revival of the play won awards, but advertising copy writers have 
figured out an epilogue. A print ad for Pixion software is built 
around Willy Loman's grandson, who, unlike his tragic relative, 
doesn't have to spend his days on the road, trudging around with 
heavy sample cases as he tries to sell his wares to his customers. 
According to this story, the young Loman gets to sit back in his 
chair, never leaving the office, while he shows his products to 
far-flung clients over the Internet. Grandpa's sample case sits 
over in the corner of his office, a reminder of what life was like 
before telecommuting. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BE THE FIRST ON YOUR BLOCK: Worth magazine, which caters to the  
high end of the economic scale, has been scouting around for the 
next generation of high-tech toys for people willing to spend very 
big bucks for the very latest. On Worth's suggested shopping list 
is a new super CD player from Sony that will retail for about 
$5,000. If you want a pricey cell phone, Worth reports that Nokia 
has one that has a calendar, optional vibrating ringer and other 
features, and it'll be yours for $1,000. If it's a car with a hefty 
price tag you want, Worth notes that Aston Martin -- the make driven 
by James Bond -- has a new version of its DB7, able to accelerate 
from zero to 60 mph in under five seconds. That will come in handy 
for a dash to the electronics store when the CD players and cell 
phones go on sale. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
