<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Criticized for Teachers Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Math and science students whose teachers hold  
``emergency'' credentials do no worse on tests than students whose 
teachers are fully certified, all else being equal, say researchers 
critical of plans by President Clinton and some states to end such 
hires. 
</P>
<P>
	``Education is the last remaining field in America where people  
think you can boost quality by tightening the rules and multiplying 
the regulations,'' said Chester E. Finn Jr., president of the 
Thomas Fordham Foundation, a privately run school-reform research 
organization. The foundation on Wednesday released a collection of 
reports criticizing a slate of teacher hiring, training, and 
evaluation trends. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers say students whose teachers have any kind of  
certification (standard, emergency or alternative) outperform 
students whose teachers have no certification or are certified in a 
different subject. Students whose teachers possess a bachelor's or 
master's degree in math outperform other students in math, they 
said, regardless of the teacher's certification. ``This result 
should cast doubt on assertions that standard certification should 
be required of all teachers,'' the reports concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, 44 states require teachers to pass a test to earn a  
license. But the tests, which vary, grant teachers credentials 
based on a range of measures from basic skills to knowledge of a 
specific subject to teaching performance. States often fill 
classroom shortages by allowing teachers to use emergency 
certificates or alternatives. The Education Department is spending 
$1 million to study how states license teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	Finn, a former Reagan administration Education Department  
official, said teacher hiring should be left to local school 
leaders, which he said contradicts the Clinton proposal, outlined 
in this year's State of the Union Address, to make states and 
school districts phase out emergency-certified teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	The reports say teachers have weak verbal and math skills and  
not nearly enough have a college major or minor in the subjects 
they teach. But even some standard state credentials fall short of 
putting better teachers in the classroom, they said. In California, 
Ohio, New York, and Minnesota, approved preparation programs tend 
to have very low entry requirements, no exit requirements and low 
subject content, the researchers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Licensure isn't a regulatory intrusion; it's a standard to  
protect children,'' said Bob Chase, president of the National 
Education Association, the nation's largest teachers union. ``It is 
critical for teachers to know the subject matter and content of 
what they are teaching -- and it is equally critical for them to 
understand how the brain works, how to instruct children with 
different skill levels, and how to keep a classroom full of kids in 
their seats so they can share their content knowledge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, the reports say, states such as Pennsylvania can  
maintain strong alternative certification programs while raising 
academic standards for teachers. Teachers there must take more 
academic courses and fewer education courses, and pass licensure 
exams with higher scores, but college graduates who pass the exams 
may teach under the mentorship of a principal or master teacher 
without attending a school of education. 
</P>
<P>
	``Education interest groups have pushed misguided regulatory  
schemes that will make it even harder for our public schools to 
attract strong teachers into their ranks,'' said Finn. 
</P>
<P>
	Also criticized is a Clinton-backed national program to  
credential ``master'' teachers. Danielle Dunne Wilcox, a researcher 
at Columbia University, says in her report there's no evidence that 
teachers certified by the National Board for Professional Teaching 
Standards are superior to other teachers. Clinton, who wants to 
give the voluntary program another $18.5 million this year, has 
long sparred with congressional Republicans, who see this as a step 
toward mandatory national testing and a departure from local 
control. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fordham report also takes on traditional teachers' colleges.  
Economists Dale Ballou and Michael Podgursky attack the oft-quoted 
analogy comparing education and medicine; if doctors can't treat 
patients without attending medical schools, why let teachers into 
classrooms without first sending them through education school? 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers and education leaders who agree with their  
conclusions suggested alternatives that include: giving would-be 
teachers more access and fewer hurdles, allowing key personnel 
decisions to be made by schools, and judging teachers primarily by 
gains in student learning. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
