<HEADLINE> Stocks turn Lower; Dow Down 43.70 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned lower as concerns about economic  
and political uncertainty overseas outweighed news of strong 
earnings and tame inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 43.70 at 1,1131.32, adding to its 26-point drop on Tuesday. 
The Dow had been up as much as 34 points in early trading today 
before retreating. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also mostly lower.  
</P>
<P>
	Prices fell as some investors took profits on the market's  
recent record-setting rise, which lifted the Dow to a new high on 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks also were hurt down by lingering concerns about Latin  
America's economic situation. The nervousness was set off Monday by 
comments from Argentina's presidential candidates, who hinted at a 
possible moratorium on repayment of the country's debt. That raised 
concerns on Wall Street that U.S. financial services companies 
would suffer losses because of unpaid loans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Plain and simple, the market turned a blind eye to the Latin  
American situation over the last seven or eight months,'' said 
Bryan Piskorowski, market analyst at Prudential Securities. 
``Argentina has served as a reminder that they need to watch the 
situation in Latin America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There were also increasing concern about political tensions in  
Asia after the Chinese government accused Taiwanese President Lee 
Teng-hui of embarking on a doomed attempt to split his island from 
China. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks initially rose after the Labor Department reported the  
Producer Price Index -- which measures inflation pressures before 
they reach the consumer -- fell a smaller-than-expected 0.1 percent 
in June, the first decline in four months. 
</P>
<P>
	Also today, the Commerce Department said retail sales rose just  
0.1 percent in June, a big slowdown from the May increase of 1.2 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Both reports helped ease worries about a potential breakout of  
inflation, which could cause the Fed to raise rates again this year 
to slow U.S. economic growth and keep inflation contained. 
</P>
<P>
	Some stocks rose on positive earnings reports.  
</P>
<P>
	Computer chip maker Intel reported late Tuesday its  
second-quarter earnings jumped 49 percent and the company said it 
expects a strong second half of this year. Intel was up 1 5/16 at 
66 11/16, the most active stock on the Nasdaq Stock Market today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 4.26 at 1,389.30, and  
the Nasdaq composite index was down 2.62 at 2,780.85. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 329.37 million 
shares, down from 356.50 million shares on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 1.46 at 652.18, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 2.13 at 810.20. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
