<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mariners Open $517 Million Ballpark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Finally, Seattle Mariners fans will get to see  
green grass and blue skies. And when the skies turn sodden, they 
get to watch the roof close over their heads. 
</P>
<P>
	Safeco Field, a $517.6 million project featuring a retractable  
roof, kicks off a new era of major league baseball in the Pacific 
Northwest on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	After watching their team play inside for 22 1/2 seasons in the  
tomblike and dingy Kingdome, the Mariners will begin play in their 
new home next to Puget Sound's Elliott Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	The first four home games, including Thursday night's opener  
against the San Diego Padres, are sold out, and tickets for the 
other four games of the first homestand are selling fast. 
</P>
<P>
	When the roof is open, as it's expected to be this week, fans  
can view Seattle's scenic skyline. 
</P>
<P>
	The roof was open for the Mariners' workout Wednesday afternoon,  
and Ken Griffey Jr. peppered home runs to all parts of the 
ballpark. Looking tired after playing in Tuesday night's All-Star 
game in Boston, Griffey waved off reporters who attempted to ask 
him questions about his new home. 
</P>
<P>
	Airplanes flew overhead and trains rumbled along the nearby  
tracks. This time, unlike in the Kingdome, there was no insulation. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of loud,'' Mariners designated hitter Edgar Martinez  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time, the Mariners will have a home field of  
grass, not AstroTurf. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an awesome place,'' said left-hander Jamie Moyer,  
Thursday night's scheduled starter. ``What an amazing place to be a 
part of. It's phenomenal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``What a difference from here and where we played,'' manager Lou  
Piniella said. ``I'll tell you what, when this place gets full, 
there's going to be excitement here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whether Griffey and the team's other sluggers will miss the  
carry and relatively short fences of the Kingdome is another story. 
</P>
<P>
	The park has bigger dimensions than the cozy Kingdome and the  
move across the street is expected to cut the Mariners' prolific 
home run numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Inside the gaps, it's big,'' Martinez said. ``Plus, the ball  
doesn't travel that well. Left field and right field are OK, but 
the gaps are hard to hit them out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the increased fan interest could provide the revenue to  
help keep Griffey and Alex Rodriguez in Seattle when they become 
free agents after the 2000 season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mariners feel they've got a 47,000-seat home now to match  
other recently built stadiums: Camden Yards in Baltimore, Coors 
Field in Denver, Jacobs Field in Cleveland, Bank One Ballpark in 
Phoenix and The Ballpark in Arlington, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I can pitch in the Kingdome and survive, I can pitch  
anywhere,'' Moyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	The stadium is drawing rave reviews. The fans like its features  
and the fact that they won't have to watch baseball indoors 
anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	The stadium's features range from excellent sight lines to its  
concession stands and large number of toilets. 
</P>
<P>
	But the new stadium does comes with controversy.  
</P>
<P>
	Some local fans and officials feel the Mariners' owners are  
trying to renege on their deal with taxpayers, trying for more tax 
revenue to cover $100 million in cost overruns on the ballpark, of 
which $379 million was covered by taxpayers. 
</P>
<P>
	After a three-game series with the Padres, the Mariners will  
face the Arizona Diamondbacks and Randy Johnson, who is scheduled 
to pitch on Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson was an American League Cy Young Award winner, a 20-game  
winner and the author of a no-hitter for the Mariners before he was 
traded to Houston last July 31. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mariners will open at Safeco Field with a five-game losing  
streak and a team ERA of 6.02. They're three games under .500 and 
in third place in the AL West, six games behind first-place Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Could the new park raise morale?  
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't like being indoors all day,'' third baseman Russ  
Davis said. ``This is a beautiful part of the country and you 
should be able to enjoy the weather. I think the fans are going to 
enjoy it a lot more, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seattle had an outdoor park for its first major league team, the  
1969 Seattle Pilots, but Sicks Stadium was strictly a minor league 
ballpark. The team moved to Milwaukee to become the Brewers the 
following season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
