<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Postal Service $1B in Black </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The post office is $1 billion in the black  
three-fourths of the way through its fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	With that cushion, the agency should finish the year close to  
its planned $200 million profit, reports Richard M. Porras, chief 
financial officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Costs traditionally outrun income in the fourth quarter for the  
agency. Last year the post office was $900 million in the red for 
the last three months of its fiscal year, which ends in September, 
spokesman Norm Scherstrom said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	By the end of the third quarter, May 21, the Postal Service had  
expenses of $43.1 billion and income of $44.2 billion for a net of 
$1.062 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The post office raised the price of stamps a penny to 33 cents  
in January in anticipation of rising costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the post office reported that 94 percent of local  
mail was delivered on time in the spring quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	On-time delivery was measured through a series of test letters  
sent by the accounting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers in 465 ZIP codes 
covering about 80 percent of First Class mail delivery. The company 
measured the percentage of letters delivered overnight in 85 
metropolitan areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Top performers at 96 percent were Billings, Mont.; Omaha, Neb.;  
Wichita, Kan.; Sioux Falls, S.D. and Springfield, Mass. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
