<DOCNO> APW19990714.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 04:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fraser To Be Thrashers' Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Atlanta Thrashers have players. Now, they  
have someone to coach them. 
</P>
<P>
	The NHL expansion team called a news conference today to  
introduce Curt Fraser as their first coach, The Associated Press 
learned Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Fraser, who led Orlando to the International Hockey League  
finals twice in the last four years, was chosen from a short list 
that also included former Buffalo coach Ted Nolan and ex-Edmonton 
coach Ron Low. 
</P>
<P>
	The choice of Fraser was confirmed by a source close to the  
team, speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The selection of the 41-year-old Fraser was not a surprise.  
During his first two seasons in Orlando, the Solar Bears' general 
manager was Don Waddell, who now holds the same post with Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	The hiring of a coach was Waddell's last major move before the  
inaugural season begins in October. The team selected its players 
last month in expansion and entry drafts. 
</P>
<P>
	Waddell and Fraser produced an IHL expansion team that reached  
the Turner Cup finals in 1995-96. The Solar Bears were swept by 
Utah in the championship series. 
</P>
<P>
	Orlando returned to the finals this season after becoming the  
first team in IHL history to overcome a 3-0 deficit in a best-of-7 
series. After rallying to beat Detroit for the Eastern Conference 
title, the Solar Bears lost a seven-game series to Houston for the 
league championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Fraser had a record of 192-111-25 in Orlando, the league's  
second-best mark during that four-year span. 
</P>
<P>
	The Thrashers announced an agreement in February to use Orlando  
as their top minor league team and will probably conduct part of 
their first training camp in central Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Before joining the Solar Bears, Fraser spent four seasons with  
the IHL's Milwaukee Admirals -- two as an assistant, two as coach -- 
and one season as coach of the American Hockey League's Syracuse 
Crunch. 
</P>
<P>
	Fraser had a 12-year playing career in the NHL after being  
drafted in the second round by Vancouver in 1978. The left-winger 
scored 193 goals and racked up 1,306 penalty minutes during a 
career that also included stints with Chicago and Minnesota. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 21:10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Mixed in Midday / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The benchmark Tokyo stock index fell slightly  
Thursday morning on profit-taking in the high-technology sector. 
The dollar slipped against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 64.23 points, or 0.35  
percent, to 18,293.63 points at the end of the morning session. On 
Wednesday, the average gained 176.77 points, or 0.97 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.61 yen, down 0.51 yen from late Wednesday  
in Tokyo but marginally above its late New York level of 120.59 
yen. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, investors locked in profits following the  
market's recent high-technology share rally. Concerns about the 
rapid rate of the recent share price increases were also capping 
gains. 
</P>
<P>
	``Buying centered on high-technology shares from the opening,  
but the rally peaked at about 10 a.m. on profit-taking,'' said 
Kazuhiro Nomura, head of trading at Paribas Capital Markets. 
``There is also some strong concern that values are too high.'' 
</P>
<P>
	High-technology issues got an early boost after the  
technology-rich Nasdaq Composite Index rose 39.91, or 1.4 percent, 
to end at 2,818.14 in New York on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Computer chipmaker Intel Corp.'s forecast that its profit  
margins would expand in the second half of this year lifted the 
Nasdaq. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 4.62 points, or 0.31 percent, to 1,501.69. The 
TOPIX closed up 13.38 points, or 0.90 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar edged higher from its level in  
New York on fears of more intervention by the Bank of Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's vice finance minister for international affairs,  
Haruhiko Kuroda, told reporters Thursday morning that his ministry 
is ``always prepared to take proper actions in the market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan has sold yen and bought dollars several times  
in recent weeks in order to keep export prices low and help sustain 
the country's fragile economic recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 123.22 yen, down  
from 123.34 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell  
to 1.6300 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.6600 percent, 
driving its price up to 101.48 yen from 101.21 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 11:10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hormone Is Clue To Appetite Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Scientists have moved closer to discovering how an  
appetite-stimulating hormone works in the brain, a finding that may 
help them develop drugs to fight obesity and eating disorders. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers knew melanin-concentrating hormone is one of many  
compounds that control how much someone eats. They also knew MCH 
needs a place to attach itself in the brain, called a receptor. 
Until now, they had not located it. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a report in Thursday's issue of the journal Nature,  
two groups working separately identified the receptor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would call it an exciting discovery because it opens a new  
hope for the treatment of food-consumption disorders,'' said 
Olivier Civelli, head of one of the groups, at the University of 
California at Irvine. 
</P>
<P>
	The other group is at SmithKline Beecham Pharmaceuticals in  
England. It has already started the search for compounds to block 
MCH from binding to the receptor. Scientists hope that would curb a 
person's appetite. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if a drug is found, it will be at least a decade before it  
reaches the market. 
</P>
<P>
	The body produces several compounds in the brain that control  
appetite, and scientists don't know how big a role MCH plays. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we would argue that it's more important than the  
others,'' said Shelagh Wilson, SmithKline's associate director of 
vascular biology. ``Yes, it may be one small part, but it may be 
the one small part that actually tips the balance and works for an 
obese patient.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The connection was identified by trial-and-error: matching all  
of the compounds produced by the brain to a previously identified 
receptor whose purpose was unclear. 
</P>
<P>
	The study also suggests that MCH may play a role in other forms  
of behavior, said Gary Schwartz, a Johns Hopkins University 
professor who was not involved in the research. 
</P>
<P>
	The receptor to which MCH hitches appears in many regions of the  
brain, not just those controlling appetite. So MCH could also 
affect movement, grooming and other activities, he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
