<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Deputy Charged in Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A former sheriff's deputy has been charged in  
a colleague's 1985 slaying after DNA tests showed a match with 
genetic material the killer left near his victim. 
</P>
<P>
	A warrant charges Ted Kirby, 54, with capital murder in  
sheriff's Sgt. George Arthur's shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	A manhunt was under way for Kirby, who moved to Spokane, Wash.,  
in 1996 after retiring. Kirby's wife has told investigators she 
hasn't seen her husband since he left their Spokane home June 30. 
That was shortly after investigators contacted Kirby at his home 
and took a court-ordered saliva sample. 
</P>
<P>
	``The DNA sample obtained from Ted Kirby was found to match the  
DNA sample left near the crime scene by the murderer,'' police 
Capt. Jim Tatreau said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirby is considered armed and dangerous, said Spokane County  
sheriff's Deputy David Reagan. 
</P>
<P>
	Detectives believe Kirby was lying in wait in Arthur's van when  
the sergeant left Men's Central Jail in downtown Los Angeles the 
night of June 1, 1985, Tatreau said. 
</P>
<P>
	Arthur was fatally shot after the van had traveled a few blocks.  
Witnesses described a bleeding man fleeing the wreck, and 
investigators were able to gather biological evidence from the 
scene, Tatreau said. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Los Angeles police and sheriff's deputies reopened the  
case and reinterviewed witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Detectives were looking into the possibility that Kirby and  
Arthur were involved with the same woman, the Los Angeles Times 
said, citing unidentified sources. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
