<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Girl Recovering After Brain Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- A girl who had half her brain removed to  
prevent the spread of a deadly neurological disease should be able 
to live a normal life, free of the seizures that plagued her, 
doctors said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Amber Ramirez, 15, was moving and able to murmur unintelligibly  
Wednesday after surgeons at Johns Hopkins Medical Center removed 
the left half of her brain Tuesday during a nine-hour operation. 
She was listed in fair condition Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lincoln, Neb., girl suffered from Rasmussen's syndrome, a  
rare disease that eats away at the brain tissue. A hemispherectomy, 
removing the damaged half, is often the only means of eliminating 
the seizures caused by the syndrome. 
</P>
<P>
	However, there was a risk she would lose her ability to speak.  
Doctors say it appears she will be OK, and that the right half of 
her brain should take over most of the functions lost by the 
removal of the left, including speech and fine motor movements. 
</P>
<P>
	``I anticipate that she will be able to speak and eventually  
live a quite normal life,'' said her surgeon, Dr. Benjamin Carson. 
</P>
<P>
	Amber's disease began with a limp in 1993, when she was 9. Two  
months later, she began to have seizures, often one every hour. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've lived most of my life with seizures,'' she said before  
the surgery. ``I'm tired of putting up with that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carson said he expects Amber will be ready to begin  
rehabilitation within two weeks, and will be able to walk within a 
year. Rehabilitation could last several years. 
</P>
<P>
	Her mother, Sheri Ramirez, said the recovery shouldn't be a  
problem for Amber. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's a determined kid.'' Ms. Ramirez said Wednesday.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
