<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Current Account Surplus Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's broadest measure of trade declined 23.7  
percent in May, the Finance Ministry announced Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The surplus in the current account decreased to a seasonally  
unadjusted $8.71 billion (1.054 trillion yen) from the same month 
last year, the ministry said. 
</P>
<P>
	The current account measures trade in merchandise, services,  
tourism and investment. It is calculated by determining the 
difference between Japan's income from foreign sources against 
payments on foreign obligations. It excludes net capital 
investment. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the fall, the figure was higher than the $7.38 billion  
(892.5 billion yen) estimate from Tokyo-based economists surveyed 
by Dow Jones Newswires. 
</P>
<P>
	The current account surplus had fallen 16.5 percent in April  
from the previous year. 
</P>
<P>
	The surplus rose 17.6 percent in fiscal year 1998 to a record  
high of $127 billion (15.227 trillion yen) for the 12 months to 
March 31. 
</P>
<P>
	The previous record was $123 billion (15.033 trillion yen) set  
in fiscal 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	The huge surplus has been a constant source of friction with the  
United States and other trading partners. They have been urging 
Japan to boost its economy to stimulate imports. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
