<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kasich Exits Race, Endorses Bush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. John Kasich of Ohio shelved his Oval  
Office dreams Wednesday and threw his support behind a ``soul 
brother,'' Texas Gov. George Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Crushed under the Bush financial steamroller -- Kasich raised  
$1.6 million compared with the front-runner's $36 million -- he was 
the second Republican presidential candidate to drop out of the 
race this week. Sen. Bob Smith abandoned his GOP campaign for the 
White House and said he would run as an independent. 
</P>
<P>
	Appearing with Bush at a news conference, Kasich conceded he  
couldn't compete and said, ``I think you have to be man enough to 
take the good along with those things that are disappointing. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine-term congressman said he plans to work for Republicans  
across the country for the next year and a half, but that he would 
not run for re-election next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The time does come when you know it's time to go,'' he said.  
``I accomplished everything I ever set out to accomplish in the 
House of Representatives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich heads the House Budget Committee, but would have to  
relinquish that position after 2000 because of chairmanship term 
limits. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush and Kasich declared themselves philosophically compatible.  
Bush playfully encouraged speculation about Kasich as a vice 
presidential prospect and said ``he's going to fit perfectly on my 
team.'' Kasich pledged to campaign for Bush, saying ``I can't find 
any issues that I have problems with him on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're soul brothers,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Kasich had devoted more than a year to his presidential  
aspiration, but by last month his exploratory campaign was being 
kept afloat only by the excess money in his congressional 
re-election account. 
</P>
<P>
	With the other hopefuls getting ready to pull out all stops in  
the Iowa straw poll, the campaign reached a financial crossroad. 
</P>
<P>
	In Clinton, Iowa, supporter Marianne Vidal said she was sorry to  
see Kasich drop out. 
</P>
<P>
	``He seems to be a down-to-earth person and that's what the  
American public needs,'' she said. ``I think with maturity and 
people getting to know him more, he will have a good chance the 
next time around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich said he's planning thank-you visits to Iowa and New  
Hampshire, where he had thrown himself into grass-roots politics, 
making the rounds of living rooms, diners, backroads and bowling 
alleys. 
</P>
<P>
	He competed in a sled-dog race, played baseball on the famous  
``field of dreams,'' and shook hands at town dumps because that's 
where people congregate on Saturday mornings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had probably the greatest experience of my life,'' Kasich  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	He was vague about his plans for life after Congress. Kasich has  
worked for the government -- first as a legislative aide, then state 
senator, then congressman -- his entire adult life. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he has in mind some sort of public service work that  
wasn't a government job. He'll also learn about fatherhood; his 
wife Karen is expecting their first baby in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Smith, Kasich had been unable to break out of single-digit  
showings in recent polls, and Kasich had maintained from the start 
that he would not put his name on the ballot unless he managed to 
get a bankroll of at least $18.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think John's always been realistic about this thing,  
realistic about his fund raising,'' said Robert Bennett, chairman 
of the Ohio Republican Party. 
</P>
<P>
	On Capitol Hill, Kasich is known for exuberance, tenacity and  
love of debate. 
</P>
<P>
	He was one of the major authors of the budget-balancing plan  
agreed to in 1997 -- perhaps the high water mark of his 
congressional career. 
</P>
<P>
	He spent years trying to kill the B-2 bomber, and managed to  
limit production but not end it. 
</P>
<P>
	He also placed himself at the front of an effort to eliminate  
several business subsidies, a stance that led to arguments with 
fellow Republicans over word play -- some objected to calling the 
subsidies ``corporate welfare'' -- and which allowed him to build an 
unlikely alliance with consumer advocate Ralph Nader. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
