<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cable TV Boosts Time Warner Profit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Time Warner posted net earnings Wednesday of  
$593 million in the second quarter as a large gain from cable 
television deals boosted profits. 
</P>
<P>
	The earnings, which were equivalent to 43 cents per share,  
compared to net profits of $101 million, or 2 cents a share, in the 
same period a year ago. Revenues slipped to $3.57 billion from 
$3.67 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Time Warner's net figures for the second quarter reflected  
several one-time gains, mainly a $771 million profit from various 
sales and exchanges of cable television properties. 
</P>
<P>
	Combined operating income at Time Warner and its subsidiary Time  
Warner Entertainment rose 4 percent in the quarter to $1.13 billion 
from $1.09 billion in the same period a year ago, not counting 
one-time gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnings in most of Time Warner's business areas -- publishing,  
cable, and entertainment -- posted gains except for the WB broadcast 
network, which recorded a wider loss as the fledgling network 
continued to absorb startup costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Time Warner's publishing business had an 11 percent rise in  
operating earnings, which the company attributed to advertising 
gains at several of its major magazines, including Sports 
Illustrated, InStyle, Money and Teen People. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's main movie studio, Warner Bros., posted gains  
thanks to the box office success of ``The Matrix,'' which has taken 
in $307 million so far. Time Warner's boutique studio New Line also 
did well with the release of the ``Austin Powers'' sequel. 
</P>
<P>
	Time Warner's cable networks CNN, TNT, TBS and HBO all posted  
advances during the quarter. The company's cable delivery systems 
also had large gains, due largely to $771 million in gains from 
selling and exchanging cable systems with other companies. Even 
without the one-time gains, earnings from the cable subcriber 
business rose. 
</P>
<P>
	Losses at the WB network, a new and successful network aimed at  
kids and young adults, widened to $30 million from $23 million in 
the same period a year ago due to higher startup costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Time Warner's shares rose $1.56 1/4 cents to $77.31 1/4 on the New  
York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first half of the year, Time Warner posted net earnings  
of $731 million compared to $39 million. Operating earnings, 
excluding one-time gains and other non-recurring factors, rose to 
$2.17 billion from $1.93 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-month revenues rose to $6.84 billion from $6.81 billion.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
