<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Voting on Disabled Rule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators are prepared to approve new  
rules requiring the telecommunications industry to make pagers, 
cellular phones and other equipment and services easier for 
disabled individuals to use. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Communications Commission was scheduled to vote  
today on the rule, which will ``represent the most significant 
opportunity for people with disabilities since the passage of the 
Americans with Disabilities Act in 1990,'' said FCC Chairman Bill 
Kennard. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing that has been done since that time that is  
more significant in insuring access for persons with 
disabilities,'' he said Tuesday, adding later: ``We're writing the 
ADA for the information age.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Without going into specifics, Kennard said the rules would  
require manufacturers to do all they can to address the needs of 
the disabled during the design phase of products and services. The 
costs of implementing such features would be kept down by 
incorporating them early in the production process, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the rule, such equipment as voice-activated phones,  
talking Caller ID and phones with keypads that have large buttons 
or specific identifying marks would be more commonplace. Also more 
widely available would be ``text telephones,'' usually referred to 
as TTY or TDD systems, and phones with volume controls or headsets. 
</P>
<P>
	The rule stems from a provision of a 1996 telecommunications  
law, which instructed the FCC to take steps to give disabled people 
better access to telecommunications services and devices that suit 
their needs. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennard said commissioners do not intend to micromanage the  
design process of telecommunications products. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just telling the manufacturing community that we're most  
interested in the ends, not the means,'' he said. ``Make your 
products more accessible for people with disabilities and do it 
early on in the design of the products.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Failure to comply with the rules could result in penalties or  
damage awards ranging from the thousands to the millions of 
dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it's our hope that by giving the manufacturers some  
flexibility ... we'll really accomplish a lot, not only for people 
with disabilities but for our whole society,'' Kennard said. 
</P>
<P>
	He pointed out that many products commonly used today -- such as  
the vibrating pager or closed-caption television sets -- were 
designed for people with disabilities, who account for roughly 54 
million Americans and a high number of the nation's unemployed. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Fontes, senior vice president of the Cellular  
Telecommunications Industry Association, called the new rule an 
important step. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said many in the industry have come up with ways to make  
telecommunications equipment more usable by the disabled. 
</P>
<P>
	``The wireless industry has been committed not only to the  
letter of the law, but the spirit of the law, even before access to 
telecommunications service was part of the Telecom Act,'' he said. 
``We were working on issues such as hearing aid compatibility on 
wireless phones before 1996.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
