<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Folksy Gore Loosens Stiff Reputation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Scuffing the linoleum of the Soul City  
Cafe with the turned-up toes of his shiny cowboy boots, Al Gore 
claps the shoulder of a man he is trying to recruit for campaign 
work. ``You da man!'' Gore tells him. 
</P>
<P>
	Take away the microphone and lectern, and this presidential  
candidate isn't as stiff as his reputation. 
</P>
<P>
	On a two-day swing through Iowa, a state crowded with  
presidential candidates this week, Gore left his vice presidential 
props behind. 
</P>
<P>
	The dress shirt and necktie are gone, replaced by sport shirts --  
all in shades of green -- that show off the muscles of a man who 
lifts weights with his 16-year-old son and is training for a 
marathon. A bronze Chevy Suburban replaces his usual limousine. 
</P>
<P>
	Trailing George W. Bush in many polls and raising just half of  
what the Texas governor did for the first half of the year, Gore 
drew parallels Wednesday between his 2000 presidential race to Iowa 
Gov. Tom Vilsack's 1998 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a time when he was 20 points behind in the polls and  
there were people who said he couldn't win, right? Hmmmm,'' he 
reminded Democratic activists at Java Joe's coffeehouse with a 
theatrical stroke of his chin. 
</P>
<P>
	``He developed -- what was it? -- momentum and ideas while his  
Republican opponent was ready to move into the mansion before the 
election. I don't know, maybe it's deja vu.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Never mind that Gore has an increasingly formidable Democratic  
primary opponent, former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, on his 
heels. Gore only once, and then vaguely, appeared to acknowledge 
the coming primary fight when he appealed to Democrats here to show 
``unity of purpose.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Java Joe's, he peeled off his navy sportcoat and jauntily  
tossed it across the room to a surprised aide. He prompted a 
toddler to give him a ``high five'' slap. And, with campaign aides 
chatting among themselves while he began to answer a voter's 
question on domestic violence, Gore flashed real irritation: 
``Could I have your attention in the back? Thank you! This is 
important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After a commanding, 90-minute dialogue with about 50 Iowa women  
on issues from gun control to abortion rights, Gore asked them to 
indulge his ``punch line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With an ``Aw, shucks'' slump of his shoulders, shuffle of his  
feet, he said: ``I would like you to stand for me in the 
caucuses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa's caucuses, likely to be held early February, will kick off  
the nation's presidential nominating contests. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruce Ellingsen, a Council Bluffs railway worker, was impressed  
with what he saw as a mastery of issues and a smooth, genuine 
performance by Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously he's done a lot of practicing for this to have  
happened,'' observed the yet-undecided Ellingsen. 
</P>
<P>
	``He seems to be more common-like,'' agreed Gerrit Vander  
Meiden, an elderly Pella, Iowa, family farmer. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore can showcase this side to only a handful of voters at a  
time. His crowds at each stop number in the dozens and peaked on 
this trip at around 200. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the lighter tone, Gore's campaigning can still feel  
canned and hit-or-miss when it comes to connecting with people. 
</P>
<P>
	``What do they want to hear from me?'' he quizzed an adviser  
before stepping inside Soul City for a barbecue-and-greens dinner 
with 16 local black organizers. And so methodical was he shaking 
hands around the table that he blew right past Iowa first lady 
Christie Vilsack as she waited to introduce him to camera-cute 
cousins Danielle Hill, 13, and Daniel Turner, 8. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll make sure you get to meet him later,'' Mrs. Vilsack  
apologized. 
</P>
<P>
	The message that Gore is not Bill Clinton -- and in fact, would  
like people to see him as better than Clinton -- is subtle but 
pervasive. 
</P>
<P>
	At a school safety forum with 200 Council Bluffs residents,  
campaign aides positioned the ``Stronger Values'' and ``Stronger 
Families'' banners so that they appeared just over Gore's shoulder 
in news photographs. The ``Safer Schools'' poster was hung clear 
across the Kirn Junior High gymnasium. 
</P>
<P>
	To women, Gore griped that Republicans are gunning for him,  
amassing millions in campaign dollars because ``they don't like a 
lot of the changes that you and I have brought about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No mention of Clinton, the man whose signature was on the bills  
and executive orders actually making those changes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
