<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boxer Kelly a Work in Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) -- Kevin Kelly is a work in progress.  
</P>
<P>
	After just three amateur bouts and a tough start as a pro, the  
29-year-old Australian has advanced to a shot at a world title. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether he's advanced enough to become a world champion will be  
determined Saturday night when he challenges WBA super welterweight 
champion David Reid. 
</P>
<P>
	It's been a long trip for Kelly, both in miles from Australia  
and in hard knocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly (24-5-3, 11 knockouts) lost four of his first 10 fights.  
</P>
<P>
	``He only had three amateur fights,'' said trainer George Reno.  
``So virtually he was serving an apprenticeship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his last 10 fight, all wins, the former British Commonwealth  
champion has scored seven knockouts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've sort of come along,'' Kelly said Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	Most boxing observers don't believe Kelly has come along far  
enough to beat Reid in the fight at the Boardwalk Convention 
Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't look past anybody,'' said Reid (12-0, seven  
knockouts). 
</P>
<P>
	Plans, however, already call for him to make a title defense  
against Keith Mullings in late August. And there is a possible 
lucrative fight against IBF junior middleweight champion Fernando 
Vargas next spring. 
</P>
<P>
	Vargas will defend his title against Raul Marquez Saturday night  
at Stateline, Nev. 
</P>
<P>
	So Reid has a lot at stake.  
</P>
<P>
	As for the challenger, he said, ``I've come here to fight the  
fight of my life. This fight will determine how I live the rest of 
my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reid will be making the first defense of the 154-pound  
championship he won with a clear-cut decision over Laurent 
Boudouani of France March 6 at the Convention Center. 
</P>
<P>
	While the champion from Philadelphia will be fighting for only  
the 13th time as a pro, he was schooled long and well as an amateur 
career in which he won gold medals at the 1996 Olympics and 1995 
Pan American Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The FX telecast will start at 10 p.m. EDT, with the main event  
set for 11 p.m. Also to be televised will be a 10-round lightweight 
bout between John John Molina, a former IBF junior lightweight 
champion from Puerto Rico and James Crayton of Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	Another 10-round will match junior welterweights Hector Camacho  
Jr. of Puerto Rico and Mike Cooley of Omaha, Neb. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
