<DOCNO> APW19990714.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 16:26:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Tagliabue Warns Phillips on Fine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Lawrence Phillips, the troubled running back who  
revived his career in Europe, was told Wednesday by commissioner 
Paul Tagliabue that he will be fined for past misdeeds if he signs 
with an NFL team. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips, who became the first running back to gain more than  
1,000 yards in the NFL Europe's eight-game season, met for an hour 
with Tagliabue. 
</P>
<P>
	``I worked hard to meet my responsibilities in NFL Europe this  
spring and I'm determined to do the same in the NFL starting this 
summer,'' Phillips said after the meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	The league later said in a statement that Tagliabue told  
Phillips ``that as a result of past misconduct, he will be subject 
to a substantial fine this season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The statement said the amount will be determined later,  
presumably depending on his contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips pleaded no contest to beating a former girlfriend while  
at Nebraska, then left the school after his junior season. 
</P>
<P>
	The St. Louis Rams chose Phillips as the sixth overall pick of  
the 1996 draft, but he was arrested on drunken driving charges and 
spent 23 days in jail during 19 months with the team. 
</P>
<P>
	He was subsequently signed by the Miami Dolphins, but played  
little. 
</P>
<P>
	He was cut by the team at the beginning of last season after  
being arrested on charges of hitting a woman who refused to dance 
with him at a nightclub. He pleaded guilty to battery and received 
six months' probation. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips revived his career in Europe, gaining 1,021 yards and  
scoring 14 touchdowns as he led Barcelona to the league 
championship game. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, a number of teams are interested in him, including  
Baltimore, Green Bay, San Francisco and Oakland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
