<HEADLINE> Hawks Sign Top Picks Terry, Bowdler </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Atlanta Hawks signed their two first-round  
draft choices Wednesday -- Jason Terry, the point guard from Arizona 
who is expected to replace the traded Mookie Blaylock, and 
little-known forward-center Cal Bowdler of Old Dominion. 
</P>
<P>
	Terry was taken with the 10th overall pick in the June NBA  
draft. Bowdler was the 17th player chosen. 
</P>
<P>
	Both rookies signed three-year guaranteed contracts with a team  
option for a fourth year. Terry's agent, Larry Fox, would not 
confirm the terms of his deal, but it was believed to be about 
$4.73 million over three years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jason and I feel comfortable with the contract,'' said Fox.  
</P>
<P>
	Bowdler's agent, William Pollak, said the 6-foot-10 rookie will  
receive $3.3 million over his three-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hawks' other first-round pick, Dion Glover of Georgia Tech,  
remains unsigned. He was the 20th player chosen. 
</P>
<P>
	Terry averaged 21.9 points per game last season and was named a  
first-team All-American and Pac-10 player of the year. He led the 
Pac-10 in scoring, assists (5.5) and steals (2.8) and is the only 
player in Arizona history to finish his career with more than 1,000 
points and 200 steals. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowdler averaged 14.7 points per game as a senior at Old  
Dominion and led the Colonial Athletic Association in both 
rebounding and blocked shots. 
</P>
<P>
	Terry is a leading candidate to replace the departed Blaylock,  
who was traded to the Golden State Warriors just before the draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Lenny Wilkens said Terry would battle veterans Anthony  
Johnson and Bimbo Coles for a starting role. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jason plays an up-tempo game,'' Wilkens said. ``Certainly,  
he'll have good support around him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Pete Babcock said Bowdler can play both center  
and strong forward, giving the Hawks more flexibility on the bench. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
