<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> USDA Moves on Dairy Price Overhaul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government is going forward with a farmer  
referendum on overhauling of the way milk is priced, despite 
widespread opposition in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The Agriculture Department's proposal is intended to soften  
regional pricing disparities. 
</P>
<P>
	While it could hurt many producers outside the upper Midwest,  
the plan is expected to be approved nationwide because milk prices 
would otherwise be deregulated as of Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Agriculture Committee voted 32-15 earlier this month  
to block the USDA plan and implement an alternative proposal that 
is closer to the current pricing system. The legislation is 
sponsored by more than 220 lawmakers, a majority of the House. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA announced Wednesday that farmers will vote from Aug. 2 to  
Aug. 6 on its plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is outrageous that the USDA insists on pushing their agenda  
on unwilling dairy farmers who will end up in a Catch-22 when they 
will be forced to choose between a bad plan and no plan at all,'' 
said Rep. John Sweeney, R-N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the government's current system, guaranteed minimum prices  
for fluid milk are lowest in the upper Midwest and highest in the 
South and West, up to $3 per hundred pounds higher in some places, 
because the price is based on a farm's distance from Eau Claire, 
Wis. The Depression-era system was designed to spur production in 
areas where it had been scarce. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, Congress set the system for elimination and ordered  
USDA to come up with a new plan. 
</P>
<P>
	A vote in favor of USDA's proposal doesn't mean farmers like it,  
said Chris Galen, a spokesman for the National Milk Producers 
Federation. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a vote in favor of the lesser of two evils. It should in  
no way prevent Congress from moving forward with the legislative 
changes they are considering,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chances for the alternative plan are less certain in the Senate.  
The Agriculture Committee has not scheduled a hearing on the 
measure, and Senate rules would give senators from the upper 
Midwest more leverage to stop it if it is offered as an amendment 
to another bill. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
