<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Release Rollover Test Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal safety regulators are using a computer  
to steer vehicles through sharp turns to show that a reliable test 
can be developed that assesses a vehicle's propensity to roll over. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration has tested 12  
vehicles in severe driving maneuvers using the computer to execute 
turns at speeds up to 60 mph. One compact pickup, a 1997 Ford 
Ranger, tipped so far to the side during two tests that it was 
caught by the metal outriggers on its sides that are designed to 
prevent it from rolling over and hurting the driver, according to 
an agency report on the tests to be made public today. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven of the vehicles -- nearly all light trucks such as pickups  
or sport-utility vehicles -- tipped to the side, lifting two wheels 
off the ground, during at least one of the tests, the 117-page 
report said. Only one car had two wheels lift off the ground 
slightly during a test. 
</P>
<P>
	NHTSA officials say they planned to propose a federal rollover  
test later this year to provide consumers with information on the 
relative likelihood of rollover for cars and light trucks -- pickup 
trucks, SUVs and vans. 
</P>
<P>
	That would be a big step for the agency, since it has tried  
unsuccessfully to come up with a reliable rollover test in the 
past. 
</P>
<P>
	Highway crash data shows that pickups and sport-utility  
vehicles, which have a higher center of gravity, roll over more 
than cars. But developing a test to assess rollover propensity has 
long been controversial among automakers. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry argues such tests are not reliable since a driver  
cannot duplicate how sharp his turns are for each vehicle he 
maneuvers, even if he is driving around set cones, among other 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	However, NHTSA officials said in the report that their driving  
tests on a dozen vehicles show they can reliably repeat the 
maneuvers with the aid of the computer that makes the turns for the 
driver. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-seven percent of all fatalities in light trucks result  
from rollover, the agency said. By comparison, 22 percent of car 
deaths involve rollovers. More than 9,400 people died in rollover 
crashes in 1997, the latest year for which statistics were 
available. 
</P>
<P>
	Smaller pickups and SUVs have higher rollover rates than their  
larger counterparts. Earlier this year, the agency required all new 
SUVs with wheelbases less than 110 inches to have a warning label 
saying they had a higher rollover risk. 
</P>
<P>
	In one of the agency's rollover tests, the Ranger pickup tipped  
sharply after suddenly making a large turn while traveling 48 mph, 
then turning back even farther in the opposite direction. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the vehicles tested that tipped did so during this type  
of maneuver, known as a fishhook. 
</P>
<P>
	In another test, the Ranger tipped up when a single large turn  
was made, similar to getting on a cloverleaf ramp, at 52 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	``If no outriggers were present, the vehicle might well have  
rolled over,'' the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ranger and a 1998 Chevrolet Tracker sport-utility also  
tipped up on two wheels by more than 2 inches in a test similar to 
the cloverleaf ramp that involved some braking by the driver. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal test researchers cautioned against comparing the vehicle  
test results to draw conclusions about any individual vehicle since 
so few vehicles have been tested and officials were still deciding 
on the best test. 
</P>
<P>
	``The results cannot be used to draw meaningful comparisons  
about the stability of specific models,'' an agency memo said. 
However, the report did say the Ranger ``exhibited the highest 
rollover propensity in this study.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ford spokeswoman Jennifer Flake said the company could not  
comment on the Ranger's performance ``until we've had a chance to 
look at the specific test results.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at General Motors, which makes the Tracker, said the  
outrigger adds weight to the vehicles and skews test results. NHTSA 
also is reviewing alternative rollover tests suggested by GM. 
</P>
<P>
	Three vehicles -- a 1998 Ford Explorer SUV, the Ranger pickup and  
a 1998 Chevrolet Lumina -- had tires that broke their seals and 
deflated in maneuvering the test corners, dropping the wheel rims 
onto the pavement. An agency document said when the tire was ripped 
from part of the rim, the vehicle was difficult to control and was 
more likely to slide sideways, also ``increasing the risk of 
rollover.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seven vehicles tipped up on two wheels only slightly, 1 to 2  
inches, in some of the tests: a 1998 Ford E-150 Club Wagon van; a 
1998 Chevrolet Astro van; the 1998 Chevrolet Tahoe SUV; a 1998 
Chevrolet Lumina car; and the Explorer, Tracker and Ranger. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
