<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Texas Wants Credit for Capture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- FBI agent Don Clark offered a terse answer when  
asked if any single law enforcement agency led the way in the 
capture of the man suspected of being the railroad killer. 
</P>
<P>
	``No,'' Clark, the agent in charge of the FBI's Houston office,  
replied at a news conference Tuesday after discussing the long 
hours his task force worked and the thousands of tips, mostly 
dead-end, it received. 
</P>
<P>
	By all other accounts, however, the man most responsible for  
brokering the remarkable surrender Tuesday of Angel Maturino 
Resendez was rookie Sgt. Drew Carter of the Texas Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	Though they didn't complain publicly, Texas authorities were  
annoyed by Clark's failure to acknowledge Carter's work and by the 
FBI's decision to circumvent the Rangers and almost instantly 
announce the arrest in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Cox, spokesman for the Rangers' parent agency, the  
Department of Public Safety, said state officials were ``aware, of 
course, that an arrest probably was imminent and we were preparing 
to announce that fact.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``But we had not done so yet because we here at the Austin  
headquarters had not received word yet Ramirez was taken into 
custody,'' he said. ``Suddenly, we began getting calls from media 
hearing that Ramirez was taken into custody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cox was quick to add that the DPS and FBI enjoy a close  
relationship. ``The FBI has tremendous resources and has helped us 
over the years,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	And Rangers Capt. Earl Pearson, Carter's boss, said  
disagreements are part of any team law enforcement effort. 
</P>
<P>
	Carter had established a rapport with Maturino Resendez's sister  
in Albuquerque, N.M. She persuaded her brother to walk from 
neighboring Ciudad Juarez, Mexico, and surrender in El Paso on 
Tuesday. Carter met him on the bridge with a handshake, then 
handcuffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Clark insisted that the FBI was not trying to steal the  
spotlight from the DPS, which has had jurisdictional friction with 
Washington in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the FBI -- not the DPS -- that mounted an assault on the  
Branch Davidian compound near Waco in 1993 after a bungled Bureau 
of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms raid resulted in a deadly shootout 
and 51-day standoff. The FBI siege ended with a fire that destroyed 
the compound and left cult leader David Koresh and about 80 
followers dead. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
