<DOCNO> APW19990714.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 12:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Visits Northern Virginia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TYSONS CORNER, Va. (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush visited  
northern Virginia's booming high-technology region Wednesday, 
collecting $400,000 for his presidential campaign and touring a 
summer camp to train youngsters for computer careers. 
</P>
<P>
	The visit was the front-running Republican's second to Virginia  
in less than a month and attracted high-tech luminaries such as 
America Online's chairman and chief executive, Steve Case, as well 
as executives from Network Solutions and Oracle. 
</P>
<P>
	While Bush's aides touted the event as an overwhelming show of  
support for Bush from northern Virginia's high-tech leaders, some 
of those in attendance were there to simply meet and hear Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Case declined to say afterward whether he supports Bush, and a  
list of donors did not include his name. ``It's early in the 
process,'' Case said as he hurried to elude a reporter at the Ritz 
Carlton. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, at a Washington news conference, Bush received the  
endorsement of former Republican presidential rival John Kasich, 
who dropped out of the race Wednesday. ``I feel as though I have a 
soul brother,'' Kasich said, wearing a Bush campaign cap. 
</P>
<P>
	Accepting the Ohio congressman support, Bush responded, ``People  
in this country want a campaign that is positive and hopeful and 
inclusive, a campaign that attracts new faces and new voices; a 
campaign that will speak to our better angels, not our darker 
impulses; a campaign that will give America a fresh start after a 
season of cynicism. That's exactly the kind of campaign John Kasich 
was running. He's going to fit perfectly on my team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich accompanied Bush to a campaign appearance in Baltimore,  
where they toured a center that teaches carpentry skills to the 
unemployed and remodels inner city homes. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tysons Corner, Bush addressed about 500 at the hotel in the  
heart of Virginia's ``high-tech heaven'' and repeated his campaign 
themes of cutting taxes, reducing government regulation of 
business, free trade, and improving the military and education. 
</P>
<P>
	He also took a slap at the Democratic presidential front-runner,  
Vice President Al Gore, by saying that America's current prosperity 
is not due to the Clinton-Gore administration's policies. ``They no 
more invented prosperity than they invented the Internet,'' Bush 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush did not say whether he supports efforts by states to impose  
taxes on Internet commerce, a topic of great interest in the 
high-tech community. Business representatives, meeting in 
Williamsburg last month, said they adamantly oppose any tax that 
singles out the Internet, such as a charge on World Wide Web 
access. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush aides said the candidate will await the recommendation of a  
congressional commission headed by Gov. James Gilmore, who is 
endorsing Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Gilmore introduced Bush at the fund-raiser and accompanied him  
on a visit to a summer computer program at Alexandria's Thomas A. 
Edison High School, where a student demonstrated a computer program 
to design houses. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm looking for a new house,'' Bush quipped.  
</P>
<P>
	At the fund-raiser, Gilmore said Bush understands northern  
Virginia's high-tech needs because of his work to promote the 
growth of technology growth in Texas. Gilmore drew laughs by 
introducing Bush as the next ``webmaster of www.whitehouse.gov.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Washington lawyer Joe Howe said he has yet to choose a  
candidate. ``I think we would all like to get to know a little more 
about this man,'' Howe said. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside, about 30 protesters chanted ``Virginia is not for  
sale'' and held signs reading ``stand up for gun safety.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
