<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 09:10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Has 25 Years As Street Vendor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) -- It's been 25 years since Lois Bodoky's  
beauty shop burned down and she turned to selling hot dogs. 
</P>
<P>
	Bodoky, known to many in Burlington simply as ``the hot dog  
lady,'' was one of the first vendors on Church Street, long before 
the three blocks dotted with restaurants and stores were blocked 
off to traffic and turned into a pedestrian mall. 
</P>
<P>
	In those days, she and her husband would push their wooden maple  
cart down one side of the street and up the other during lunch hour 
as cars streamed by. 
</P>
<P>
	She now commands a place in the middle of Church Street -- a  
prime spot during the holiday shopping time in December -- and just 
below the building where she used to do hair. 
</P>
<P>
	She turned 77 on Fourth of July and plans to sell hot dogs for  
as long as she can. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had a lot of fun,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	On the busy brick-paved street, Bodoky stands out among nearly  
20 vendors. She still favors the silver cats-eye glasses, dotted 
with rhinestones, that she's worn since the 1950s. Nowadays, 
they're hard to find, and she orders hers from France. 
</P>
<P>
	She works amidst a young, casually dressed crowd, but Bodoky  
wears her white hair pinned in curls on top of her head. Her thin 
eyebrows are penciled to a pronounced curve, the skin below covered 
in a sheen of blue and then pink. 
</P>
<P>
	But mostly Bodoky is known for selling hot dogs.  
</P>
<P>
	She has always used local McKenzie hot dogs and Bouyea-Fassetts  
rolls. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither the price nor the menu has changed much over the years.  
A plain hot dog sells for $1, while one topped with sauerkraut, 
chili and onions, or all of the above, goes for a little more. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lois believes in volume more than price,'' said her husband,  
John. 
</P>
<P>
	Bodoky has loyal customers, including men in suits or in  
construction clothes who down a fast lunch on a nice day, and the 
young and the unemployed who roam Church Street and appreciate a 
bargain meal. 
</P>
<P>
	But never on Sunday. And no longer during January, February and  
March. 
</P>
<P>
	That's when Bodoky and her husband take a break and get away for  
their anniversary. In recent years, they've gone to Niagara Falls 
and to Plymouth, Mass., after Bodoky said she discovered she was a 
descendant of Miles Standish. 
</P>
<P>
	The rest of the year they're happy to be on Church Street.  
</P>
<P>
	The Bodokys' day starts around 9:30 a.m. at their home downtown.  
There, they chop onions, concoct chili and load cans of sauerkraut, 
rolls and hot dogs into the aluminum cart. 
</P>
<P>
	At around 11 a.m., they head to Church Street, towing the cart  
in a trailer behind their car. During the day, John sits behind 
Lois in a portable chair, on call to fetch more rolls or sauerkraut 
as needed. 
</P>
<P>
	He drove trucks until they moved from California to Vermont in  
1971. They wanted to be near their son who lived in in New York 
City, but didn't want to live there. 
</P>
<P>
	They settled in Burlington ``and fell in love with the place,''  
she says. 
</P>
<P>
	She opened Lojo's, a second-floor beauty parlor on Church  
Street. But when it burned down in 1974, she had to find a new 
space. And she knew it had to be on Church Street. She looked and 
looked but never found a place that suited her or that she could 
afford. 
</P>
<P>
	Then she started thinking about hot dogs. She loved stopping at  
a hot dog stand in Brooklyn near the home of her son, now 51. 
</P>
<P>
	So she proposed the idea to John. He thought she was crazy, she  
says, but she persevered. 
</P>
<P>
	She says she loves the changes she's seen on Church Street, with  
new stores opening and more vending carts. It's what's she's 
dreamed of for Burlington and for her business. She's always had a 
vision of carts topped with beautiful umbrellas lining the street, 
just as in European cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Her most famous customer is U.S. Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., who  
started campaigning for the Senate the same year she started 
selling hot dogs. Leahy has stopped by so many times over the years 
for a hot dog and a chat that the two of them have gotten to know 
each other. Leahy put a salute to Bodoky in the May 24, 1999, 
Congressional Record, to mark her 25th year in business. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Discovery Channel did a piece about Burlington, it  
featured two local landmarks: Lois Bodoky and Shelburne Farms, a 
scenic estate on Lake Champlain that has been turned into an inn 
and educational farm. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
