<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Rejects Disability Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- The Boeing Co. has rejected federal charges that  
it unfairly withdrew job offers to applicants it believed had 
disabilities. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, in a lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court here, the  
Equal Employment Opportunity Commission accused the aerospace 
manufacturer of violating the Americans with Disabilities Act in 
the cases of four Boeing job applicants. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing said Tuesday it complied with the statute, while also  
ensuring its employees were not placed in dangerous situations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Boeing feels confident the decisions it made were right,  
appropriate and lawful,'' the company said in a statement released 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The company has a duty to see that individuals are not placed  
in jobs that would put them at risk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the government filed the charges last Tuesday Boeing  
initially declined to comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit seeks an injunction, back pay, penalties and  
possibly jobs for the applicants. It does not name a dollar amount. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
