<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Mostly Unchanged / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices drifted lower Wednesday despite two  
economic reports that appeared to reduce the likelihood that the 
Federal Reserve would increase interest rates again this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the government's benchmark 30-year Treasury bond  
fell 3/32 percent, or 94 cents per $1,000 in face value, as its 
yield rose to 5.91 percent from 5.90 percent late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In separate reports Wednesday, the government said prices at the  
wholesale level unexpectedly declined last month while consumers' 
spending slowed dramatically. Such reports indicate the U.S. 
economy could be cooling down and thus reduce the need for an 
interest rate increase on top of last month's modest move to higher 
rates by the Fed. 
</P>
<P>
	Inflation erodes the value of fixed-rate securities, such as  
Treasurys. 
</P>
<P>
	Many traders were awaiting Thursday report of inflation at the  
consumer level. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader Treasury market, prices of short-term securities  
fell 3/32 percent and intermediate securities fell 1/8 point to 3/16 
point, reported Bridge Telerate. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose to 4.70 percent while  
the discount rose 0.01 percentage point from Tuesday to 4.58 
percent. Six-month yields fell to 4.67 percent, as the discount 
fell 0.02 percentage point to 4.50 percent. One-year yields rose to 
4.96 percent as the discount rose 0.01 percent to 4.72 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 5.00 percent from 4.94 percent Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds was unchanged at 119 3/8. The average yield to 
maturity was also unchanged at 5.51 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
