<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Cohen Seeks To Repair US-Greek Ties  
</P>
<P>
	ATHENS (AP) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen sought today to  
repair relations between the United States and Greece still bruised 
from a sharp disagreement over Kosovo policy. In talks with Greek 
Premier Costas Simitas, Cohen discussed the renewal of cooperation 
between Greece and the United States in Kosovo now that the 11-week 
NATO bombing campaign is over. Greece, with historic religious, 
ethnic and geographic ties to the Yugoslav Serb population, 
strongly opposed the NATO bombing campaign, although it stopped 
short of using its power as an alliance member to veto the effort. 

</P>
<P>
	Israeli Premier To Make 1st Visit to D.C.  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- On the eve of his first visit to Washington as  
Israel's prime minister, Ehud Barak said the United States should 
scale back its role as ``policeman and judge'' in Mideast 
peacemaking. Barak also said that while he would resume an Israeli 
troop pullback in the West Bank suspended by his hard-line 
predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu, he would not stick to the tight 
timetable stipulated by the U.S.-brokered Wye River 
land-for-security agreement. Under the accord signed in October, 
the Palestinians were to assume full or partial control of 40 
percent of the West Bank before heading into talks on a permanent 
peace agreement with Israel. 

</P>
<P>
	Thais Protest at U.S. Embassy  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- More than 100 Thai environmentalists  
gathered at the U.S. embassy today to demand that the United States 
take responsibility for cleaning up some toxic Vietnam-War chemical 
defoliants recently discovered at a provincial airport. They 
presented an embassy official with two sacks of dirt which they 
said was contaminated soil. Drums of buried chemicals were found by 
workers expanding a runway at a provincial airport, near the 
seaside resort of Hua Hin. The workers renovating the runway fell 
ill, and fears arose that the chemical might be Agent Orange dumped 
by U.S. military units who were stationed there in the 1960s and 
70s. 

</P>
<P>
	Suspected Railway Killer Surrenders  
</P>
<P>
	EL PASO, Texas (AP) -- Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, the Mexican  
drifter suspected of killing eight people as he hopped freight 
trains around the country, turned himself in Tuesday in a deal 
brokered by his sister. Ending a six-week manhunt, the 39-year-old 
Resendez-Ramirez walked with a brother across the bridge from 
Mexico to El Paso where he was arrested. The tattooed ex-convict -- 
who is charged with three murders and linked to five other 
slayings, all of them in Texas, Kentucky and Illinois -- was on the 
FBI's 10 Most Wanted List and had been in Mexico for an 
undetermined amount of time, investigators said. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Promises To Repay Kazakstan  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia agreed today to pay off its $115 million  
debt to Kazakstan for use of the Baikonur launch pad, in an 
apparent effort to persuade Kazakstan to lift a launch ban in time 
to send a cargo ship to the Mir space station. Russian Deputy Prime 
Minister Ilya Klebanov reached a debt deal with Kazak officials in 
emergency meetings in Astana, the capital of the Central Asian 
nation, said a spokesman for the Russian Space Agency. The Kazak 
government banned all launches from Baikonur on July 6. 

</P>
<P>
	Pakistan Shells Indian Highway  
</P>
<P>
	MUSHKOH VALLEY, India (AP) -- Indian reconnaissance flights have  
spotted cement bunkers in a disputed Kashmir border region and 
airstrikes appear imminent, an intelligence officer said today. The 
three bunkers are near the Siachen glacier, outside the area where 
Indian forces have been battling an infiltration by Pakistan-based 
fighters for two months. Airstrikes around the town of Turtuk seem 
imminent, an intelligence officer, speaking on condition of 
anonymity, told The Associated Press. 

</P>
<P>
	Hard-Liners in Iran Staging Rally  
</P>
<P>
	DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- While hard-liners have called  
for a rally of their own, Iranian moderate leaders vowed that six 
days of protests on a scale unseen since the 1979 Islamic 
revolution will be brought to an end today. The huge 
demonstrations, which have left two people dead and scores injured 
or arrested, mark the first time Iranians have taken to the streets 
in such numbers to demand more freedoms in a nation hard-liners 
seek to firmly regulate. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stock Prices Close Higher  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks jumped today amid hopes for Japan's  
economic recovery. The Nikkei gained 176.77 points to close at 
18,357.86. 

</P>
<P>
	American League 4, National League 1  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Moments after Ted Williams threw out the first  
ball, Pedro Martinez pitched himself into the All-Star game record 
book last night. Martinez struck out five in two innings, leading 
the American League over the Nationals 4-1 for its third straight 
win. Martinez became the first pitcher to strike out the first 
three hitters in an All-Star game, fanning Barry Larkin, Larry 
Walker and Sammy Sosa. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
  	   	
</P>
