<HEADLINE> Hill Agrees To Race One More Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SILVERSTONE, England (AP) -- Former world drivers' champion Damon  
Hill ended speculation of retirement and announced today he would 
race for the remainder of the season for the Jordan Formula One 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	The 38-year-old Briton had threatened to quit after crashing out  
of last month's French Grand Prix, but a fifth-place finish at last 
Sunday's British GP -- expected to be his last race -- enticed him to 
continue racing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am looking forward to helping the Jordan team achieve its  
highest-ever constructors' championship position,'' Hill said in a 
statement released by the Silverstone-based team. 
</P>
<P>
	Team chief Eddie Jordan said Hill's decision to finish the year  
was a major boost for Jordan. 
</P>
<P>
	``His contribution to this massive team effort is invaluable and  
we are all eagerly anticipating the last eight races,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill, currently on vacation with his family in Spain, will  
rejoin the team this week for testing at Monza, Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan is currently third in the constructors' championship.  
</P>
<P>
	Hill, the 1996 world drivers' champion, cited poor form and a  
lack of enthusiasm for his desire to quit racing following the 
French GP, which was won by his teammate Heinz-Harald Frentzen. 
</P>
<P>
	Following a week of intense speculation, Hill agreed to race at  
Silverstone to bid farewell to his fans but didn't make any 
statement about his future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
