<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House To Debate Spending Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House wants to spend $30 million to help  
states buy land for parks, though lawmakers would still provide far 
less than President Clinton wants for such purchases. 
</P>
<P>
	The House hoped to complete its debate today on a $14.1 billion  
measure financing the Interior Department and federal cultural 
programs. On Tuesday, lawmakers voted 213-202 to amend it by 
requiring that $30 million be spent for grants to all 50 states 
from the now-dormant land and water conservation fund. 
</P>
<P>
	The fund has not distributed money to the states since 1994. It  
collects $900 million annually from offshore oil and gas drilling 
leases. Sixty percent of the money is to be used for state grants 
and the rest for federal land acquisition. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the program, states receiving the federal grants must  
provide an equal amount of money. 
</P>
<P>
	The language was sponsored by Reps. James McGovern, D-Mass.; Tom  
Campbell, R-Calif.; Joseph Hoeffel, D-Pa.; and Rush Holt, D-N.J. It 
was supported 157-45 by Democrats and opposed 157-55 by 
Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the sponsors' victory, the bill provides less than  
one-third of the near $800 million Clinton requested for federal 
and state land purchases under his so-called ``lands legacy'' 
proposal. And the amendment's fate is uncertain because the Senate 
version of the bill contains no such language. 
</P>
<P>
	The $30 million would come from cutting coal research and other  
programs in the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	In the same measure, the House rejected an effort by Rep. Tom  
Coburn, R-Okla., to cut $2 million from the Fish and Wildlife 
Service's $711 million resource management program. The 287-131 
vote marked a setback for ongoing conservative efforts to trim 
spending bills. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, the Interior measure contains nearly $200 million less  
than this year's bill and nearly $1.2 billion less than Clinton has 
requested. The House planned to continue debating the bill on 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would also provide less than Clinton wants for land and  
water conservation, restoration of Florida's Everglades and energy 
conservation. 
</P>
<P>
	The House also approved an $8.4 billion measure financing  
construction at U.S. military bases in the United States and abroad 
for the coming year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
