<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 14:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Frankel Targeted Southern States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Martin Frankel, the fugitive suspected  
of bilking insurance companies out of hundreds of millions of 
dollars, was smart to do business in the South, where experts say 
there is often little state oversight of the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``No question about it. He took advantage of small states that  
don't have the horses to keep up with what he was doing,'' said Bob 
Hunter, insurance director for the Consumer Federation of America 
and former Texas insurance commissioner. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankel, a Greenwich, Conn., money manager who vanished in May,  
is suspected of embezzling at least $215 million -- and perhaps as 
much as $915 million -- from seven insurance companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Six were in the South -- three in Mississippi, and one each in  
Arkansas, Tennessee and Oklahoma -- and one was a Southern border 
state, Missouri, which was known in the '80s for its lax industry 
regulations. The insurers' parent company was Tennessee-based 
Thunor Trust. 
</P>
<P>
	Two Southern states have reputations for tight insurance  
regulations -- Texas and Florida -- but most others ``are 
understaffed and don't have the funds to chase around a 
billion-dollar industry,'' said Brendan Bridgeland of the Center 
for Insurance Research in Cambridge, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee's insurance department's budget ranks near the bottom.  
It amounts to 0.04 percent of the premiums state residents pay, 
compared with 0.17 percent for Florida, according to the National 
Association of Insurance Commissioners. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1996 Money magazine story on insurance regulation included a  
list of states where insurers have strong influence over state 
regulators and lawmakers. Ten of the top 12 were in the South. The 
others were Missouri and Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankel allegedly controlled Thunor Trust, set up in 1991 by  
Franklin businessman John Hackney to buy small, struggling 
insurance companies. Through his lawyer, Hackney has denied any 
wrongdoing and said he is a victim of Frankel. 
</P>
<P>
	Those insurance companies believed their policyholder money was  
being invested through Frankel's brokerage firm, Liberty National 
Securities. But apparently, no trades were ever made. Instead, 
prosecutors say Frankel stole the money. 
</P>
<P>
	Regulators in the affected states say they should be applauded  
for discovering what was happening before the problem got any 
worse. Before he fled, Frankel reportedly was pursuing deals that 
would have vastly enlarged his insurance empire. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tennessee department examiners began to ask questions as far  
back as last year about some of the things that were bothersome to 
them,'' said Mississippi Insurance Commissioner George Dale. 
</P>
<P>
	``Usually if an insurance company is in financial difficulty,  
the red flags are going to be consumer complaints, slowness in 
paying claims. That wasn't the case here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, there were potential red flags. One was extremely heavy  
trading and remarkable returns as high as 20 percent that the 
insurers believed they were earning on investments of U.S. Treasury 
bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	Oklahoma regulators noticed something strange during a 1997  
review of one of Frankel's companies, Insurance Commissioner 
Carroll Fisher said. Farmers and Ranchers Life Insurance Co. of 
Oklahoma City had made a large number of securities transactions 
with Liberty National. Examiners traced the trades and were 
satisfied they were legal. 
</P>
<P>
	If they had taken their probe one step further, they might have  
made a startling discovery, Carroll conceded: Frankel wasn't 
allowed to run a brokerage. 
</P>
<P>
	The Securities and Exchange Commission had stripped his license  
several years earlier, and Liberty National was an unlicensed 
brokerage. It took the same name as a licensed Michigan firm that 
had nowhere near the assets to handle such heavy trades. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee regulators say they kept a close eye on Thunor Trust  
and its one in-state insurer, Franklin American Life Insurance Co. 
</P>
<P>
	State examiners questioned unusually heavy trading of Franklin  
American bonds, but they received copies of financial statements 
that appeared to back them up, so no action was taken, said Marilyn 
Elam, a spokeswoman for the state Department of Commerce and 
Insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't until Franklin American and Liberty National  
flagrantly violated a state law that regulators took action. 
</P>
<P>
	The state requires an insurance company's assets be kept in a  
bank, but Liberty National had control of them. The state ordered 
the company to place the bonds in a bank, which was done, but then 
regulators discovered the bonds had been removed again. 
</P>
<P>
	They ordered the money placed in another bank. When Frankel  
fled, the state seized $57 million from the account. 
</P>
<P>
	Elam dismissed critics who say Tennessee does not aggressively  
regulate insurers. She said Tennessee is a ``free enterprise 
state'' that wants to protect policyholders without being ``so 
heavy-footed that we squash the rights of businesses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, John Summers, a Nashville lawyer and lobbyist who often  
battles the insurance industry, said the relationship between the 
state and the insurance industry is too cozy. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's virtually no regulation,'' he said. ``What you have is  
the fox guarding the henhouse.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
