<DOCNO> APW19990714.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 13:10:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Bank Rescue Funds Still Short </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Big bond issues not enough to replenish Thai bank rescue fund    	
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- More money will likely have to be  
raised for Thailand's rescue fund for failing financial 
institutions, the central bank's governor said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Chatu Mongol Sonakul told reporters that $13.5 billion in bond  
issues to date has been insufficient to cover losses by the 
nation's financial institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	The struggling rescue fund illustrates the difficulties still  
facing the financial system two years after the country was knocked 
into recession. 
</P>
<P>
	Chatu Mongol did not say whether he had proposed any means to  
replenish the rescue fund, nor did he say whether he has discussed 
the matter with the Finance Ministry, the lead player in restoring 
the country's economic health. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, the fund spent about $27 billion to shore up weak  
financial institutions, with much of the money borrowed from the 
domestic market. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, 56 non-bank finance companies have been shut down by  
the government and seven commercial banks have been nationalized by 
the central bank. The fund is the largest creditor to all of these 
failed institutions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
