<DOCNO> APW19990714.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 16:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AlliedSignal Earnings Up 13 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MORRIS TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) -- Sweeping reorganization, cost  
cutting and shifts to some higher-profit products helped 
AlliedSignal Inc. post a 13 percent jump in second-quarter 
earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Income from continuing operations was up 12 percent, on sharply  
higher profits in the aerospace systems, turbine technologies and 
transportation products divisions within AlliedSignal, which is 
awaiting shareholder approval of its planned merger with Honeywell 
Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	AlliedSignal, which also makes automotive products, chemicals  
and advanced materials, reported net income for the April-June 
quarter totaling $395 million, or 70 cents per share, matching 
estimates from analysts surveyed by First Call. 
</P>
<P>
	In the year-ago period, AlliedSignal earned $350 million, or 61  
cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	Net income was $400 million, or 71 cents per share, including  
one-time pretax charges of $258 million, primarily for severance 
pay and reorganization in its aerospace business. AlliedSignal also 
recorded a pretax gain of $268 million from selling its stock in 
Harrisburg, Pa.-based AMP after AlliedSignal failed in its hostile 
takeover bid last year of the world's largest maker of electrical 
and electronic interconnection systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales in the second quarter slipped to $3.82 billion from $3.87  
billion, hurt by double-digit declines in sales of performance 
polymers and specialty chemicals and electronic solutions. 
Excluding company divestitures, sales were up 5 percent, 
AlliedSignal said. 
</P>
<P>
	``AlliedSignal is in the midst of an extensive and accelerating  
business transformation'' unprecedented in the company, said 
Lawrence A. Bossidy, chairman and chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	That includes a companywide program to increase productivity and  
customer satisfaction, layoffs related to the Honeywell merger, and 
a new business plan including use of the Internet for sales, 
finding cheaper sources of raw materials, and receiving prototype 
designs for products customers want. 
</P>
<P>
	AlliedSignal said it will hold a special shareholders meeting on  
Sept. 1 for approval of its merger with Minneapolis-based 
Honeywell. Under the proposed deal, AlliedSignal would buy 
Honeywell for about $15 billion in stock, creating a $24 billion 
industrial powerhouse that makes everything from aircraft landing 
systems to home thermostats. 
</P>
<P>
	The new company would keep Honeywell's better-known name, but  
use Morris Township as its headquarters. The companies said they 
will cut 4,500 jobs while combining their work forces of 120,000 
people in more than 95 countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of AlliedSignal rose $1.25 to $66.25 in trading on the  
New York Stock Exchange. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
