<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Up on Dry Weather / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures advanced Wednesday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade as hot, dry weather moved into Midwest 
growing regions. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were concerned about pockets of dryness across major  
growing areas, particularly in central Illinois, one of the 
nation's largest corn and soybean growing states. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures across the region were expected to rise into the  
90s over the next few days, which could further drain moisture from 
the soil and lead to heat stress. That, in turn, could lead to 
reduced yields. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 1 1/4 cents to $2.60 1/2 a bushel;  
December corn rose 4 1/2 cents to $2.01 a bushel; December oats rose 3/4 
cent to $1.09 1/2 a bushel; November soybeans rose 1 1/4 cents to $4.21 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef and pork bellies futures were mixed on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange, while lean hogs advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle rose .53 cent to 63.65 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .28 cent to 77.25 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs rose 1.53 cents to 45.95 cents a pound; August pork bellies 
fell .32 cent to 32.95 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
