<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Iran Hard-Liners Rally 100,000  
</P>
<P>
	DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- Iranian hard-liners sent  
100,000 people into the streets of Tehran to make it clear they 
will not cave in to student-led demands for reforms. The hard-line 
backlash jeopardizes the standing of President Mohammad Khatami, a 
moderate clergyman and hero to the many Iranians who yearn for 
greater freedom after 20 years of strict Islamic rule by the 
clergy. 

</P>
<P>
	Taiwan Leader Denies Policy Change  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwanese President Lee Teng-hui, who  
sparked an uproar by insisting Beijing deal with Taiwan 
``state-to-state'' and not as part of China, told Washington on 
Wednesday he's not seeking formal independence that could prompt 
China to go to war. Lee said his new definition of the delicate 
Taiwan-China relationship merely clarifies the political reality 
that has emerged 50 years after the island separated from China, 
when the communists gained control of the mainland. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate GOP Tallies HMO Victories  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Republicans refused to extend new HMO  
rules to all 161 million people with private health insurance 
today. GOP leaders crafted alternatives to other Democratic 
proposals in an effort to blunt political damage. Only a handful of 
Republicans have defected in a series of votes this week over the 
details of new patient protections. That's partly because 
Republicans answered -- or promised to answer -- Democratic proposals 
on emergency room care, women's health and clinical trials. 

</P>
<P>
	Kasich Exits Race, Endorses Bush  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. John Kasich of Ohio shelved his Oval  
Office dreams today and threw his support behind Texas Gov. George 
Bush, the GOP front-runner. Crushed under the Bush financial 
steamroller, he was the second Republican presidential candidate to 
drop out of the race this week after Sen. Bob Smith, who abandoned 
the GOP to run as an independent. 

</P>
<P>
	Suspect Linked in 9th Murder  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- The man accused of being the railroad killer was  
linked to a ninth slaying and charged with capital murder 
Wednesday. Shortly after Angel Maturino Resendez appeared in court 
on a burglary charge in Houston, authorities said they had him 
linked by a palm print to a ninth slaying -- that of an 87-year-old 
woman who was bludgeoned in her home with an antique iron last 
October. 

</P>
<P>
	Boston Votes To End School Busing  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A generation after Boston erupted in violence over  
court-ordered busing to desegregate public schools, the school 
board voted Wednesday to end busing in a city where the vast 
majority of pupils are now minorities. The Boston school board 
voted 5-2 to end busing in a city where much has changed since the 
1974 federal court order that forced the city to bus white students 
into black neighborhoods and vice versa. 

</P>
<P>
	Human Cell Research Debated  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton's top ethics advisers are  
close to recommending a change in federal law to allow the 
government to finance a certain type of human embryo research. The 
issue is over experiments with ``master cells,'' the building 
blocks for other tissues in the body that scientists can cull from 
human embryos. These embryonic stem cells are generating huge 
excitement because they could lead to new therapies for Alzheimer's 
and other devastating diseases. But the use of them has raised 
troubling ethical questions, and is generating opposition from 
anti-abortion forces and some members of Congress. 

</P>
<P>
	Apple's Earnings Beat Expectations  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Apple Computer Inc.'s profit nearly doubled in  
the recent quarter, easily beating Wall Street forecasts, as demand 
surged for the company's iMac desktop computer. The results 
released Wednesday offered the latest evidence of a resurgence at 
Apple this past year, further easing any doubts over the company's 
prospects. Apple's profit in its fiscal third quarter rose to $203 
million, or $1.20 a share. That was up from a profit of $101 
million, or 65 cents a share, in the year-ago quarter. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Rise, Nikkei Gains 26.92  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices gained in early trading Thursday  
following strength in high-technology shares in New York. The 
Nikkei rose 35.23 to 18,393.09. In New York today, the Dow 
industrials ended down 26.92 at 11,148.10. The Nasdaq rose 39.90 to 
2,818.13, a record. 

</P>
<P>
	West Wins WNBA All-Star Game  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Western Conference stars defeated the  
Eastern Conference 79-61 in the first-ever WNBA All-Star game. Lisa 
Leslie was named the game's MVP, while rookie sensation Chamique 
Holdsclaw suffered a chip fracture on her left index finger. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LINDA KIM  
  	   	
</P>
