<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of America To Go Wireless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Bank of America customers next year will  
be able to do their banking with mobile phones, electronic 
organizers and other handheld, Internet-connected, wireless 
devices. 
</P>
<P>
	Charlotte-based Bank of America on Wednesday announced a deal  
with Toronto-based 724 Solutions Inc. The technology company will 
provide software to let Bank of America's 30 million U.S. customers 
to accomplish banking transactions with wireless communication 
devices, including cellular phones, hand-held organizers and 
``smart phones,'' which are a hybrid of the two. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of America says it will be the first major U.S. financial  
institution to offer wireless banking. Currently, customers who 
want to do online or Internet-based banking have to use a personal 
computer or a television set-top device, which run through 
telephone or cable lines. 
</P>
<P>
	But sales of wireless communication devices are growing. Nearly  
12.2 million non-PC Internet-access devices will be sold next year, 
nearly matching personal computer sales, according to International 
Data Corp. Last year, there were 64.4 million mobile phones in use 
in the United States; by 2003 that will have risen to 118 million, 
said Callie Pottorf, research analyst with International Data. 
</P>
<P>
	Not many of today's mobile phones connect to the Internet. But  
by the end of this year, there may be more than 30 models that 
will, Pottorf said. And Jupiter Communications predicts more than 
10 million mobile phones will be capable of accessing Internet data 
by 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, the Bank of Montreal signed a similar agreement with 724  
Solutions. But Bank of America will have a ``more substantial'' 
rollout of the service, said Greg Wolfond, 724 founder and chief 
executive. 
</P>
<P>
	It remains to be seen how many bank customers will want to do  
routine banking so often that they will use a handheld, wireless 
device. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're a regular consumer with a regular bank account, a PC  
is sufficient to keep on top of your (account) balances,'' said 
Bruce Kasrel, senior analyst with Forrester Research. Active stock 
traders are more likely users of the technology, he said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 13:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
