<HEADLINE> Britain Leads at Admiral's Cup Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COWES, Isle of Wight (AP) -- Britain took a lead in the Admiral's  
Cup on Wednesday after an opening day filled with chaos and 
collisions. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before the weather had a chance to take its toll off the  
Isle of Wight coast, France quit the competition and then rejoined 
with a smaller team to add high drama to the unofficial world 
championship of off-shore racing. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States, defending titlist, shared fifth-place with  
Australia in the aggregate standings after a day described by 
American skipper Ken Read as ``the strangest day on the water I've 
ever had.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Admiral's Cup commenced with behind the scenes wrangling  
which forced France to initially withdraw in a row over an illegal 
mast on one of its three boats. 
</P>
<P>
	France rejoined the competition with its remaining two boats,  
resulting in several difficult clashes for the three-boat U.S. 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	Read, helmsman on the biggest American boat 'Idler' - which has  
a crew containing six America's Cup sailors - said he was stunned 
by some of the events during a testing day on the water. 
</P>
<P>
	'Idler' was involved in a crunching collision with Dutch boat  
'Innovision' in the second race of the day. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had just turned on the mark and the Dutch boat was coming  
towards us,'' he said. ``She tried to jibe away but they got their 
turn wrong and hit us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Luckily it was a glancing blow - it's a miracle no-one was  
injured.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Idler finished sixth in the first race, won by Innovision, but  
grabbed second place in the afternoon race while the Dutch boat 
finished fifth. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
