<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Officials Start Ga. Quail Program / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, Ga. (AP) -- In the 1950s, Georgia was known as the quail  
capital of the world. The bobwhite quail thrived in weeds and 
shrubs around the edges of fields and found plenty of 
muscle-building bugs to eat. Quail hunting was a tradition in many 
families. 
</P>
<P>
	All that began to change in the 1960s. Urban sprawl and new  
farming techniques, including more reliance on pesticides, reduced 
the bird's habitat and food supply. As a result, Georgia's quail 
population has declined more than 70 percent in the past 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Wildlife officials hope they can reverse the trend this fall  
when they kick off a pilot program known as ``Georgia's Bobwhite 
Quail Initiative.'' It will offer incentives and cost-sharing 
payments to landowners who agree to provide quail habitat. 
</P>
<P>
	Landowners will have to develop management plans and compete for  
acceptance into the program, which includes counties in eastern, 
central and southwestern Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	The quail is a type of small bird that belongs to the same  
family as pheasants and partridges. The best known in North America 
is the bobwhite, which is heavily camouflaged to protect it from 
predators. Young and adult quail eat insects and seed. During the 
fall and winter, quail live in groups known as coveys. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a number of reasons we should be concerned about  
quail,'' said Reggie Thaxton, a senior wildlife biologist with the 
Georgia Department of National Resources Wildlife Resources 
Division in Forsyth. ``It's part of our heritage. We know there are 
a lot of people who like quail who aren't hunters. They enjoy 
hearing and seeing them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also, quail are considered an indicator species -- a barometer of  
the ecosystem, Thaxton said. 
</P>
<P>
	When quail have problems, other creatures that share their  
habitat have problems. Those creatures include songbirds such as 
the prairie warbler, the Bachman's sparrow and the loggerhead 
shrike. 
</P>
<P>
	The habitat they need is called ``early succession'' habitat,  
which includes such weeds as beggerweed and ragweed, shrubs such as 
plum and native grasses. The vegetation is generally less than 
knee-high. 
</P>
<P>
	``Quail and these early succession songbirds have been declining  
quite drastically since the '60s,'' said Thaxton, who will 
coordinate the initiative. ``This is a pro-active approach to 
trying to restore early succession habitat and thereby stop the 
decline before they reach critically low levels.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Landowners will be encouraged to create hedgerows and field  
boarders. Besides providing quail habitat, these areas help reduce 
soil erosion and stop the flow of sediment that can degrade water 
quality. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 07:50:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Slow Growth Seen for Health Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- National health care spending is projected to  
grow more slowly than had been expected in the next decade, the 
government said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The revised projection is due largely to decreased Medicare  
spending last year and slower growth projections for both private 
and Medicare spending in the latter part of the next decade, 
according to a study by the Health Care Financing Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the downward revision, national health spending still is  
expected to double by 2008 to $2.2 trillion, up from $1.1 trillion 
in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The new projections show the rate of annual growth slows to an  
average of 6.5 percent for the 1997-2007 decade. Last year's 
calculations had projected a 7 percent yearly average growth. 
</P>
<P>
	``These figures show that our efforts, such as waste, fraud and  
abuse initiatives, have helped control health care costs in the 
United States,'' said Donna Shalala, secretary of health and human 
services. 
</P>
<P>
	Medicare spending is projected to grow just 4.5 percent a year  
over the 1997-2000 period, compared to 5.1 percent foreseen in last 
year's figures, the study said. 
</P>
<P>
	The study indicates that national health spending growth will  
accelerate through 2000, due mostly to an acceleration in the 
private-sector. That reverses the current trend of higher public 
spending, and the reversal is expected to be more significant than 
anticipated last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Annual private-sector growth had been projected at 6.7 percent  
over 1997-2000 in last year's survey. The revised report forecasts 
a 7.3 percent annual growth in that time period, due largely to 
higher health insurance premiums and faster projected growth of 
drug spending. 
</P>
<P>
	For 2001 through 2008, both public and private-sector spending  
growth is projected to be slower than the levels projected last 
year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
