<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American Airlines Seeks Gov't Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- American Airlines has asked to meet  
with U.S. Justice Department lawyers this month about the 
government's claim that the nation's second-largest air carrier 
tried to drive small, startup airlines out of business. 
</P>
<P>
	American also is trying to schedule a meeting with Justice  
attorneys later this month in hopes of getting a court date set 
soon on the government's lawsuit claiming American saturated 
lower-cost competitor Vanguard Airlines' routes with additional 
flights and cutting fares. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice lawsuit, which is the first predatory-practices case  
brought since airlines were deregulated in 1978, alleges that 
American monopolized airline passenger service to and from 
Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport, the nation's third 
largest. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department said American increased its prices  
between Dallas-Fort Worth and Wichita by 50 percent after it forced 
Vanguard Airlines out of that route. 
</P>
<P>
	As well as the attorneys' meeting, American filed a response to  
the Justice Department charge Tuesday requesting that Judge J. 
Thomas Marten schedule a pretrial conference in August. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline said in its response that it is ``well within the  
law'' in its scheduling practices. 
</P>
<P>
	Also yesterday, American Airlines won dismissal of a passenger  
lawsuit alleging that the carrier was predatory in its pricing. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Wilkie D. Ferguson of Ft. Lauderdale, Fla.,  
dismissed the claims that American cost passengers more money for 
tickets by driving low-fare airlines out of markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Customer Matthew Zifrony had alleged in the lawsuit that  
American helped force Pan American Airlines out of Miami and 
Vanguard Airlines Inc. out of routes to Dallas-Fort Worth. Zifrony 
could not be immediately reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	American's parent company, Fort Worth, Texas-based AMR Corp., is  
still contending with about a half-dozen similar civil lawsuits 
filed in Wichita, Kan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ultimately we think all of these civil lawsuits will be  
dismissed because they're without merit,'' said airline spokesman 
Chris Chiames. 
</P>
<P>
	The dismissed Florida lawsuit, which had requested the judge to  
bar American's allegedly anticompetitive conduct, was filed shortly 
before the lawsuit filed by the U.S. Justice Department. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
