<DOCNO> APW19990714.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 02:50:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Press Pet Causes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional Republicans still have a lot of  
loose ends on foreign policy and defense they want to tie as 
election season intensifies, many of them perennial causes, some of 
them probably lost causes. 
</P>
<P>
	The perennials range from demanding that the U.S. Embassy in  
Israel be moved to Jerusalem -- something that a would-be New York 
senator, Hillary Rodham Clinton, now is also espousing -- to scaling 
back U.S. support for the United Nations, denouncing Cuba's Fidel 
Castro and decrying human rights in China. 
</P>
<P>
	Debates over these issues -- and many more -- are looming in the  
days ahead as the House and Senate move toward completion of a 
variety of spending and authorization bills, and as the annual 
renewal of China's trade status heads toward a floor vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Presidential hopeful Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire scolded his  
now former fellow Republicans for not being true to their ideals or 
the party platform in announcing Tuesday that he was changing 
political stripes and becoming an independent. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's put out there so suckers like me and maybe suckers like  
you can read it,'' he said of the party platform in a floor speech. 
</P>
<P>
	But, GOP lawmakers have still been managing to slip bits and  
splinters of GOP dogma into a variety of amendments and 
resolutions. 
</P>
<P>
	The House later this week, for instance, is due to debate a  
State Department bill that would, among other things, pay roughly 
$1 billion in U.S. debt to the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	The House is expected to follow the Senate's lead in including a  
cutback in the U.S. contribution to the U.N.'s regular operating 
budget of 25 percent to 20 percent. Such a reduction has not been 
approved by other U.N. members. 
</P>
<P>
	At some point, either on the House floor or later in a  
conference with Senate negotiators on the State Department bill, 
Rep. Christopher Smith, R-N.J., is expected to push once more for 
an anti-abortion amendment. His measure would deny U.S. support for 
international family planning programs that support abortion 
rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years in a row, such a provision has drawn a veto from  
President Clinton, and likely would again. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department bill, which goes before the House Thursday,  
also contains nonbinding language advocating moving the U.S. 
Embassy from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem. 
</P>
<P>
	That's another perennial favorite, not only of Republicans but  
of many Democrats as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton joined the move-the-embassy bandwagon as she tested  
the waters of New York for a possible Senate bid, even though 
Clinton administration policy continues to say the city's future 
must be determined by Israelis and Palestinians in negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	The House on Monday approved a nonbinding resolution urging the  
United States to boycott this week's U.N. meeting in Geneva to look 
into whether Israel violated international law in building 
settlements on Arab-claimed land. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar resolutions -- which do not carry the force of law -- have  
been passed to reaffirm U.S. policy toward Taiwan, to denounce 
China's human rights record and to voice support for U.S. troops. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress keeps trying to pare support for a program that  
provides fuel oil to North Korea -- in hopes of dissuading that 
communist regime from expanding its nuclear program. And the Senate 
has voted to ban all foreign aid to Russia if it doesn't obey NATO 
commanders in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans also keep trying to fan dying embers of inquiries  
into Democratic fund raising and Chinese nuclear espionage. 
</P>
<P>
	When Attorney General Janet Reno appeared at a House hearing on  
Tuesday to talk about technology export controls, Rep. Steven 
Buyer, R-Ind., went out of his way to praise FBI Director Louis 
Freeh -- as he sat next to Reno. 
</P>
<P>
	He praised Freeh for good judgment in recommending an  
independent counsel on campaign fund raising, a course of action 
she rejected. Looking straight at Reno, Buyer apologized that he 
couldn't spread the praise ``around the table.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., hinted the House might revive a  
dormant threat to hold Reno in contempt if she continued to 
withhold parts of a Justice Department memo Weldon suggested was 
relevant to the inquiry into whether technology transfers to China 
were influenced by Chinese campaign contributions to Clinton's 
re-election campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno, in a tight voice, told Weldon the department had provided  
Congress ``with everything we could under the law.'' Holding her in 
contempt, she noted dryly, ``wouldn't change the law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Tom Raum covers national and international  
affairs for The Associated Press. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
