<HEADLINE> Suspect Mistakenly Freed Surrenders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- An Arizona murder suspect who was  
mistakenly released from jail in a paperwork mix-up has surrendered 
to authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen Brown, 37, charged with stabbing his girlfriend more than  
100 times, turned himself in to FBI and Kansas City, Mo., 
investigators Tuesday, a week after he was let out of Pima County 
Jail. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, 37, was indicted on July 2 on a charge of first-degree  
murder in the May 22 death of Carol Buvik-Arnold, 37. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown's mother in Kansas City told investigators Tuesday she  
wanted to help her son turn himself in. Later in the day, his 
Tucson attorney, Richard Lougee, met with authorities here to 
negotiate his surrender. 
</P>
<P>
	His mother, Sharion Beaver, then took investigators to where  
Brown was staying. He hugged his mother and then was taken into 
custody, said Pima County sheriff's Sgt. Brad Foust. 
</P>
<P>
	Lougee said he expects Brown will waive an extradition hearing  
and be returned to Tucson. 
</P>
<P>
	Foust said ``a communications breakdown'' resulted in the  
wrongful release. 
</P>
<P>
	But Superior Court Clerk Patricia Noland said three copies of  
the indictment had been sent to the jail. 
  	   	
</P>
