<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lucent Unveils Laser Network System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MURRAY HILL, N.J. (AP) -- Lucent Technologies today unveiled a  
new networking system that transmits information on a laser light 
beam through the air, cutting out the need for underground cables. 
</P>
<P>
	The WaveStar OpticAir system uses dense wavelength division  
multiplexing, or DWDM, which combines voice, data and video 
information on a light beam. 
</P>
<P>
	DWDM can transmit data at 10 billion bits per second, Lucent  
says, while the fastest phone line can move data about 1.5 million 
bits per second. 
</P>
<P>
	The WaveStar system takes information from a traditional  
landline, such as fiber optic cable, shoots it through a two-inch 
wide amplifying lens to a receiver up to three miles away, which 
then distributes the information through a network via cable. 
</P>
<P>
	One drawback to the system is that nothing, such as a building,  
can obstruct the beam as it travels from the amplifying lens to the 
receiver. 
</P>
<P>
	But the ability to expand a network without having to install  
underground fiber optic cable overshadows this drawback, Lucent 
spokeswoman Mary Ward said. 
</P>
<P>
	For instance, she said, a local network provider doesn't have to  
go to a city and ask them to dig up streets so that more fiber 
optic cable can be laid down. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucent's system will be field-tested this December, with the  
company hoping for a commercial release by March 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Lucent, based in Murray Hill, N.J., is one of the world's  
largest providers of telecommunications equipment and services and 
was once a part of AT&AMP;T Corp. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
