<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Earns $2.48B in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- Ford Motor Co., profiting from robust car  
and truck sales in the United States, reported today that its 
second-quarter operating earnings rose 4 percent to $2.48 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's No. 2 automaker earned $2 a share on an operating  
basis for the April-June period compared with $2.38 billion, or 
$1.91 a share, for the same period of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The results surpassed the company's previous for high quarterly  
operating earnings of $2.42 billion in the second quarter of 1997 
and included profits from Associates First Capital, a finance unit 
since divested. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales totaled $42.3 billion, up 13 percent from $37.3 billion a  
year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford's operating earnings exceeded Wall Street analysts'  
expectations. The average estimate of 15 analysts surveyed by First 
Call Corp. was $1.95 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's stock rose 75 cents to $54.25 a share in early  
trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The profit improvement was largely the result of rising  
automotive earnings in North America. Ford continued to struggle in 
Europe and South America. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a great quarter in North America, offset by a  
continuing poor performance overseas,'' said analyst John Casesa of 
Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. ``The quarter is a reminder that despite what 
is clearly a compelling vision to transform the company 
longer-term, there are some near-term challenges that Ford needs to 
address.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Industry sales in the United States are on pace to set a record  
this year, barring a strike or other major event that severely 
restricts production or demand. Ford said it earned just under $2 
billion in the region, up 19 percent from the April through June 
period of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are so many positive factors at work in the U.S. economy  
right now,'' President Jac Nasser said. ``We're confident vehicle 
sales will remain strong through the balance of 1999 and into 
2000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Ford executives said continued cost-cutting also was a  
significant factor. Automotive costs declined by $300 million in 
the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our strong earnings momentum over the last 13 quarters is the  
result of our intense drive to improve quality, lower costs and 
become more nimble,'' Nasser said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford's net earnings were $2.34 billion, or $1.89 a share,  
including a one-time profit reduction of $146 million related to 
its acquisition of the car unit of Sweden's Volvo AB. Ford said 
that under U.S. accounting rules, it was required to write-up the 
inventory it acquired from Volvo to its fair value, resulting in 
the increase in cost of sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford earned $89 million in Europe as Volvo results reduced its  
European profits by $125 million. Excluding Volvo, Ford earned $214 
million, down 31 percent from the $310 million earned a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The European results reflect lower sales of the aging Fiesta  
subcompact and Mondeo compact sedans and fewer exports, which were 
offset by strong initial sales of the new Focus subcompact and a 
better performance by Ford's Jaguar unit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ford Motor Co.'s market share is up in Europe, but restoring  
our profits in the region to a more robust level will take time and 
a continued focus on great products, quality and lower costs,'' 
Nasser said. 
</P>
<P>
	In South America, Ford lost $120 million, compared with earnings  
of $14 million a year ago. Ford blamed the downturn in Brazil, 
where vehicle sales declined 20 percent industrywide in the first 
half. Ford said it expects the Brazilian economy to remain weak for 
the rest of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	First-half operating earnings totaled $4.32 billion, up 11  
percent from the $3.9 billion in the first six months of 1998. 
Revenues during the period totaled $80.2 billion, an 8.5 percent 
increase from $73.9 billion in the first half of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ford's problems in Brazil are not intractable, but meaningful  
improvement will take creativity and ingenuity on our part, a 
continued focus on costs, and government policies that encourage 
sustainable economic growth,'' Nasser said. 
</P>
<P>
	Net income from worldwide automotive operations was $1.9  
billion, down $120 million from 1998's second quarter. But 
excluding the Volvo profit reduction, automotive earnings totaled 
$2.1 billion, up 1 percent from $2.05 billion a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford said its automotive cash reserve totaled $24 billion at the  
end of the quarter, up from $22.3 billion a year earlier. Minus 
outstanding debt, Ford's net cash was $12.6 billion, down from 
$14.1 billion a year ago because of the Volvo purchase and other 
acquisitions. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first six months, Ford said it reduced automotive costs  
by $400 million. Its full-year goal is a reduction of $1 billion 
from 1998 levels. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford's Visteon Automotive Systems parts unit earned $282 million  
in the second quarter, up 17 percent from $241 a year ago. For the 
first half, Visteon earned $490 million, a 14 percent improvement 
from $430 million earned in the same period of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford Credit earned $335 million in the quarter, up 12 percent  
from $300 million a year ago. Ford's Hertz rental-car unit posted 
an $88 million profit, up 17 percent from $75 million. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
