<DOCNO> APW19990714.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 15:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rules Eyed After Internet Mergers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Recent mergers of cable TV companies could  
mean higher Internet access prices for rural residents and perhaps 
lead to new regulations, some senators are suggesting. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Orrin Hatch, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee,  
said Wednesday that the 1996 law deregulating cable television 
prices did not anticipate the impact mergers might have on the race 
among telecommunications companies to provide fast cable Internet 
access, called ``broadband.'' 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T's recent takeover of the large cable company  
Tele-Communications Inc. and its plan to buy MediaOne are 
intensifying debate over whether to force cable businesses to share 
their high-speed lines with competitors -- something America Online, 
consumer groups and some phone companies want. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Communications Commission has declined to force  
high-speed line sharing. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch, R-Utah, and the chairman of the Senate Commerce  
Committee, Republican John McCain of Arizona, are considering 
whether Congress should act to prevent companies from freezing out 
competitors or restricting consumers' options for Internet service. 
</P>
<P>
	But they left open the possibility that the market in the future  
-- through the expected big growth in high-speed Internet services -- 
could serve as a check on the power of individual companies, making 
new regulations unnecessary. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T and a few lawmakers predicted that the marketplace would  
straighten out the problem in the long-run. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are encouraging an open system,'' C. Michael Armstrong,  
chairman and CEO of AT&AMP;T, said at a Judiciary Committee hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just let it rip,'' agreed Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y. ``Since  
we're doing so well in the private sector, why should the 
government get involved?'' 
</P>
<P>
	A day earlier, that is what Broward County, Fla., did. By 4-3,  
county commissioners voted to require AT&AMP;T to open its cable 
network to competing Internet service providers in an effort to 
foster competition between local companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Telephone companies' high-speed Internet services are subject to  
federal regulations. Cable companies' provision of these services 
are not. 
</P>
<P>
	Broadband access over cable lines offers connection speeds  
dozens of times faster than today's standard telephone modems 
hooked to regular phone lines. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable, telephone, satellite and wireless companies, however, are  
all racing against each other to provide high-speed connections to 
consumers and businesses, using various technologies. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeing consumers from the sluggish performance of the Internet,  
high-speed connections will finally make possible new computer 
applications that include TV-quality video and better audio on the 
Web. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 16:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Apple's Earnings Beat Expectations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Apple Computer Inc.'s profit nearly doubled in  
the recent quarter, easily beating Wall Street forecasts, as demand 
surged for the company's iMac desktop computer. 
</P>
<P>
	The results released Wednesday offered the latest evidence of a  
resurgence at Apple this past year, further easing any doubts over 
the company's prospects. 
</P>
<P>
	Apple's profit in its fiscal third quarter rose to $203 million,  
or $1.20 a share. That was up from a profit of $101 million, or 65 
cents a share, in the year-ago quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding a one-time gain, Apple would have earned $114 million,  
or 69 cents a share in the three months ended June 26, exceeding 
the 64 cents projected by analysts surveyed by First Call. 
</P>
<P>
	Apple released its financial results after the markets closed.  
Apple shares were trading at $56 in after-hours trading after 
jumping 4 percent, or $2.25, during the regular trading session on 
the Nasdaq Stock Market to close at $55.93 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue rose 11 percent to $1.56 billion from $1.40 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	Apple, based in Cupertino, Calif., credited a 40 percent rise in  
unit sales of computers, fueled by the iMac. Apple's share of 
retail desktop sales was 6.7 percent in May, double that of a year 
ago, according to ZD Infobeads research firm. 
</P>
<P>
	The iMac desktop, which has spurred a design shakeup in the PC  
industry since its introduction last August, is shaped like a giant 
jelly bean, equipped with a built-in monitor, and comes in five 
translucent colors through which inner circuitry is faintly 
visible. 
</P>
<P>
	Apple also profited from an unexpected drop in the cost of iMac  
parts, including memory and microprocessor chips, chief financial 
officer Fred Anderson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The results were somewhat offset by higher expenses as Apple  
added 500 workers for a total work force of 8,800. 
</P>
<P>
	Apple said its sales and growth rate are expected to rise  
slightly the next quarter, but will increase more strongly as the 
company rolls out new product lines, Anderson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Apple is widely expected to introduce a new consumer laptop to  
the market next week, but has declined to comment. 
</P>
<P>
	In the nine months ended June 26, Apple earned $490 million, or  
$2.99 a share, up from earnings of $203 million, or $1.40 a share, 
in the year-ago period. Revenues rose to $4.80 billion from $4.36 
billion. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
