<HEADLINE> ABC To Broadcast NHL All-Stars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ABC, which takes over hockey games from Fox this  
season, will show four regional telecasts and the NHL All-Star game 
in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney Corp., which owns both ABC and ESPN, acquired the rights  
to the NHL in August for $600 million over five years. Fox's deal, 
which ran from 1994-99, was worth about $30 million a season. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC's first broadcast will be the NHL All-Star game on Feb. 6 in  
Toronto. The network will also show weekend coverage for the first 
three rounds of the playoffs and up to five Stanley Cup finals 
games in prime time. 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN, which was part of the NHL package with Fox for the past  
five seasons, opens with the Pittsburgh Penguins at Dallas Stars on 
Oct. 1 at 7:30 p.m. The cable network has increased the number of 
games on ESPN2 from 75 last season to 102 in 1999-2000. 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN will air up to 27 regular-season games, playoff coverage  
and the first two games of the Stanley Cup Finals. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
