<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Acclaimed Writer Williams Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Sherley Ann Williams, an author who used her  
experience as a migrant farmworker to write a critically acclaimed 
novel about black slavery, has died. She was 54. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Williams died of cancer July 8, said Kate Callen, a  
spokeswoman for the University of California at San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Williams had been working on a novel and a sequel to her  
1986 historical novel, ``Dessa Rose,'' a story about a privileged 
Charleston bride and a young pregnant slave. The New York Times 
praised the novel as ``artistically brilliant, emotionally 
affecting and totally unforgettable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Williams' first book of verse, ``The Peacock Poems,'' was  
nominated for a Pulitzer Prize and a National Book Award in 1975. 
Her second book of verse, ``Some One Sweet Angel Chile,'' was 
another National Book Award nominee, and a TV performance based on 
the book won an Emmy Award. 
</P>
<P>
	Her 1992 children's book ``Working Cotton'' received the  
American Library Association Caldecott Award. 
</P>
<P>
	She also wrote a one-woman drama called ``Letters From a New  
England Negro'' that was performed at the National Black Theater 
Festival in 1991 and at the Chicago International Theater Festival 
in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Williams was born in Bakersfield and grew up in Fresno,  
where her parents were migrant workers. As a child, she loved to 
read, but her mother tried to discourage her from reading so she 
wouldn't develop ambitions she might not be able to fulfill. 
</P>
<P>
	An eighth-grade science teacher encouraged her to pursue  
college, but her parents died by the time she was 16 and she 
survived by picking crops in the same fields where they had 
labored. 
</P>
<P>
	She attended California State University at Fresno, where she  
earned a bachelor's degree in English. After obtaining her master's 
degree in American literature at Brown University, she joined the 
literature department at UC San Diego in 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	She is survived by a son, a sister and three grandchildren.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
