<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Helicopter Maker To Cut 1,100 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Helicopter maker Sikorsky Aircraft Corp.  
plans to cut 1,100 jobs from its work force -- most of them in 
Connecticut -- citing a need to reduce overhead and become more 
competitive in a global marketplace. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also said Wednesday it plans to close some of its 10  
plants in the state, but company spokesman William Tuttle would not 
identify the factories targeted for closure. 
</P>
<P>
	All but about 1,000 of Sikorsky's 8,100 employees are in  
Connecticut. The company also has plants in West Palm Beach, Fla., 
Troy, Ala., and smaller facilities around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the plants outside Connecticut will be affected by the  
cuts, Tuttle said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sikorsky is a division of Hartford-based United Technologies  
Corp. Among its helicopters are: the Black Hawk, used in a variety 
of military operations; the Seahawk, used by navies all over the 
world; the Comanche, used by the U.S. Army; and aircraft for civil 
applications, including medical rescue choppers. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it planned to offer early retirement packages  
for salaried and hourly employees who are 55 and older and have at 
least 10 years of service. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuttle would not say how many employees the company expected to  
lay off and how many may take the early retirement deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're hoping to allay layoffs,'' Tuttle said. ``We're putting  
the emphasis on packages right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sikorsky has cut nearly 2,200 jobs over the past five years,  
including 500 already in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, Sikorsky said the job cuts and plant closings  
are designed to strengthen its competitiveness as it continues a 
decade-long shift from reliance on U.S. government contracts toward 
commercial and international markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Through this restructuring, we will build a stronger  
competitive company to ensure our continuing leadership position in 
the global marketplace,'' said Sikorsky president Dean C. Borgman, 
who took office July 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, which has its headquarters in Stratford, is named  
for the inventor of the modern helicopter, Igor Sikorsky. 
</P>
<P>
	Other United Technologies divisions have seen layoffs and job  
cuts as the defense industry softened. Its jet engine division, 
Pratt &AMP; Whitney, last year announced it was eliminating 2,000 
positions. 
</P>
<P>
	Other United Technologies divisions include Carrier air  
conditioning equipment, Otis elevators and Hamilton Standard 
aerospace systems. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
