	During the manhunt, the FBI referred to him by one of his  
aliases, Rafael Resendez-Ramirez. 
</P>
<P>
	Until the murder charge was filed in Hughes Springs, the only  
charge against him in Texas was burglary, at the scene where Dr. 
Claudia Benton, 39, was killed Dec. 17 in the Houston enclave of 
West University Place. She was beaten in the head, stabbed three 
times in the back and covered with a blanket. 
</P>
<P>
	Maturino Resendez's fingerprints were found on parts from the  
woman's stolen car, and prosecutors said DNA evidence might also 
link him to the slaying. 
</P>
<P>
	After a prosecutor in Houston described the bloody scene of Ms.  
Benton's killing, Maturino Resendez, wearing an orange jail 
jumpsuit and handcuffs, calmly asked state District Judge William 
Harmon if he could plead guilty. 
</P>
<P>
	It was unclear whether Maturino Resendez was specifically  
addressing the burglary charge or all of the charges against him. 
His admission of guilt was not an official plea because his court 
appearances were only to set bail and assign him a lawyer. He was 
jailed without bail. 
</P>
<P>
	In Texas, a charge of capital murder can usually be filed only  
when there is evidence that a murder occurred during the commission 
of certain felonies, such as burglary. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision of whether to charge also Maturino Resendez with  
capital murder in Ms. Benton's death rests with Harris County 
District Attorney Johnny Holmes, whose county has notched the most 
death-penalty convictions in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 469 people on death row in Texas, 146 -- about one-third --  
were sent there by Harris County. If Harris County were a state, it 
would rank third in the number of people executed in the nation 
with 56. Virginia has executed 67. 
</P>
<P>
	After hiding out in Mexico, Maturino Resendez surrendered to a  
Texas Ranger at an El Paso border station Tuesday in a deal 
brokered by his sister. 
</P>
<P>
	It's still unclear why he turned himself in. Mexico doesn't have  
the death penalty and doesn't return suspects to countries where 
they may face the death penalty. But Mike Cox, a Texas Department 
of Public Safety spokesman, said Maturino Resendez may have feared 
bounty hunters. A $125,000 reward had been offered for his capture. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas' hold on Maturino Resendez also might mean Kentucky and  
Illinois officials never get to prosecute him. Lexington, Ky., 
police Sgt. Mark Barnard said he hopes that is not the case. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't care if he gets the death penalty seven times,''  
Barnard said. ``I want him in Kentucky.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maturino Resendez is thought to have traveled by hopping freight  
trains. All of the victims were killed near the tracks. 
Investigators have said they have no idea what motivated the 
killings. 
</P>
<P>
	The killing spree apparently started with the 1997 slaying of a  
21-year-old college student in Kentucky. The most recent slayings 
were those of a 79-year-old man and his 51-year-old daughter, found 
dead June 15 in Gorham, Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	Several hundred people in Weimar attended a ceremony Wednesday  
to pray and give thanks for the suspect's capture. As the sun set 
and a train whistle blew in the background, residents of the South 
Texas town hugged and cried. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0340 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 10:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Kosovo Visit Moves U.N. Prosecutor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- After walking amid the shoes and  
clothing of children buried at the site of a mass killing in 
western Kosovo, a top U.N. war crimes prosecutor said today she was 
``profoundly moved'' by what she had seen. 
</P>
<P>
	Louise Arbour, paying her first visit to the Serb province,  
toured one of the worst killing fields of the Kosovo conflict just 
a day after British forensic specialists discovered the bodies of 
11 children shot to death at close range in Celine. 
</P>
<P>
	War crimes investigators have exhumed 57 bodies so far from nine  
separate grave sites in the village, nine miles northwest of 
Prizren. British officials have said the dead are believed to have 
been shot by Serb forces just after NATO began bombing Kosovo on 
March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not possible to have this kind of experience and not be  
profoundly moved,'' Arbour said after visiting the dug-up graves 
and seeing the children's belongings. ``It's just too overwhelming 
to have the full visual impact.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a NATO spokesman said today that an anti-tank mine  
explosion in Kosovo killed one person and critically wounded 
another, the latest in an alarming number of deaths by mines in the 
province. 
</P>
<P>
	And NATO's supreme commander for Europe, U.S. Gen. Wesley Clark,  
said the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army was largely in compliance 
with demilitarization requirements -- although officials said strife 
between ethnic Albanians and Serbs in Kosovo continued. 
</P>
<P>
	Arbour, the chief prosecutor for the U.N. tribunal on war crimes  
in former Yugoslavia, stopped first at a grave site at Celine and 
headed later to a site in Vlastica, southeast of Pristina. 
</P>
<P>
	In Celine, Arbour walked up a hill and stopped by a grave with  
pink flowers in a clear plastic tube, where a teen-age girl was 
found buried. Then she continued up the hill and came to the 
10-by-20-foot grave site uncovered Tuesday by the British. 
</P>
<P>
	Eighteen of the 21 bodies found buried there by villagers were  
women and children; six were under the age of 10, including a 
2-year-old. Bedding, a child's pair of leather shoes and several 
shirts still littered the area. 
</P>
<P>
	As Arbour looked at the scene, village leader Hamdi Fazliu shook  
his head and said sadly: ``Baby, two years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	British officials have said all the dead are believed to have  
come from one family, shot by Serb forces on March 25 or March 26. 
The Serbs apparently discovered the villagers hiding in a dry 
riverbed hidden by trees and shot them, according to officials of 
the NATO-led peacekeeping force. 
</P>
<P>
	Fazliu said Serb forces had attacked the villagers out of  
revenge because they couldn't find any KLA fighters. 
</P>
<P>
	An international tribunal official, Keith Martin, said the  
bodies were being taken for autopsies at a temporary morgue in 
another village. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole village is being treated as a crime scene,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The mine blast occurred Tuesday, when civilians hit the mine  
while driving along a muddy tract of road in the zone of Kosovo 
controlled by French peacekeepers, NATO spokesman Jan Joosten said. 
The exact location wasn't immediately known. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident was ``distressing,'' Joosten said, because the area  
had been cordoned off for mines, but residents repeatedly removed 
warnings and barriers so they could use the road. 
</P>
<P>
	With ethnic Albanian refugees flooding back into the province,  
NATO peacekeepers have been struggling to get out the word about 
the danger of mines. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 27 people have been killed in at least 61 confirmed  
mine incidents in the past month, according to NATO figures. The 
United Nations said the total number of deaths and injuries from 
mines may be as high as 170. 
</P>
<P>
	About 20 percent of casualties have been KLA soldiers helping in  
demining operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Clark, arriving on a visit to review NATO forces in the  
province, held talks with KLA chief of staff Agim Ceku in Pristina. 
</P>
<P>
	He told journalists afterward that the KLA is in compliance with  
a June 21 demilitarization agreement that required them to put 
their weapons in storage and stand down from military operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, acts of retribution by ethnic Albanians against Kosovo's  
Serb minority were reported from all parts of the province. 
</P>
<P>
	Joosten said four ethnic Albanians were arrested in Kosovo's  
capital, Pristina, on Tuesday trying to evict Serbs from their 
homes. Two of the men had KLA identification cards. 
</P>
<P>
	Ethnic Albanians have been taking revenge for Serb forces'  
brutal campaign of killings and expulsions against the province's 
Albanian majority during NATO's 78-day bombing of Yugoslavia. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0341 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 10:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Portuguese Inflation Up 0.2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- Consumer prices rose 0.2 percent in June  
comared with the previous month and are up 2.3 percent for the past 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The figures reported Wednesday by the National Statistics  
Institute were in line with private forecasts. The inflation rate 
has slowed since the start of the year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0342 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 14:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Business Targets Family Leave Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal law giving employees up to 12 weeks  
of unpaid leave a year to recover from illness, care for a new 
child or nurse a sick family member is causing confusion in the 
workplace, business groups told a Senate subcommittee Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	They asked Congress to fix the 1993 family leave law before  
considering the Clinton administration's plan to expand it to cover 
more workers. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., said he suspects some  
opposition is coming from employers who would prefer not to have to 
comply the Family and Medical Leave Act. 
</P>
<P>
	``I seem to be hearing from those who are looking through  
regulatory process as a way of undoing some of the legislation we 
achieved,'' Dodd said during a hearing before the Senate Health, 
Education, Labor and Pensions Committee's panel on children and 
families. 
</P>
<P>
	Aug. 5 will mark the sixth anniversary of the law, which was  
intended to help employees balance the demands of work and family 
life. The law applies to public agencies, public schools, and 
private employers with 50 or more workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Employees must maintain health coverage for the duration of the  
leave, an average of about 10 days, said John R. Fraser, deputy 
administrator of the Labor Department's Wage and Hour Division. 
</P>
<P>
	The law has been a ``tremendous success,'' Fraser said. By Sept.  
30, the department had received only 13,600 complaints, ``an 
extremely small number given the millions of workers who have taken 
time off,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, he said, the Labor Department found no evidence of  
widespread problems or abuse, Fraser said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Edward Harold, a New Orleans lawyer who represents  
businesses in employment-related matters, said the law ``has proven 
to be a financial boon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The confusion that leads all these people to my door is not a  
product of the act itself,'' he said, but of the rules developed by 
the Labor Department, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that many of the regulations were written not to  
implement Congress's intent, but rather to expand the rights of 
employees beyond what Congress intended,'' Harold said. 
</P>
<P>
	Problems include businesses notifying employees of their rights  
by the required deadlines, getting enough information from 
employees on health problems that might qualify for the leave, and 
trying to determine what constitutes a ``serious illness,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Verdisco, president of the International Mass Retail  
Association, said in a statement that ``clarifying and resolving'' 
problems with the law would make it ``more useful and easier to 
understand and comply with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration has proposed revising the law to:  
</P>
<P>
	--Make it apply to any business with 25 or more employees. The  
law now covers only about half of the work force, Dodd said. 
</P>
<P>
	--Allow eligible employees to take an additional 24 hours of  
unpaid leave each year to participate in their children's school 
activities. 
</P>
<P>
	--Allow states to create innovative ways of using unemployment  
compensation payments to support people taking parental leave. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990714.0343 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-14 10:56:00 </DATE_TIME>
